<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Teamsters     01-17 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Teamsters,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Meets with Teamsters Leaders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Bush met Tuesday with leaders
of the International Brotherhood of Teamsters to thank the union
officials for their support in his election to the White House,
according to a Bush spokesman.
   The meeting included six Teamsters officials who are scheduled to
go on trial next month as the result of a Justice Department civil
suit accusing them of racketeering, The Washington Post reported in
its Wednesday editions.
   The brief session was held in the office of John H. Sununu,
Bush's incoming chief of staff, said Sheila Tate, a spokeswoman for
Bush. The meeting had not been publicly announced.
   ``The Teamsters people were meeting with Sununu and the
president-elect simply stopped by briefly. The purpose was to thank
them for their support during the election campaign,'' she said.
   The meeting was set up by the Bush campaign and William J.
McCarthy, president of the Teamsters, Ms. Tate said.
   The Post reported that Sununu noted the Justice Department case
against the Teamsters but said any discussion of the case would be
inappropriate in the meeting.
   Last June, the Justice Department filed suit in New York,
charging that the Teamsters were infiltrated by organized crime and
urging a federal court to put the union under government trusteeship.
   The case is scheduled to go to trial Feb. 27 and the 18
defendants include McCarthy and others in the group who met with
Bush and Sununu, the Post reported.
   In 1981 and 1985, after the election of President Reagan and Vice
President Bush, Bush had appeared at the union's board meetings
during inaugural week to thank the organization for endorsing the
Reagan-Bush ticket.
   According to the Post, the meeting Tuesday was in lieu of a
public appearance by Bush at a Teamsters' board meeting, which union
officials had sought.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
