<FIRST>u w AM-Jackson-Barry     01-17 0168</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jackson-Barry,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jackson Worried About Barry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Jesse L. Jackson has expressed concern
for District of Columbia Mayor Marion Barry's ``health and
well-being'' in recent weeks, the Washington Post said in its
Wednesday's editions.
   Jackson told the newspaper he has talked and prayed privately
with Barry and is seeking to counsel the embattled major.
   In a telephone interview Tuesday, Jackson said his involvement is
personal and not political. Jackson declined to defend or criticze
Barry, whose latest controversy involves visits to a former city
employee under a drug investigation at a downtown hotel, the Post
said.
   ``I'm in no position to make a political evaluation of the
current situation,'' the paper quoted Jackson as saying. ``My first
consideration is his health and well-being.''
   Jackson said he intends to visit with Barry this week while
Jackson is here for the presidential inauguration.
   ``I know the burden of being under attack. I have been there,''
Jackson said. ``People are hurt and their families are hurt.''
</TEXT>
