<FIRST>r a PM-Nunsearch     01-17 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nunsearch,0561</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thoroughly Modern Nuns Audition for Part in Hit Musical</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONNI EFRON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   She wore black stretch pants, a sequined vest and a
top hat. Sister Rena Foley did not look like a nun.
   Sister Brigid Riley looked the part in full Carmelite habit and
veil. But she didn't act it: She took to center stage like a veteran
performer and played snappy spoons to a bluegrass tune.
   Life imitated show business Monday as about a dozen real-life
nuns showed up at the Charles Street Playhouse to audition for the
musical ``Nunsense,'' a gentle spoof of convent life.
   Judging their performances was a panel of nun-impersonators, the
show's regular cast. The habit-wearing actresses sing, clown and
even tapdance in an off-beat comedy about nuns who stage a talent
show to raise money to bury four of their sisters who died of
botulism and are being temporarily stored in the convent freezer.
   The five real-life nuns judged most talented will each be given a
cameo role in the show for one week in February or March.
   The producers billed the audition as ``Nunsearch'' and advertised
for ``real nuns'' in Catholic and secular newspapers. They have
promised to donate $2 from every ticket sold for the special shows
to a charity chosen by the performing nun.
   ``We're constantly getting mail from nuns and priests who love
the show,'' said co-producer Ken Biller. ``We're doing it to raise
some money for charity and also of course to get publicity.''
   ``Nunsense,'' written by Dan Goggin, has played in 30 American
cities since its 1985 debut, Biller said. It's now playing in New
York and Philadelphia, is entering its third season in Boston, he
said.
   Some of the nuns who auditioned said they had dreamed of stage
careers before taking the veil.
   ``I always wanted to go to Hollywood,'' said Sister Marie
Fuhrman, 37, who works with the elderly in South Boston. ``But I
just knew I belonged in the convent.''
   ``When you get past 30, you start to say, I wish I'd done this, I
wish I'd done that,'' she said. ``Even if I don't make the part, at
least I can say I auditioned for an off-Broadway show.''
   Sister Marie, who confessed to sweaty palms, delivered a comic
monologue while her sisters and her mother superior cheered her
bravery.
   ``You see nuns on TV, they're such stereotypes of pious, holier
than thou types, and they're such stuffed shirts and prudes,'' she
said. ``We're not all that stuffy.''
   Sister Rena was a professional dancer and even owned her own
dance studio before entering the Sisters of St. Joseph convent at
age 28. Now grey-haired, she performed a jazz number to the tune of
``City Lights'' _ complete with shoulder rolls, high-kicks, and the
splits for a finale.
   Sister Brigid of the Carmelite Sisters for the Aged and Infirm in
South Boston said she decided to perform her wooden spoon routine in
hopes of attracting more young women to her order.
   ``We are getting acolytes and novitiates, but not as many as we
did,'' she said, adding that she believes that nuns' participation
in a professional musical will show young women ``we're not just
behind the walls doing our work. There is joy.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890117-0009 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 0045EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a BC-Opera     01-17 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Opera,0594</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jessye Norman, Samuel Ramey Electrify Met</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two giant talents of the opera world, soprano
Jessye Norman and bass Samuel Ramey, electrified a Metropolitan
Opera audience, many of whom usually would be happy to stay away
from one-act operas by Bartok and Schoenberg.
   On Monday night the two Americans sang Judith and Bluebeard, in
English, in a striking, theatrical new production of Bartok's
``Bluebeard's Castle.'' And Miss Norman did the entire job _ a tour
de force _ in the Met's premiere of Schoenberg's ``Erwartung,''
which can be translated ``Expectation.''
   Both Miss Norman, of Augusta, Ga., and Ramey, of Colby, Kan.,
have big voices, with beautiful, lush tone in all parts of the
register. However much vocal control, breath, volume or musicianship
is called for, they're equal to it and there's plenty more where
that came from.
   Their characterizations _ as set by Goran Jarvefelt, a native of
Bolinas, Sweden, making his Met debut _ were right on target.
   As the curtain goes up, newlyweds Bluebeard and Judith have just
arrived at Bluebeard's dark castle. As Judith asks for the key to
one door after another, she goes from a cheery, inquisitive girl to
being imperially demanding. Bluebeard goes from pride to cringing,
knowing what's coming and dreading it.
   As Judith opens doors and takes from him parts of his past,
Bluebeard takes off parts of his garb, starting with the dark
glasses that have given his white face a skeletal look, through fur
collar, coat, cloak, shirt and finally wig.
   The remarkable set is by Hans Schavernoch, a native of Gmunden,
Austria, making his Met debut. Side walls extend inward, meeting in
a V, so that one doesn't have to sit in the center to see the walls.
One wall folds back, when Bluebeard shows Judith the world. The
other wall has the doors, through which implements of torture, a
battering ram, a big pile of gold and jewels and a tall tree appear.
   When the last door opens, revealing the three wives Bluebeard
murdered, they appear as zombies who crawl forth and walk, silently.
Bluebeard puts the cloak of death on Judith and she follows them,
moving like a queen.
   Her red gown and cloak were magnificent. Lore Haas from Vienna,
who has worked extensively with Schavernoch, also was making her Met
debut.
   When ``Bluebeard's Castle'' was performed by the Met in 1974, the
concept was nothing like this. It was almost a concert.
   James Levine conducted with deliberate care. The orchestral music
contains some chilling moments.
   Miss Norman's singing was just as remarkable in ``Erwartung.''
But it's a letdown after the other opera. It's sung in German and
the plot is impenetrable. ``The Woman'' is searching for a man in a
forest. Once she finds a corpse and puts his hand on her skin to
warm it. The next time she's at that part of the stage, the corpse
is gone. Is she crazy? Did she kill him? Is she hallucinating?
   The same design team used the other opera's backdrop, plus three
autumn trees, a park bench, flowers, candles and a grand piano. The
only thing we objected to all evening was the piano and Miss Norman
running between it and the bench. ``Erwartung'' is confusing enough.
   The Feb. 1 performance will be videotaped for showing March 31 on
PBS.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890117-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 0102EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Angola     01-17 0792</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Angola,0813</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legacy of War: Cripples and Stagnation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN LINNEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUITO, Angola (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight-year-old Domingos Casela was walking
through a field to his family's small corn patch and stepped on a
mine.
   Domingos and thousands like him are maimed reminders of a civil
war neither side is able to win. The conflict has gripped Angola
since independence from Portugal in 1975, causing stagnation and
desolation in one of Africa's most richly endowed nations.
   Several months after Domingos stepped on the mine, he hobbled up
a ramp at the Kuito-Bie Rehabilitation Center with a rubber-tipped
metal rod in place of his lower left leg, undergoing physical
therapy to prepare for the artificial limb he will wear the rest of
his life.
   His doctors say the mine was planted by the National Union for
the Total Independence of Angola, or UNITA. The U.S.-supported
rebels are fighting a war of attrition against the Marxist
government of the Angolan Popular Liberation Movement, known by its
Portuguese initials MPLA.
   South Africa says it halted 13 years of aid to UNITA after
signing a U.S.-mediated accord Dec. 22 with Angola and Cuba on
withdrawal of the 50,000 Cuban troops in Angola and independence for
South-West Africa, also known as Namibia, which South Africa has
controlled since World War I.
   All South African troops in southern Angola moved back across the
border to Namibia when a truce between the two nations began Aug. 8.
   Dr. Sabino Salongue, director of the rehabilitation center in
Angola's fertile central highlands, said most of amputees being
treated were victims of mines planted by UNITA. Others lost limbs
when gangrene set in because rifle wounds were poorly tended, he
said.
   Visitors to UNITA headquarters at Jamba, in southeastern Angola
near Namibia, see amputees of the other side who stepped on mines
planted by the Cuban-supported army to impede rebel advances.
   Many victims of the war are Ovimbundu, the people of central
Huambo and Bie provinces who in 1960 were 38 percent of the 5
million living in a colony 14 times the size of Portugal.
   UNITA leader Jonas Savimbi, 54, is an Ovimbundu. His father
worked for the Caminho de Ferro de Benguela, the railway on which
agricultural products and ores from Zambia and Zaire once rolled to
the Atlantic ports of Benguela and Lobito.
   Today, the Cunje railway station four miles outside Kuito is a
mass of broken bricks and shards of blue-and-white Portuguese tiles,
target of a UNITA attack.
   Grass and wildflowers grow between the rails. Five huge steam
locomotives built by Bayer, Peacock and Co. Ltd. of Manchester,
England, rust on sidings with no place to go since UNITA blew up the
bridges between Huambo and Kuito.
   Armando Ferreira, 54 years a railroader, still shows up at the
yard each day. He said people on both sides are weary of war and
eager for the railway to run again so their corn, bananas and millet
can go to market and they can receive goods from the outside.
   An international conference is scheduled for Jan. 25-26 in
Luanda, capital of Angola, to raise funds for a 10-year development
plan in the Lobito corridor, including reconstruction of the
Benguela railway. The conference is sponsored by the Southern Africa
Development Coodination Conference and the European Economic
Commission.
   The cost of re-opening the railroad has been estimated at
$300-$600 million.
   Kieran J. O'Cuneen, the Economic Commission representative in
Angola, fears potential donor nations may balk at committing
substantial funds because the war has made it impossible to conduct
a technical study in the region.
   He and others involved in development projects feel withdrawal of
Cuban troops, which began Jan. 10 and is to be finished by mid-1991,
could lead to more economic aid and development if the civil war
also ends.
   President Jose Eduardo dos Santos says Angola will not negotiate
with UNITA and seeks diplomatic relations with the United States.
His government has declared a year-long amnesty to begin Feb. 4,
which spokesman Paulinho Pinto Joao says will be open to all
renounce violence and accept the constitution.
   President-elect George Bush has written Savimbi, however,
promising continued U.S. support until the government does negotiate
with UNITA.
   Covert U.S. military aid to the rebels was blocked for a decade
by a 1975 congressional amendment, but resumed in 1986 and is said
to total about $15 million annually.
   A Western diplomat said Washington's policy toward UNITA was
``outdated'' and the Marxism espoused by the ruling ruling party was
``only skin deep.''
   ``You'll see; this is not a Marxist nation,'' he said. ``Nearly
all their trade is with the West. When the Cubans have left, then
they'll get rid of the Russians.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
