<SECOND>PM-BRF--France-US Maneuvers,0159</SECOND>
<HEAD>France, U.S. To Conduct Joint Mediterranean Maneuvers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   France and the United States will conduct joint air
and sea maneuvers in the Mediterranean during the first half of
February, the French news agency Agence France-Presse reports.
   Quoting unidentified sources in the Defense Ministry, the news
agency said Monday that the French aircraft carriers Clemenceau and
Foch and the American carrier Theodore Roosevelt are to participate
in the exercise code-named Phinnia.
   The defense source told AFP the exercises have been planned since
April and have no connection to the Jan. 4 downing of two Libyan
MiG-23 jets by U.S. Navy planes in international waters off the
Libyan coast.
   The number of troops to take part in the exercise and the precise
date were not given, AFP said.
   Commandos from France's Rapid Action Force will also participate
in the exercises, which are designed to reinforce cooperation, the
defense official was quoted as saying.
