<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Reagan made his debut as a news
announcer for a radio station, and his dad marked the occasion with
a congratulatory phone call.
   ``Good morning, Mike. This is your old man,'' President Reagan
kiddingly told his eldest son in a call from the White House on
Monday.
   ``I'm a little far away to hear your first program but I just
wanted to congratulate you on the first day and wish you well,''
said the president, who was a radio sports announcer in Iowa in the
1930s.
   ``Well, thank you very much, dad,'' said the younger Reagan, who
was surprised and pleased by the call.
   Michael Reagan was hired by KSDO to deliver news and information
during morning rush hour. He worked for the station for a month last
summer on a temporary basis as a talk show host.
   ``The people of San Diego really liked him,'' said Mike Shields,
the station's president and general manager. ``The name Reagan has a
lot of magic in Southern California and that's because of his
father.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: A version moved on sports wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retired NBA greats Walt Hazzard, Wali Jones, Bill
Bradley and Dave DeBusschere didn't know what they were in for when
they showed at ``The Cosby Show.'' They were enlisted by Bill Cosby
for a surprise game, and then lost to a group of women.
   The women, including Olympians Nancy Lieberman and Teresa
Edwards, defeated the men 83-80 in a taping Monday of the NBC sitcom
episode scheduled to be broadcast in March.
   Hazzard and Jones were enlisted to appear as extras in a
restaurant scene but then found out they were going to play some
basketball.
   ``Just as the tape started rolling, out of the other locker room
rolls the women's team,'' said NBC publicist Mary Neagoy. ``None of
the guys except Cosby knew they were going to play women. They were
surprised.''
   ``We did a lot more passing than the women. You appreciate
passing when you get to be over 50,'' Cosby said later.
   Lieberman was on the '84 Olympic team and Edwards won the gold in
'88. Also on the women's team were Rhonda Rompola, assistant women's
basketball coach at Southern Methodist University; college player
Anucha Sanders and Stephanie Givens, actress Robin Givens' sister.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Ben Nighthorse Campbell, D-Colo., went ``back
to the blanket'' last weekend, an Indian phrase for returning to
tribal settings.
   Campbell, who has been making Indian jewelry since he was 12, was
the featured artist at the Colorado Indian Market.
   Wearing Western attire and a white cowboy hat with beaded
hatband, Campbell talked to passers-by about art and politics. He
markets his art under the name Ben Nighthorse.
   Born to a Portuguese mother and a Cheyenne father, Campbell is
the only American Indian in Congress.
   He turns out 130 to 150 pieces of jewelry each year, most of them
small rings and earrings, from a small workshop in his Washington
apartment.
