<TEXT>
   A Royal Navy mine sweeper once commanded by Prince
Charles is being converted into a floating museum.
   The 420-ton Bronington has been sold to a business consortium
that intends to maintain the vessel as a museum portraying life
aboard a mine sweeper, said Defense Ministry official Tim Sainsbury.
   The ship will be moored in Manchester, he told Parliament on
Monday.
   Charles, 40, who commanded the ship in 1976, sometimes suffered
seasickness as a result of the ship's tendency to roll heavily.
   According to news reports at the time, Charles was forced to use
a bucket during a particularly heavy swell, then offered it to
another pallid-faced officer, saying, ``Would you care to use the
royal bucket?''
