<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 0222EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-TexasConnection     01-17 0611</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Texas Connection,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Presidency Brings New Wave Of Texans To Washington</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush is bringing a tidal wave of Texans
with him to the capital city, and they promise to make their way of
doing things felt on the social as well as political scene.
   In addition to a Texas president _ albeit a transplanted Yankee _
a Texas speaker of the House, appointees from defense
secretary-designate to FBI director, and four committee chairmen in
Congress, Washington will have to reckon with their families.
   ``Batten down the hatches,'' warns The Washington Post on
Sunday's front page. ``Nervy, sexy, filthy rich Georgette Mosbacher,
wife of the incoming commerce secretary and a certified social
cyclone, is headed our way.''
   But Mrs. Mosbacher, wife of Houston oilman Robert Mosbacher,
isn't the only sign that Texas has arrived.
   ``You'll see more boots than you've seen. You'll see more hats
than you've seen,'' says Texas Republican Sen. Phil Gramm. ``And if
the emergence of Texans into positions of power brings good Mexican
food to the capital, the achievement will be miraculous.''
   ``The quality of the barbecue is going to pick up, the quality of
the Mexican food is going to pick up,'' says Rep. Charlie Stenholm,
a Democrat and Texas farmer. ``The social scene is going to pick up
and we'll have a little high culture; the cotton-eyed Joe and the
two-step are going to be right at the top of the list.''
   A.C. Greene, director of the Center for Texas Studies at the
University of North Texas in Denton, that despite the influx, the
days of the wheeler-dealer, swashbuckling Texas politicans are gone.
   Greene says he's not convinced Bush and his coterie of
nationalized Texans will wield the same sort of behind-the-scenes
clout as Lyndon B. Johnson did as Senate majority leader, vice
president and president; as Sam Rayburn did when he was House
Speaker; and John Nance Garner did as Frankin D. Roosevelt's vice
president.
   If any Texan has real connections, Greene says it's House Speaker
Jim Wright of Fort Worth, who has ``has fought those battles in the
corridors of power,'' and may actually be more influential in
Washington than Bush, at least for now.
   LBJ's inaugural chairman 24 years ago, Dale Miller, isn't
expecting any Texas invasion at all, he says, because the state has
always had a presence in Washington in the 47 years he's been in
here.
   ``There's always been a pronounced Texas influence here in
town,'' Miller says. ``I've known a very strong Texas influence in
Washington for 47 years.''
   But others are expecting a flock of Texans who will leave a
Texas-size style imprint on the government.
   ``Texans are really going to be here in a big way. Texas will
have a big part to play,'' says veteran journalist Sarah McClendon,
who predicts less ``gobbledygook'' in government publications
because of the Texas preference for simple and direct language.
   Gramm says he thinks the four Cabinet appointments and other
high-profile jobs already awarded to Texans are just the tip of the
iceberg. ``There will be literally hundreds of Texans in
decision-making positions. People tend to hire people they know and
people they trust.''
   But Greene says: ``A lot of these are cosmetic positions,
especially the appointed positions. Bush doesn't have the
connections LBJ did, and there is just no substitute for on-the-Hill
politics in Washington.''
   Still, Gramm says it's a ``plus for Texas and America.''
   ``I know all of these Texans care about our state and those who
are not Texans know the guy at the top cares about Texas and that's
obviously going to help,'' Gramm says.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
