<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 0208EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     01-17 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Surges In Japan; Stocks Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar surged against the Japanese yen Tuesday,
while investors reacted to the weaker yen by pushing share prices
lower on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar eased in the afternoon to close at 127.70 yen, up 1.05
yen from Friday's close of 126.65 yen, after opening at 127.93 yen
and surging to peak at 128.15 yen in early morning trading.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues dipped 70.86 points, or 0.23 percent, to close at
31,227.52.
   Finance Minister Tatsuo Murayama attributed the dollar's strength
to the difference in key interest rates between Japan and the United
States, and to reported statements by West German monetary
authorities that the dollar's current level is acceptable.
   Murayama said the Bank of Japan will not intervene to stem the
dollar's rise because ``the situation does not require imediate
countermeasures.''
   Currency traders said the dollar's remarkable strength against
the yen followed the U.S. currency's bullish advance in overseas
markets overnight. The dollar closed Monday in London at 128.05 yen
and in New York at 128.10 yen.
   Traders said the dollar also was strong because of reduced
chances for central bank intervention in the United States and Japan
due to national holidays.
   Many U.S. traders were absent from the market Monday in
observance of Rev. Martin Luther King's birthday, while Japanese
banks and government offices were also closed Monday in observance
of the Coming of Age Day.
   ``There were strong demands for buying the dollar, but traders'
fear over intervention prevented such a move,'' said a dealer at a
major commercial bank, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``Then
when they were freed from such a fear, they all went out to buy the
dollar.''
   But the traders added that the dollar's gain is unlikely to
continue ahead of U.S. trade reports due Wednesday in Washington.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, dealers said the dollar's steep gain
sidelined many investors.
   ``The market seems to be taking a break (Tuesday) because of
unstable currency rates,'' said a dealer at a major brokerage house
in Tokyo. ``But the underflow of the market is still bullish.''
</TEXT>
