<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 0308EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-IndianLand     01-17 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Indian Land,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shoshone Set Back In Land Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM GARDNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Western Shoshone Indians have vowed to
press their claim to full grazing rights on a half-million acres of
land despite an appeals court ruling limiting the number of horses
and cows they can have.
   ``This isn't the end to litigation. We don't consider this issue
resolved,'' said Thomas E. Leubben, attorney for the Western
Shoshone National Council. ``Only Congress can resolve the Western
Shoshone land issue.''
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals on Wednesday reversed U.S.
District Judge Bruce Thompson's September 1986 order that gave
sisters Mary and Carrie Dann, members of the Shoshone tribe, the
right to graze cattle and horses at their 180-acre ranch in
north-central Nevada's Crescent Valley.
   Thompson had ruled the Danns had aboriginal and treaty rights to
graze their livestock on 530,000 acres without being regulated by
federal agencies or paying grazing fees.
   The appellate ruling limits the Danns to grazing 26 cows and 79
horses, the number their parents had on the land when the 1934
Taylor Grazing Act took effect. The sisters currently have 768 cows
and 850 horses.
   A tearful Carrie Dann said at a news conference Monday she has no
plans to reduce the herd.
   ``I'm not really afraid of going to jail because I believe I'm
right,'' she said.
   The U.S. government sued the Danns for trespassing in 1974 to
prevent them from using the land for grazing. The 14-year-old case
has been argued three times in federal court in Reno, twice in the
appeals court and once before the U.S. Supreme Court.
   The sisters claim that an 1863 treaty with the United States
gives them the right to use the land for grazing.
   The government contends that the Western Shoshone lost its
ancestral land in 1979 when the Indian Claims Commission awarded the
tribe $26 million for the acreage. The Indians have refused to
accept the money.
   ``This land was never given by the United States to us. It is the
Creator's land,'' Carrie Dann said Monday.
   ``The Creator put us on this land,'' she said. We were not placed
here by the United States government. Our livelihood is tied to this
land. They wanted to do away with our livelihood. They're trying to
destroy our beliefs, our culture.''
   Luebben, of Albuquerque, N.M., said he would continue to argue
the case in federal court, but added he would try other avenues.
   ``Considering this decision by the 9th Circuit Court of Appeals,
the Shoshone people are going to have to appeal to the public and to
Congress,'' Luebben said.
   ``We consider this decision to be wrong and extremely unjust,''
he said. ``There is still institutional racism in the United
States.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890117-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 0301EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-NewVietnam 1stLd-Writethru a0415 01-17 0614</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-New Vietnam, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0415,0627</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Vets Visit Minefield They Sowed In Vietnam</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with new material. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   For a group of former U.S. Marines, a return
visit to Vietnam touched off memories of their tense first trip to
the war zone more than 20 years ago and also opened up sights they
had never seen before. AP Special Correspondent George Esper, on his
second reporting trip to Vietnam since the war ended, accompanied
them and filed this report:
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE ESPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GIO LINH, Vietnam (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five former U.S. Marines stood at what
was their military base two decades ago. Surrounded by unexploded
shells, they unfurled the stars and stripes and prayed and wept for
their fallen comrades.
   While Mike Wallace, a 41-year-old farmer from Langdon, Kansas,
prayed for help to ``deal with the memories, the pain and the
loneliness,'' poor women and children with hoes hacked away at the
reddish dirt, trying to uncover the casings of shells for scrap
metal.
   They said that two weeks ago an old man was killed when an
uncovered shell exploded, and that such shells had killed many
others, including children.
   A Vietnamese captain, Hoang Van Thanh, stood with the Americans
at the ceremony just south of what was once the Demilitarized Zone
that divided Vietnam at the 17th parallel. He verified that mines
and other unexploded artillery and mortar shells were still killing
and wounding civilians.
   The former U.S. Marines had suspected that civilians were still
being killed and wounded by unexploded shells and land mines that
their engineer battalion, the 11th Marines, planted to protect a
string of U.S. bases just below the DMZ in the late 1960s.
   The men, who came back to check claims by Vietnamese officials
that all of the mines had been cleared, were shocked to see the
children picking at the shellings at the former U.S. artillery base
at Gio Linh.
   ``I feel outrage,'' said Nate Genna, a 41-year-old maintenance
worker from Boston as he looked out over the children. ``This whole
place should be quarantined, fenced up; only professional people,
not children. Look at them.''
   Wallace said: ``My legs are walking but my mind is not wanting to
do this because for so long I spent time in this place watching
people get killed.''
   ``It's peaceful, but I'm real nervous,'' he said. ``I've got to
admit I could hardly get out of the van to come up here. I'm scared
to death, the time I was here we was under attack and that's the
only memories I have of here.
   ``Even though it's in peace, its still looks awfully threatening
to me.''
   In the salute to the dead, Gene Spanos, a 39-year-old police
lieutenant from Rosemont, Ill., said, ``On behalf of the men that
lost their lives and women in Vietnam during the conflict, we
present this small ceremony, some token of appreciation in the lives
that they gave. For those who did not return, eternal rest. For
those who did return, gratitude and peace.''
   Everywhere the former marines went, they were greeted warmly as
they retraced their steps northward along Highway 1 where they once
swept the road for land mines.
   Children followed them along the route and the Americans stopped
to snap photos.
   ``This is the first time I've felt we're performing our mission
since I've been here,'' said William Johnson, 41, of Manchester,
Conn. ``This is for the people.''
   ``This is where it all began,'' said fireman Frank Noe, 40, from
Stoughton, Mass. ``This is where we grew up. This is where we became
men 20 years ago.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
