<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 0313EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MinorityEducation     01-17 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Minority Education,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>Education Secretary, NEA President Urge Excellence for Minorities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE EMBRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Secretary of Education Lauro F.
Cavazos said minority students are getting an inferior education
because of a lack of minority teachers.
   Cavazos on Monday called the shortage a matter of ``true
urgency,'' pointing out that 30 percent of the nation's students are
minorities, while only 13 percent of the educators are.
   ``Today, the person that takes roll ... and assigns work ... is
usually an Anglo teacher, doing the best he can do,'' Cavazos said
in the keynote address to the National Conference on Recruitment and
Retention of Minority Students. ``In the eyes of some minority
students, knowledge and education are equated with whites, and
perhaps ... minority students believe education belongs to one group
or another,'' he said.
   National Education Association President Mary Hatwood Futrell
said earlier Monday that the minority student population is expected
to increase in the 1990s as the number of minority teachers in
public schools drops to 3 percent.
   Futrell said a shortage of minority teachers will threaten the
system because it deprives minority students of positive role models
and ``creates an educational deficit'' for whites because it gives
``them a distorted view of the world ... and valuable contact with
teachers who offer dramatic proof that adversity can be overcome and
that the American dream is not a myth.''
   Cavazos said more minority teachers must be recruited, and that
recruitment must begin in elementary schools by encouraging
minorities in academia.
   He also said parents should work with and encourage their
children during the pre-school years.
   ``If we educators made it a top priority to enlist the aid of
parents, think what a difference it would make,'' he said. ``We must
help all parents create a home environment that supports achievement
and learning. Too often in low-income homes, education is
undervalued.''
   Futrell noted an anthropological study that found students at a
predominantly black Washington, D.C., high school were limiting
their academic success ``so their peers won't think they are acting
white.''
   The teachers union president said educators ``have to do
something to ensure that our children don't think this way,'' and
said schools should ``develop courses and programs aimed at helping
build self-esteem.''
   Futrell said students must be told, ``It's OK to be smart, to use
your abilities and excel.''
</TEXT>
