<FIRST>r i PM-UN-Namibia     01-17 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UN-Namibia,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Security Council Agrees to Smaller Namibian Peacekeeping Force</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a cost-cutting move, the Security
Council has directed that a fewer peacekeepers than originally
planned should monitor South-West Africa's independence from South
Africa.
   The council, in unanimously approving the peacekeeping force on
Monday, asked Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar to identify
``possible tangible cost-saving measures'' to the mission.
   ``There's going to be a considerable reduction in money,'' Gen.
Vernon A. Walters, the U.S. ambassador, told reporters after the
vote. He said helicopters and sensors can monitor an area better
that ``soldiers just standing shoulder-to-shoulder on the ground.''
   Black-ruled nations of southern Africa had lobbied to deploy the
7,500 peacekeepers, at least 360 military police and 2,000 civilian
administrators under U.N. auspices _ at a cost of about $800 million
a year.
   But the council's five permanent members _ the United States,
Soviet Union, China, Britain and France _ want to hold the cost to
between $400 million and $500 million, diplomats said on condition
of anonymity.
   The council must now determine the strength of peacekeeping
forces and cost of their deployment under the U.N. plan whereby the
territory also known as Namibia will become independent after
elections in November.
   In its resolution, the council asked Perez de Cuellar to prepare
a report estimating the size and needs of the U.N. Transition
Assistance Group.
   When the report is ready, probably in about two weeks, the
council will vote on formally creating the force.
   Namibia is to gain independence under peace accords signed Dec.
22 by Angola, Cuba and South Africa that also stipulate that 50,000
Cuban troops in neighboring Angola will leave by July 1991.
   Washington has suggested cutting the Namibian peacekeeping force
from 7,500 to 3,200 because fighting has stopped between South
African forces of the South-West Africa People's Organization.
   South Africa captured Namibia from Germany in World War I, and
the League of Nations gave it a mandate for the mineral-rich
territory. The U.N. General Assembly revoked the mandate in 1966 but
South Africa refused to leave.
</TEXT>
