<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 0514EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Overtown-Scene     01-17 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Overtown-Scene,0623</SECOND>
<HEAD>In The Heart Of Overtown: A Smoldering Rage</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhotos</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Overtown Disturbance, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   When Miami's Overtown neighborhood erupted in
flames Monday night, city leaders immediately attempted to calm
fears by talking to angry residents. City Commissioner Rosario
Kennedy was escorted on a tour behind the roadblocks by two police
officers and accompanied by Associated Press newsman Will Lester.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By WILL LESTER</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rosario Kennedy was looking for a better
understanding of the black rage that descended upon Miami on the day
that honors the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.
   The Cuban-born city commissioner found her answers early today on
a dark corner of 20th St. and NW 3rd Ave., in the heart of Overtown.
   Miami Guy's Auto Parts had burned to a shell. A torched car was
turned on its side.
   The riot started after by a motorcyclist's death Monday night. At
least two officers were pursuing the motorcycle for an alleged
traffic violation. One of the officers fired a shot, the motorcycle
crashed into a moving car, killing the cycle's 21-year-old driver,
police said. Police refused to say whether he was hit by the bullet.
   Wary police in riot gear kept automatic rifles poised,
occasionally dropping the barrel toward any rapid movement.
   On the corner was a group of about 15 young black men: angry,
nervous _ watching every police move.
   The 43-year-old Mrs. Kennedy, just over 5 feet tall in her pumps
and wearing a bright red pants and top, walked over.
   What caused this to happen? she asked.
   ``How can a person shoot a guy riding a motorcycle?'' replied one
man, who would not identify himself. ``Do something about the ones
that got the guns.''
   As his voice rose, the others lost their shyness. The crowd began
to grow.
   A young shirtless teen-ager stepped forward.
   ``The blacks have been here since I don't know when,'' he said.
``But 10,000 Cubans a year ... they get jobs just like that. And now
the Nicaraguans ... ''
   Miami officials have been providing shelter at a stadium for
about 250 Nicaraguans seeking political asylum.
   A stone clattered to the pavement and several police rifles
leveled at the crowd.
   ``Don't you murder him,'' came a cry from another teen. ``We're
coming to your homes if there's another murder.''
   As the anger grew, police quietly urged Mrs. Kennedy into a
waiting car.
   During the ride through the streets of Overtown with two officers
and a reporter, Mrs. Kennedy got the scare of the night when her car
approached a group of heavily armed policeman.
   The police dropped behind the car doors and leveled pistols
directly at Mrs. Kennedy and the driver, Officer Raymond Carvil.
   Carvil placed the blue police light on the dash and the pistols
dropped.
   Gunfire crackled in the early morning hours amid the housing
projects, and officers shouted reports of ``Molotov cocktails.'' One
Latin man living in a project with his wife was reportedly beaten on
his front porch, officers said.
   Mrs. Kennedy and other city leaders had hoped this week's Super
Bowl would polish up the image of Miami, a one-time tropical
paradise, tarnished by race riots in 1980 and 1982, the flood of
refugees from Cuba in 1980 and the Colombian drug wars throughout
the decade. But she admitted the opportunity was fast slipping away.
   ``It's extremely unfortunate that it's happening now,'' she said.
   And she found more anger than she'd expected.
   ``I was surprised by the depth of anger,'' she said. ``We'll be
talking to community leaders later today.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
