<FIRST>r a PM-King'sLegacy     01-17 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-King's Legacy,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blacks Gain Majority In County Government At Voting Rights Site</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-King Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENDAL WEAVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SELMA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Martin Luther King Jr.'s battles for voting
rights were remembered as the first black county commissioners
elected in 112 years were sworn in by Alabama's first black federal
judge.
   ``We bring home to Dallas County the harvest of the Martin Luther
King voting rights act,'' said U.S. District Judge U.W. Clemon, who
administered the oath of office Monday to the three blacks and two
whites in the county's new government.
   The election of the first blacks to the Dallas County Commission
since Reconstruction followed 10 years of legal combat that
abolished the old at-large election system which had kept the panel
all white for more than a century.
   Under the new election plan, commissioners are elected from five
districts, three with large or nominal black voting majorities.
Dallas County, with a population of 55,000, is about 56 percent
black.
   The three black commissioners _ Erskine Minor, D.L. Pope and
Perry Varner _ were sworn in along with white commissioners Deans
Barber and Doug Morrow at a courthouse ceremony in which the
overflow crowd of about 300 sang ``The Battle Hymn of the Republic.''
   The ceremony coincided with Alabama's state holiday for both
Confederate Gen. Robert E. Lee and King, who led the 1965
Selma-to-Montgomery voting rights march. The march took place with
federal protection after a band of marchers were beaten and routed
by mounted state troopers on the Edmund Pettus Bridge, which crosses
the Alabama River at Selma.
   ``Bloody Sunday,'' as the bridge violence became known, drew
national attention to the next march led by King, which helped
inspire passage of the 1965 federal Voting Rights Act.
   ``I suspect there is no place on this planet that is more
identified with Dr. King and his quest for American justice than
right here in Selma, Alabama,'' James P. Turner said after Monday's
ceremony a few blocks from the bridge.
   Turner investigated violence against voting rights marchers in
1965 and is acting head of the Justice Department's civil rights
division for the Reagan administration. He and a team of Justice
Department lawyers helped win the election system change in Selma.
   ``I predict that someday students of modern history will point to
Selma, Alabama, as 20th century America's cradle of democracy, where
people of all races began to live Doctor King's dream of
brotherhood,'' Turner said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
