<FIRST>u i PM-Britain-Bombings 1stLd-Writethru a0472 01-17 0702</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Bombings, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0472,0715</SECOND>
<HEAD>Case Of Four Jailed For IRA Pub Bombings Sent To Court Of Appeal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: LEADS with seven grafs to CORRECT Richardson's age to 31,
break up paragraphs, correct to four number sentenced. Picks up 7th pvs,
`In a ...' ^By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Citing new evidence, the government has reopened
the case of four people jailed for life in two 1974 bombings of
British pubs that killed seven people, including three soldiers, and
injured 91.
   The bombings occurred during a wave of IRA terrorism, and
champions of the ``Guildford Four'' said the government had in its
zeal to obtain convictions ignored evidence that pointed to other
suspects.
   The Irish government welcomed Monday's decision, and The Times of
London said in an editorial today that it was ``as difficult as it
was wise.''
   Responding to pressure that made the case a cause celebre in
Britain and Ireland, Home Secretary Douglas Hurd told Parliament
Monday that new information had emerged meriting that the case be
heard by the Court of Appeal.
   Carole Richardson, 31; Patrick Armstrong, 36; Paul Hill, 34, and
Gerry Conlon, 33, were convicted of planting bombs in two pubs
frequented by British soldiers in Guildford, a town southwest of
London, in October 1974. Five people, including two soldiers, were
killed and 65 injured.
   Armstrong and Hill also were convicted of a pub bombing in the
London suburb of Woolwich a month later in which the bartender and a
soldier died and 26 people were injured.
   All four were sentenced to life imprisonment in October 1975, and
two years later a court rejected their appeal.
   In a written reply to a lawmaker's question, Hurd said he was
satisfied that ``there are new and substantial points which clearly
... are best considered by the court.''
   These, he said, included apparent alibis for Hill and Miss
Richardson that had never been put to a court, and indications that
Miss Richardson was injected with drugs during her interrogation and
suffering symptoms of withdrawal from barbiturates.
   ``The possible effects of these drugs on the reliability of her
statements were not adequately exposed to the jury or the Court of
Appeal,'' Hurd said.
   However, Hurd declined to act on a point of law raised by two
senior British judges who have argued that the appeals court ruled
against the four despite being aware of confessions by two Irish
Republican Army men to the bombings.
   The Irish government, in a statement, said it ``has consistently
conveyed the serious concern about the Guildford Four case to the
British authorities.'' Grant McKee, co-author of ``Time Bomb,'' a
recent book on the case, said: ``We are very gratified that this is
the first official recognition of the justifiable concern about this
case which has attracted people of the eminence of two archbishops,
two Law Lords and two former Home Secretaries.''
   The archbishops are Archbishop of Canterbury Robert Runcie,
spiritual head of the Church of England, and Archbishop of
Westminster Cardinal Basil Hume, leader of Roman Catholics in
England and Wales. The Law Lords, two of Britain's most senior
judges, are Lord Devlin and Lord Scarman. The two former Home
Secretaries are Merlyn Rees and Lord Jenkins.
   Cardinal Tomas O Fiaich, the Roman Catholic Primate of All
Ireland, called Monday's move a ``culmination of the efforts of
people in Britain and Ireland who have become convinced of the
innocence of these people.''
   It is the second time in two years that the government has
reopened a case involving people convicted of IRA terrorism who
claimed to be victims of a miscarriage of justice.
   Six Irishmen serving life terms for pub bombings in Birmingham in
1974 that killed 21 people went before the Court of Appeal after a
similar campaign but their convictions were upheld last year.
   Like the Birmingham Six, the Guildford Four have figured strongly
in Anglo-Irish relations. They are held up as examples by those who
claim British courts are biased against the Irish or those who
sympathize with the IRA.
   The mainly Catholic IRA is fighting to end British rule in
Protestant-dominated Northern Ireland and unite it with the 95
percent Catholic Republic of Ireland under socialist rule.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890117-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 0537EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-StateRadio     01-17 0204</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-State Radio,0208</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Trying To Break Into The Broadcast Business</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFORT, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voice of America it won't be, but a state
official is hoping to start a little ``Voice of Kentucky'' of sorts.
   And little it will be if Paul Warnecke starts broadcasting
governmental proceedings on 10 watts of power. That's roughly a
five-mile radius from the transmitter.
   Warnecke, director of the Division of Telecommunications, wants
the AM station to promote tourism in Frankfort.
   No disc jockeys have been chosen, and no decision has been made
about whether Gov. Wallace Wilkinson will figure in the programming.
However, a contract to build the transmitter will be put to bid
later this month, and whoever gets the contract will have to apply
for a licence from the Federal Communications Commission on behalf
of the state.
   Vicky Dennis of the Tourism Cabinet said programming likely would
include publicity about attractions in Frankfort and Franklin County.
   Motorists would be alerted to the broadcast by signs along the
highway, Dennis said. It's hoped the message would lure drivers into
the capital city.
   The small coverage area would be similar to the low-power
broadcasts that some major airports use to keep travelers aware of
traffic conditions.
</TEXT>
