<FIRST>r i PM-China-Apology     01-17 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Apology,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Minister Apologizes for Giving Out Bonuses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of China's Water Resources Ministry has
apologized for handing out holiday bonuses in defiance of a
government call for public frugality, the government news agency
said today.
   Xinhua reported that Minister Yang Zhenhuai acknowledged he
indiscriminately used state funds by giving each ministry employee
$12.40 _ about half the average monthly wage _ to help celebrate
National Day on Oct. 1.
   ``I myself take responsiblity for the mistake,'' he said, adding
that his predecessors had always encouraged plain living and hard
work but he had failed to carry out this tradition.
   His comments came after the State Council, China's cabinet,
listed the ministry among government offices that ignored an order
to cut spending by 20 percent by giving holiday bonuses.
   China's leaders have called on government offices to take the
lead in an austerity program designed to reduce nearly 20 percent
inflation.
   Xinhua said the Auditing Administration has warned staff members
that indiscriminate distribution of cash and goods will be dealt
with severely.
   Next month is the Lunar New Year or Spring Festival, China's
biggest holiday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
