<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 0539EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-HumanRights     01-17 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Human Rights,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reagan Administration Human Rights Policies Criticized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two human rights organizations have chastised the
Reagan administration for providing military and financial
assistance to military groups with poor human rights records.
   In particular, the organizations cited aid to the Contra rebels
in Nicaragua, the UNITA insurgency in Angola, and the national
armies of El Salvador, Guatemala, the Philippines, and the Sudan.
   The criticism was detailed in a report, ``The Reagan
Administration's Record on Human Rights in 1988,'' issued Monday by
the Lawyers Committee for Human Rights and Human Rights Watch, a
New-York based organization that monitors and promotes human rights
worldwide.
   The two groups praised the Reagan administration for placing a
greater emphasis on human rights during the last few years than it
had earlier.
   The report noted the administration's insistence that human
rights occupy a prominent place in the U.S.-Soviet agenda, which it
said has led to improvements in human rights in the Soviet Union,
including the release of hundreds of political and religious
prisoners.
   While the report acknowledged that Soviet leader Mikhail
Gorbachev was also responsible for these changes, the Reagan
administration was credited with taking ``advantage of the Gorbachev
opening'' by placing ``consistent pressure on human rights issues.''
   But the report chastised the Reagan administration for largely
disregarding ``rights transgressions in a host of friendly countries
which attract little public attention in the United States, such as
Kenya, Somalia and the Sudan in Africa; Indonesia, Nepal, Pakistan
and Sri Lanka in Asia; and Jordan, Morocco and Saudi Arabia in the
Middle East.''
   According to the report, ``human rights violations often were
overlooked out of fear that criticizing an ally, particularly allied
militaries fighting leftist rebellions, would create an opportunity
for communist influence.''
   For example, it said the United States was ``a vocal apologist
for gross abuses'' in Turkey because the country is seen as a
front-line state against the Soviet army.
   The report said the administration's ``most conspicuous failing''
was that it ``rarely protested abuses committed by the military once
a civilian occupied a presidential palace ... Moreover, in certain
cases, such as El Salvador, Guatemala, Honduras and occasionally the
Philippines, the administration minimized abuses or denied that they
were taking place.''
   The administration also was attacked for refraining from
criticizing human rights violations by Israel against Palestinians
in occupied territories.
   But the report praised the administration for providing
``pressure at key moments to nudge certain dictators and military
juntas allied with the United States towards elections, as well as
to protect newly elected civilian governments against military
coups.''
   For example, the report stated that in El Salvador, Guatemala,
the Philippines and South Korea, the administration played a role in
``easing out dictators and military juntas and replacing them with
elected heads of state.'' It also praised U.S. action in Haiti,
Paraguay and Chile.
   In Argentina, Bolivia, El Salvador and the Philippines, the
report gave the Reagan administration credit for weighing ``in at
key moments when restive militaries threatened to overwhelm newly
elected civilian presidents.''
   The report called on the incoming Bush administration ``to report
human rights violations accurately and to speak out against serious
abuses wherever they are found.''
   Human Rights Watch includes the organizations Americas Watch,
Asia Watch and Helsinki Watch. The Lawyers Committee is a public
interest law center working to promote international human rights
law and legal procedures in the United States and abroad.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
