<FIRST>r a PM-BoysArrested     01-17 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boys Arrested,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Seeking Adult Who Hired Kids to Sell Drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WYANDANCH, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police are looking for an adult who may
have been behind an alleged drug-selling venture by two boys, ages
10 and 14, who were arrested with $226 cash and three vials of crack
in their pockets.
   The youngsters were charged Sunday with possession of a
controlled substance, but the charges were reduced to juvenile
delinquency because of their ages. They were to appear in Suffolk
County Family Court today.
   The boys told police they had been working with an adult. They
both had family court warrants against them on non-drug related
juvenile delinquency charges.
   ``It's a crying shame,'' said Suffolk County Police Lt. John
Lynagh. ``These dealers are using whatever means they have to sell
crack.''
   The youngsters were nabbed in a popular drug-selling location in
this city on New York's Long Island where police periodically swoop
in and arrest drug dealers, Lynagh said Monday.
   ``I was shocked ... When I saw them, I could not believe how old
they were,'' said Suffolk County Police Patrolman John Castorf.
   Lynagh said police want to question the adult for whom the youths
said they were working. The adult is apparently known to police but
they declined to identify him.
   Three weeks ago, Lynagh said, another 10-year-old boy was
arrested for selling drugs in the same area. In that case, an adult
who had hired the youngster was later arrested, he said.
   ``These people believe we will not arrest the children, so they
have them make the deals, '' Lynagh said. ``The kids are told to run
when they see a cop.''
</TEXT>
