<FIRST>u i PM-BorderDispute 1stLd-Writethru a0420 01-17 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Border Dispute, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0420,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede CAIRO</HEAD>
<HEAD>Egypt and Israel To Meet On Disputed Border Resort</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout with details from Israel. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel will try to ensure free access to the
resort of Taba for Israeli vacationers when it opens talks with
Egypt later this week on the disputed border area, Foreign Minister
Moshe Arens said.
   Taba, a 250-acre strip of land at the northern tip of the Red
Sea, has troubled Egyptian-Israeli relations since Israel refused to
give back the land when it completed its withdrawal from the Sinai
Desert in 1982.
   Israel's Cabinet decided Monday that the government will not set
any preconditions for the negotiations, which open Thursday in Taba
and will involve Israeli, Egyptian and U.S. delegations.
   Israel occupied Taba and the Sinai Desert in the 1967 Middle East
war and returned the desert to Egypt in accordance with the 1979
U.S.-mediated peace treaty.
   The Taba dispute went to international arbitration. Last Sept.
29, a five-member panel met in Geneva and awarded Egypt some
disputed key border points, but said it was not authorized to
determine the final demarcation line.
   The debate now hinges on the sovereignity over the actual beach
area, which has an Israeli-owned hotel and a cabana.
   At the Cabinet meeting, right-wing Trade Minister Ariel Sharon
insisted on linking the Taba negotiations with full normalization of
ties between the two countries. The Cabinet rejected the idea.
   Arens expressed hope the Cabinet decision would pave the way for
improved ties: ``We have paid the price for peace and now we want to
ensure the improvement of relations.
   ``We hope to create conditions for the continuing presence of
Israelis in the area ... and to solve the problem of compensation by
Egypt to the owners of the hotel,'' he said on Israel army radio.
``We hope the Egyptians are interested in developing the ties, in
turning Taba into an example of coexistence.''
   The radio said Israeli negotiators were instructed to seek free
access to Taba for vacationing Israelis and common management of the
Sonesta hotel there.
</TEXT>
