<FIRST>r a PM-BoatFire     01-17 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boat Fire,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>Men Jump Ship When Boat Catches Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORRO BAY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three men spent 1{ hours in the chilly
Pacific Ocean when an electrical fire on their yacht forced them to
jump overboard, the Coast Guard said today.
   The 37-foot Crusader Rabbit was reported on fire Monday night off
the coast several miles north of Morro Bay, about 140 miles south of
Monterey, officials said.
   The boat's owner and two passengers tried to put out the fire but
were forced to put on their life jackets and jump into the 55-degree
water, said Coast Guard Petty Officer David Mullaly in Monterey. No
one else was on board.
   The three were unable to radio for help, but other boats saw the
flames and alerted the Coast Guard, which sent a helicopter to
rescue them, Mullaly said.
   All three, suffering from hypothermia, were taken to Twin Cities
Hospital in Paso Robles, about 15 miles east of Morro Bay.
   The boat's owner, Edward Tremper, whose age was not released, was
in serious but stable condition in the intensive care unit, said
nursing supervisor, Kathy Long. He was believed to be in his 70s,
she said.
   The two others, Gerald Lahr and Robert Long, were in stable
condition and were to be released this morning, Ms. Long said.
</TEXT>
