<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 0746EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Afghanistan     01-17 0588</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan,0615</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Hand Out Rations As Food and Fuel Crises Worsen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government soldiers today pushed back
with clubs and tree branches a crowd that thronged Soviet troops as
they doled out emergency fuel rations in an impoverished section of
Kabul.
   Less than a month before the scheduled Red Army withdrawal, the
besieged capital is plagued by severe food and fuel shortages.
   One woman was knocked to the ground as the crowd, ignoring
repeated shouts from megaphone-toting Soviet soldiers to back away,
surged around the three armored personnel vehicles distributing fuel
in the Khairkhana section.
   People banged on empty gasoline cans as the Afghan soldiers
shoved back the crowd. One soldier, a rifle under his arm, kicked
and punched several teen-agers.
   Soviet troops, five aboard each armored car, looked uncomfortable
as they poured gasoline for home heating into cans held up by people
who waited in 19-degree temperatures at the front of the line.
   ``My children are cold, I've never seen conditions so bad,'' said
one woman, who gave her name as Aziza, a 35-year-old with nine
children.
   Another woman wailed as she held out her hands to a reporter and
_ speaking through an interpreter _ pleaded for help, saying she and
her children were hungry.
   Asked if she thought the reporter was a Soviet, she said, ``All I
know is you are foreigners, perhaps you can help us.''
   The Soviet unit used the megaphones to spread word of the
emergency distribution as the armored vehicles, with 75mm cannons
pointing skyward, rolled into Khairkhana. In other parts of the
city, lines of several hundred cars and buses snaked around entire
blocks waiting for fuel.
   Children joined bread lines outside shacks owned by private bread
sellers, who get their dwindling wheat supplies from a state-run
wheat silo. Western aid officials expressed growing alarm at the
shortages.
   They are blamed on increasing disruption of Soviet-escorted
supply convoys by anti-Marxist Moslem guerrillas attacking the key
Salang highway, which runs north from Kabul to the Soviet border.
   First signs of the latest shortages came after more Soviet troops
pulled out early this month, Western diplomats reported.
   The situation appears to have worsened considerably this week.
   Diplomats say Soviet troops are pulling out of the capital ahead
of the Feb. 15 deadline set in a U.N.-mediated agreement. The
withdrawal comes nearly a decade after Moscow intervened to prop up
a Marxist government.
   Under the agreement, 50,000 Soviet troops left by Aug. 15.
   The guerrillas, who have ignored calls for a cease-fire by
President Najib, appear to be tightening an economic blockade of the
capital and are viewed as increasingly effective as Afghan soldiers
take over Salang road defenses from departing Soviet units.
   Officials of UNICEF, the U.N. Children's Fund, today said the
struggle for scarce food and fuel has cut attendance at its 40
mother and child welfare clinics in Kabul by nearly half.
   ``They say they can't come because they have to stand in bread
and fuel queues,'' said Vincent O'Reilly of Ireland, who heads the
UNICEF mission.
   In the fuel line in Khairkhana, an old, bearded man, his hands
trembling as he clutched his empty gasoline can, said, ``Allah has
brought this on us. We are black-faced in the sight of Allah.''
   Others blamed the fighting or said the guerrillas were trying to
cut off the capital. Some said they now don't want the Soviets _
about whom Afghans in the street are usually openly hostile _ to
leave.
</TEXT>
