<FIRST>r i PM-Belgium-Kidnapping     01-17 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Belgium-Kidnapping,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Asks Ransom, Threatens to Kill Ex-Prime Minister</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAF CASERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A previously unknown group claiming to
hold a former prime minister today issued a ransom demand and
threatened to kill him, officials said.
   The daily Le Soir received a letter from the Revolutionary
Socialists Brigade asking for a ransom of between $525,000 and
$790,000 for former Prime Minister Paul Vanden Boeynants, said Andre
Vandoren, the deputy Brussels prosecutor.
   He said the letter called Vanden Boeynants, a 69-year-old
Christian Democrat who disappeared outside his home Saturday, as ``a
representative of conservative capitalism.''
   ``It was a one-page, typewritten letter with political and
financial demands,'' said an official at Le Soir. He did not
elaborate.
   Earlier, a man claiming to speak for the previously unknown group
call Le Soir and said Vanden Boeynants ``will only be seen back in
small pieces.''
   Officials said a special police crisis center set up to locate
Vanden Boeynants received a similar call.
   The group claimed it had kidnapped Vanden Boeyants in weekend
phone calls to Le Soir and Belgium's French-language radio network.
   In Hilversum, the Netherlands, a caller purporting to be a member
of a French extremist left-wing group claimed responsibility for
kidnapping Vanden Boeynants in a call to a radio stations, police
said today.
   They said the male caller, who spoke Dutch with a Belgian accent,
said Action Directe, France's most notorious left-wing terrorist
group, was holding Vanden Boeynants. A police spokesman in Hilversum
who demanded anonymity said: ``we are taking this seriously.''
   Prime Minister Wilfried Martens has said Vanden Boeynants ``had
received threats lately'' and had asked to meet with the interior
minister Monday, presumably to discuss his personal safety.
   Vanden Boeynants was prime minister between 1966 and 1968 and
again from late 1978 until early 1979. He was defense minister for
seven years in the 1970s.
   He has also been a controversial politician. He received a
three-year suspended sentence in 1986 for tax fraud as head of his
meat packaging business and is under investigation for taking bribes
while he was defense minister.
   He had been scheduled to appear today before a special
legislative investigating commission.
   The 1986 conviction forced Vanden Boeynants to drop his bid for
mayor of Brussels in October.
</TEXT>
