<DOCNO> AP890117-0071 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 0848EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Libya-Gadhafi     01-17 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Libya-Gadhafi,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gadhafi Says He's Abolishing All State Institutions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libyan leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi says that all
state institutions, including the ``security apparatus'' and the
nation's news agency, will be abolished this year.
   In a speech Monday night that was broadcast by Libyan television
and monitored in London, Gadhafi said it was the people who should
rule.
   ``All the institutions which are traditionally considered as
state institutions are to be abolished,'' he said in a speech to a
Basic People's Congress, or grass-roots political committee, in the
community of Al-Jabal Al-Akhdar.
   ``These companies, these institutions and all these bodies seem
to be literally imposed on you. ... They are going to be abolished
from this year,'' Gadhafi said.
   He said that although people's congresses created the
institutions, people still considered them as ``outside their power
and belonging to a government.''
   ``The struggle for power must end,'' he said in a rare
acknowledgement of internal dissent. ``The demonstrations, the
sit-ins and the protests are all protests (against) authority, a
struggle for power.''
   Gadhafi said the action would be the cornerstone for a new time
known as ``the era of the masses.''
   The Libyan leader said that he also will abolish organized
sports, car importing companies and agricultural produce marketing
companies so farmers would be free to market their own produce.
   The government will help find work for those left jobless by the
moves, Gadhafi said.
   He said the nation's security apparatus must be eliminated
``because complaints are mounting against it and its violations are
on the increase.'' Gadhafi also said the agency duplicates
operations of the nation's bureau of investigation.
   He described the news agency JANA as ``a huge octopus with
hundreds of officials'' that is ``useless.''
   ``The Jamahiriyah news agency is one of those establishments
which is tiring me. ... The news item broadcast by the world today,
our agency reports it to us the day after tomorrow,'' Gadhafi said.
   Gadhafi, who took power in a 1969 coup, has always described his
goal as the creation of a political system in which people run the
country without parties or government bodies.
   In recent months, he has made moderating moves in internal
politics.
   In August, Gadhafi announced the abolition of the ``classical
army and the traditional police,'' saying the country would rely
instead on armed civilians for security.
   Last March, riding a bulldozer, he knocked down the wall of
Tripoli's prison and freed some political prisoners. He also said
Libyans were free to travel abroad and gave his blessing to the
flourishing black market.
</TEXT>
