<FIRST>r a PM-Falwell-Abortion     01-17 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Falwell-Abortion,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Falwell Says Beginning Of End Of Abortions Is At Hand</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SNELLVILLE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Jerry Falwell told 2,000 people
at a church service that the U.S. Supreme Court's plan to review a
Missouri law might signal the beginning of the end of legal
abortions.
   ``There's no question that abortion will be done away with,''
said Falwell, founder of the Moral Majority. ``The trend is clearly
toward life and away from death. The abortionists are losing, and
that is why they are becoming so frantic.''
   The Supreme Court has announced that it will rule on the legality
of a Missouri law that bans the use of public hospitals, employees
and money for abortions. The law was struck down by lower courts and
now is on appeal.
   While Falwell hailed the prospect of the high court taking up
abortion, which was legalized in 1973 in the landmark Roe v. Wade
case, he also said he wanted more ironclad guarantees than the court
could provide.
   ``Our ultimate goal is a constitutional amendment. A Supreme
Court reversal or modification of Roe v. Wade would be a good step
in the right direction, but it is not the answer we're seeking,'' he
said.
   Before Monday night's meeting, 15 protesters marched in front of
the First Baptist Church of Snellville chanting slogans against
Falwell. Snellville is an Atlanta suburb.
   ``We want to let Jerry Falwell know that whenever he's in town
we'll be there to protest because he endorses and finances Operation
Rescue and its agenda to suppress women's rights,'' said Jack
Pelham, leader of a group called the Coalition Opposing Operation
Rescue.
   Operation Rescue is a New York-based group that staged the
long-running anti-abortion protests in Atlanta that began during the
Democratic National Convention last summer.
</TEXT>
