<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines-Attack     01-17 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Attack,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Official Killed In Ambush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen today assassinated an official
of a government panel charged with recovering the alleged ill-gotten
wealth of ousted President Ferdinand Marcos and his associates,
police said.
   A few hours after the slaying of Jesus Ronan, another official of
the Presidential Commission on Good Government received a death
threat, officials said.
   Ronan, 58, a former air force colonel and operations director of
the commission, was shot twice in the head while driving his car in
the Manila suburb of Malabon, police said.
   They said Ronan apparently managed to hit one of the assailants
with his car. Witnesses said the man was injured and had to be
dragged away by his companions, who escaped after commandeering a
motorcycle with a sidecar.
   Police said a motive for the assassination could not be
immediately established. There was no claim of responsibility.
   But commission officials said the attack was staged by
``organized enemies'' of the commission. They did not identify the
enemies.
   Commissioner David Castro said Ronan was killed because he
enforced orders to sequester companies that Marcos or his ``front
men'' are believed to have acquired illegally during Marcos' 20-year
rule.
   ``Some power groups may be trying to send us a message,'' said
Robert Federis, the commission's investigations director.
   Federis said about four hours after Ronan was killed, a man
telephoned his office and told his secretary, ``Tell (Federis) he is
next.''
</TEXT>
