<FIRST>r a PM-Marcos     01-17 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marcos,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Philippine President's Condition Unchanged</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deposed Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos was
moved out of intensive care, but he remained in guarded condition
today at a hospital, officials said.
   Marcos, 71, was admitted to St. Francis Medical Center on Sunday,
suffering from pneumonia and bronchial asthma, hospital officials
said. He has been hospitalized three times in a little more than a
month.
   ``He's in better spirits,'' Dr. Calvin Wong, Marcos'
cardiologist, said Monday.
   Wong said Marcos' condition improved enough Monday afternoon for
him to be moved out of the intensive care unit.
   Wong said it was difficult to predict how long Marcos would be
hospitalized.
   ``I don't know how he got pneumonia, but he's very weak and I
guess that makes it more likely for him to get sick,'' said Marcos
spokesman Gemmo Trinidad.
   Marcos' two previous hospital stays were for treatment of
congestive heart failure. He last was released from the hospital
Jan. 5.
   A federal court hearing is scheduled for Thursday in New York to
determine whether Marcos is healthy enough to travel there for
arraignment on racketeering charges.
   An indictment returned Oct. 21 accused Marcos and his wife,
Imelda, of plundering more than $100 million from their homeland and
using the money to buy art and real estate in Manhattan. Mrs. Marcos
is free on $5 million bail after pleading innocent to the charges in
New York.
