<FIRST>r i PM-BelgiumKidnapping 1stLd-Writethru a0515 01-17 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Belgium Kidnapping, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0515,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ransom Demanded For Former Prime Minister</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with details of ransom letter, CORRECT
amount of ransom. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAF CASERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A previously unknown terrorist group
today demanded a $790,000 ransom for the release of Paul Vanden
Boeynants, the former Belgian prime minister it claims to have
kidnapped.
   In a one-page typewritten letter, the Revolutionary Socialist
Brigade demanded that two-thirds of the ransom come from Vanden
Boeynants' political and business partners and be given to the poor,
according to deputy Brussels prosecutor Andre Vandoren.
   The rest of the ransom would be for the group's ``participation
in the effort to mobilize ... the people.''
   Initially, it was incorrectly reported that the kidnappers were
demanding a ransom of between $525,000 _ two-thirds of the total sum
_ and $790,000.
   The letter, delivered to Brussels dailies Le Soir and Het Laatste
Nieuws, called Vanden Boeynants ``a corrupt person ... who has
stolen large public funds for his own profit'' and called for a
``people's tribunal'' to try him.
   Vanden Boeynants, 69, a businessman and Christian Democrat
politician who disappeared Saturday, is under investigation for
taking bribes when he was defense minister for seven years in the
1970s.
   A special legislative commission was to open a hearing today to
consider initiating legal action against him.
   The letter reinforced the belief the kidnapping is politically
motivated. It did not threaten the life of the politician, unlike
two anonymous phone calls earlier today to police in Belgium and to
Le Soir.
   ``We have VdB,'' said the caller, using the politician's
nickname. ``Who we are you will never know. You will never see him
again. We will return him in small pieces.'' Vandoren related the
threat to reporters.
   A third call, received by a radio station in Hilversum, the
Netherlands, came from an anonymous caller purporting to represent
the French terrorist group Direct Action. He said the group is
holding Vanden Boeynants.
   Prime Minister Wilfried Martens has said Vanden Boeynants ``had
received threats lately'' and asked to meet the interior minister
Monday, presumably to discuss his personal safety.
   Officials have expressed concern about the health of the
politician, who needs daily medication for a heart condition.
   Vanden Boeynants was prime minister between 1966 and 1968 and
again from late 1978 until early 1979.
   He received a three-year suspended sentence for tax fraud as head
of his meat packaging business in 1986. That conviction forced him
to drop a bid to become mayor of Brussels in October.
</TEXT>
