<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-ChildCare     01-17 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Child Care,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Rejects Challenge to Virginia Law on Child-Care Centers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today rejected a challenge to
a state law exempting religiously affiliated child-care centers from
some health and safety standards all other child-care centers must
meet.
   The justices, without comment, let stand a federal appeals court
ruling that the Virginia law does not violate the constitutionally
required separation of government and religion.
   The disputed 1979 state licensing law allows child-care centers
run by churches or other religious organizations to seek an exempt
status _ avoiding many of the health and safety standards applied to
such facilities.
   Exempt centers still must meet basic health and safety standards,
however.
   Child-care centers with no religious affiliation must obtain a
state license, and are not entitled to seek the exemption.
   Among the 215 centers that could obtain exempt status under the
Virginia law, 106 have opted instead to operate with state licenses.
   The law was challenged in 1980 by three licensed child-care
centers that have no religious ties _ Forest Hills Early Learning
Center in Lynchburg, Academy Day Care in Woodbridge and Holloman
Child Care Centers in Hampton and Grafton.
   A federal judge struck down the exemption as unconstitutional but
the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reversed that ruling last May
6.
   ``Absent the exemption, some church leaders would immediately be
forced to violate their convictions against submitting aspects of
their ministries to state licensing, or face legal action,'' the
appeals court said.
   Its ruling relied heavily on a 1987 Supreme Court decision in
which the justices said religious organizations may practice
employment discrimination by favoring members of their faith even
for non-religious jobs.
   In that case, the court unanimously upheld the firing in Utah of
a gymnasium custodian who failed to qualify for membership in the
Mormon Church, which owned and ran the gym.
   The court, in that 1987 ruling, said a 1972 federal law exempting
religious groups from a federal anti-bias law does not violate
separation of church and state.
   After the non-religious centers in Virginia appealed the 4th
Circuit court's decision, state officials filed a counter-appeal
contending that the appeals court was wrong in ruling that the
centers had the proper ``standing'' to challenge the 1979 law.
   Today, the Supreme Court denied review to both appeals.
   The cases are Forest Hills Early Learning Center vs. Jackson,
88-730, and Jackson vs. Forest Hills Early Learning Center, 88-932.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
