<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Lead     01-17 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Lead,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Refuses to Revive Dallas Lead Pollution Lawsuit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to revive a
$200 million lawsuit that accused a federal environmental official
of failing to take swift action against industrial lead pollution in
Dallas.
   The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that threw out the
suit against the government.
   The suit was filed by 189 families in Dallas who live near three
lead smelters, operated by RSR Corp., Dixie Metals Corp. and N.L.
Industries.
   They sought damages under the Federal Tort Claims Act, which
allows citizens to sue the government in some circumstances.
   The Dallas families said members have suffered brain damage,
developmental defects and ``lifelong debilitating effects'' from
lead pollution.
   Their suit said John Hernandez, deputy administrator of the
Environmental Protection Agency, was negligent because he ordered
further study of the problem rather than an immediate clean-up after
a congressional hearing in 1983 found high levels of lead in soil
and in schoolchildren's blood samples.
   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals here last July upheld a federal
judge's ruling that dismissed the case.
   The appeals court said Hernandez's decision to order further
study was a discretionary policy-making action immune from suit
under the Tort Claims Act.
   The plaintiffs said Hernandez's decision was based only upon
scientific considerations that did not involve the exercise of such
discretion.
   But the appeals court said Hernandez based his decision on
``economic, social and political policy considerations'' making his
choice immune from suit.
   For example, Hernandez said he was concerned that a clean-up
would set a precedent for other areas of the nation. He also said
that failure to order further study would expose him to criticism he
acted too hastily.
   One of the smelters made a pollution clean-up offer. But
Hernandez said he was reluctant to accept the offer without
additional study because the clean-up might be inadequate.
   The case is Wells vs. U.S., 88-653.
</TEXT>
