<FIRST>r a PM-PilotReturned     01-17 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pilot Returned,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Body Of American Pilot Returned To United States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THERESA HUMPHREY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DOVER AIR FORCE BASE, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The body of a U.S. Air Force
officer shot down over Libya in 1986 was returned to the United
States as his brother eulogized him for representing ``the good
things that our country stands for.''
   Maj. Fernando Ribas-Dominicci was killed in the 1986 U.S. air
raid on Tripoli. The 33-year-old captain was promoted posthumously
to major.
   The C-141 Starlifter carrying Ribas-Dominicci's body from
Torrenjon Air Base in Spain was met Monday by an Air Force honor and
color guard and by family members, including the pilot's wife,
Blanca Berain Ribas-Dominicci, 36, and 7-year-old son, Fernando Jr.,
both of Austin, Texas.
   Salvador Ribas-Dominicci, the pilot's brother, said the family
was proud of what ``Paul and Fernando and the rest of the guys were
doing in the defense of democracy, freedom and the good things that
our country stands for.''
   He referred to Capt. Paul Lorence of San Francisco, who was in
the F-111 bomber with Ribas-Dominicci when it was shot down.
   Libya had said the body it released and flew to Rome on Friday
was that of Lorence. An autopsy, however, showed it was
Ribas-Dominicci.
   Salvador Ribas-Dominicci said he was angry because the body
should have been identified and returned immediately after the plane
was shot down. ``Military people are supposed to live by codes of
honor,'' he said.
   The body will be prepared for burial at Dover Air Force Base,
which handles the bodies of servicemen and their dependents who die
in Europe, the Azores, Greenland and Iceland. Burial will be in
Puerto Rico, the brother said.
</TEXT>
