<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 1109EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w BC-Justice-Meese-Excerpts     01-17 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Justice-Meese-Excerpts,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>With Justice-Meese</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from the report on former
Attorney General Edwin Meese III by the Justice Department's Office
of Professional Responsibility:
   
   Conclusion
   ``We trust that this analysis will lay to rest the claims by Mr.
Meese that the appropriate standard for official behavior is whether
an independent counsel seeks an official's indictment. We found that
the independent counsel's report far from vindicates Mr. Meese;
rather, it details conduct which should not be tolerated of any
government employee, especially not the attorney general of the
United States. Were he still serving as attorney general, we would
recommend to the acting attorney general that the president take
disciplinary action.''
   
   On his relationship with longtime friend E. Robert Wallach:
   ``We must conclude that Mr. Meese, in certain instances involving
Mr. Wallach, either did not understand, or did not appreciate, or
simply did not care what impression could be left with the public
about his own integrity and the integrity of those functions he
oversaw.''
   
   On dealing with Wallach on subjects as varied as Wedtech Corp.
and the Iraqi oil pipeline:
   ``The subjects varied, but a strong undercurent flows through a
not insubstantial number of those communications and that
undercurrent was Mr. Wallach's seeking action in matters in which he
had a financial interest from Mr. Meese or his staff. Mr. Meese
continued to accept these communications, gave no indication
whatsoever that he was not receptive to them, and took them into
account in various official actions.
   ``We have discovered no evidence that any other friend of Mr.
Meese had a relationship remotely similar to that enjoyed by Mr.
Wallach.''
   
   Regarding the $1 billion proposed Iraqi oil pipeline, in which
Wallach was representing Swiss oilman Bruce Rappaport, and dealings
with then-national security adviser Robert McFarlane:
   ``In the pipeline matter, Mr. Meese knew that his close friend
had a financial interest in the project; nevertheless, he called Mr.
McFarlane (which resulted in a meeting between McFarlane, Wallach
and Rappaport).
   ``In addition, that call intentionally circumvented the
Department of State, and thereby initiated a sequence of events
involving important foreign policy considerations without the
participation of the principal foreign policy arm of the government.
... His call facilitated a private venture with enormous profit
potential to private individuals, including Mr. Meese's friend and
creditor, Mr. Wallach.''
</TEXT>
