<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 1113EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-GrainSales     01-17 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Grain Sales,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Near Limit of Subsidized Wheat Purchases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Private exporters have sold an additional
200,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat to China at subsidized prices,
almost cleaning out Beijing's current authorization under the
program, the Agriculture Department said today.
   Melvin E. Sims, general sales manager for the department's
Foreign Agricultural Service, said the wheat was part of 1 million
tons authorized Dec. 30 for China under the Export Enhancement
Program, or EEP.
   Under the EEP arrangement, exporters can sell wheat and other
designated commodities to specified countries at reduced prices in
order to meet foreign competition. Exporters then collect free
government surpluses of grain or other products as bonuses, or
subsidies.
   The wheat sales were handled by two companies: Cargill Inc.,
115,000 tons, and Louis Dreyfus Corp., 85,000 tons.
   Sims said the wheat was sold for March shipment and will carry an
average subsidy rate of $22.49 per ton, or about 62 cents per bushel.
   Only 10,000 tons remain available to China under the program, he
said.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels
of wheat. The 200,000 tons of wheat would be about 7.34 million
bushels.
   Wheat prices at the farm have been averaging around $4.09 per
bushel, according to recent USDA market figures, making the new sale
worth an estimated $30 million.
</TEXT>
