<FIRST>r i PM-Iran-US     01-17 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-US,0536</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Says Iran is `Limited' in Hostage Situation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES D'EMILIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's prime minister today said President-elect
George Bush is working more to justify U.S. policy in Lebanon than
to free American hostages there.
   Bush recently indicated Iran could help free nine U.S. hostages
held by Shiite Moslems believed loyal to Iran.
   But Prime Minister Hussein Musavi of Iran gave little
encouragement.
   He said the hostage issue was an ``internal question of
Lebanon,'' and his country ``is limited because it is a question of
territory.''
   Musavi was asked at a news conference what Tehran can do to help
the hostages, in view of the impending change of U.S. administration.
   As for Bush, Musavi said he believed ``he is, more than trying to
work for the release, trying to justify his policy'' in Lebanon.
   The Iranian hinted the United States should rethink its policy
toward Lebanon but did not say what changes should be made.
   Musavi also maintained ``it's not clear who these groups are who
take hostages'' in Lebanon.
   He arrived in Italy on Monday for talks to improve economic
relations. The two-day visit was his first to a Western country
since Iran and Iraq agreed Aug. 20 to a cease-fire in their 8-year
war.
   In a recent interview, Bush said the cease-fire ``has potential
for amelioration of that hostage situation, but I think it would be
improper to assume that Iran controls a key to all these hostages.''
   Still, Bush said ``it's in our interests to have better relations
with Iran.''
   In Rome, Musavi also criticized an international declaration
issued in Paris last week on chemical weapons, saying ``People can
still easily construct chemical arms.'' The declaration is not
binding on the 149 nations that said they are against the use and
spread of chemical arms.
   Musavi reiterated Iran's charges that Iraq used chemical weapons
during their war _ an allegation Iraq denies.
   Musavi left for an audience with Pope John Paul II that was the
Roman Catholic Church leader's first with an official of the Islamic
republic.
   The pope urged that Iran and Iraq exchange their 100,000
prisoners of war as soon as possible ``to alleviate the suffering of
these men and to give back to so many families the joy of being
together again,'' according to Vatican spokesman Joaquin Navarro.
   As the private audience went on in the pope's library, police
dispersed about 30 supporters and opponents of the Iranian
government who shoved each other and yelled insults in St. Peter's
Square.
   After 20 minutes of private talks, the pope publicly met Musavi's
entourage and spoke briefly to Hojatoleslam Sadeq Khalkhali,
chairman of the Iranian Parliament's foreign affairs committee.
   ``Our revolution is a religious revolution and we ask you to pray
for peace in the world,'' Khalkhali said.
   ``That's what we're doing,'' the pope responded.
   The Iranian continued, ``We know the world needs religious spirit
and until there is religious spirit there will not be morality.''
   The pope then offered his blessing to all Iranians, including
``those fallen in war.''
</TEXT>
