<FIRST>r i PM-Bahrain-Mine     01-17 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bahrain-Mine,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fishing Boat Hits Floating Mine, Skipper Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fishing boat hit a floating mine and
exploded today in Persian Gulf waters northeast of Bahrain, the
official Gulf News Agency reported. It said the skipper was killed.
   The agency quoted an Interior Ministry statement as saying
another fishing boat picked up the boat's five crew members, who
were injured in the blast, and took them to a Bahrain hospital.
   Rescuers also recovered the body of the skipper, identified as
Bahraini national Yacoub Ali Yacoub, the statement said.
   Drifting mines from the former Iran-Iraq war zone, torn from
their moorings by winter storms, remain a hazard for shipping in the
gulf. Up to 200 floating mines may be left from the war, mainly in
the northern part of the waterway.
   About 20 mines have been neutralized since a cease-fire took
effect Aug. 20.
   A floating mine was believed responsible for a Jan. 5 explosion
that triggered a blaze aboard the 36,904-ton Saudi Arabian tanker
Sagheera as it sailed into the gulf through the Strait of Hormuz.
   The blast killed the Greek master and the five other crew members
of Greek and Sri Lankan nationality. The vessel split in two and
sank.
