<DOCNO> AP890117-0098 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 1234EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Chronology     01-17 0658</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Chronology,0710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Solidarity's Chronicle of Survival</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Key events in Solidarity history:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1980</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 14 _ Electrician Lech Walesa leads an occupation stike at
Gdansk's Lenin shipyard and starts a worker revolt against the
communist state.
   Aug. 31 _ Legal registration makes Solidarity the Soviet bloc's
only independent union. During its 16 months of legal activity,
Solidarity membership will grow to an estimated 10 million and a
sense of renewal will sweep the nation.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1981</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Dec. 13 _ Martial law is declared by Polish leader Gen. Wojciech
Jaruzelski, Solidarity activities are suppressed and thousands of
members are interned, including Walesa.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1982</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 8 _ Solidarity is banned and an official trade union
alliance is created to take its place. President Reagan expands U.S.
economic sanctions against Poland by suspending its ``most favored''
trade status.
   Nov. 11 _ Walesa is freed.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1983</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   July 22 _ Jaruzelski lifts martial law but leaves many
restrictive edicts.
   Oct. 5 _ Walesa wins the Nobel Peace Prize.
   Oct. 3 _ The government steps up pressure on key activists still
underground and offers 11 in prison, including advisers to Walesa,
``one-way passports'' out of the country to avoid trial on sedition
charges.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1984</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   July 21 _ An amnesty is approved for political prisoners,
including the 11 prominent union leaders jailed after the
martial-law crackdown.
   Oct. 19 _ The popular pro-Solidarity priest, the Rev. Jerzy
Popieluszko, is slain. Four state security police will be tried and
convicted in the murder.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1985</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 31 _ Walesa accuses the government of presiding over a
political, economic and cultural disaster as supporters nationwide
mark the fifth anniversary of Solidarity's birth.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1986</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 11 _ The government orders the release of 225 political
prisoners, including all senior Solidarity leaders.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1987</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Feb. 19 _ Reagan lifts the last of U.S. sanctions against Poland.
   Nov. 29 _ Poles vote in first referendum in 41 years, but deny
government support for economic reform package.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1988</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   April 24-May 10 _ Strikes hit steel mills, shipyards and other
plants across Poland. Police break up one strike others gradually
die out.
   Aug. 16 _ Workers declare a strike at the July Manifesto coal
mine in Jasztrebie in a pay dispute. The strikes spread, creating
Poland's worst wave of labor strife in seven years.
   Aug. 26 _ Interior Minister Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak proposes talks
with workers, laying the groundwork for a possible government
meeting with Walesa.
   Aug. 31 _ On the eighth anniversary of the legalization of
Solidarity, Walesa holds his first meeting with government officials
in six years and appeals to workers to end strikes.
   Sept. 3 _ July Manifesto miners end their strike.
   Sept. 19 _ The government led by Prime Minister Zbigniew Messner
resigns amid sharp criticism of its management of the economy.
   Sept. 27 _ Parliament names Micezyslaw F. Rakowski as prime
minister.
   Oct. 25 _ The talks are postponed as government objects to two
opposition participants.
   Oct. 31 _ Government announces plans to close Lenin shipyard in
Gdansk as unprofitable.
   Nov. 30 _ Walesa holds an unprecedented live TV debate with
Alfred Miodowicz, head of the official trade union. Walesa is hailed
as the victor, and government polls show support for legalizing
Solidarity on the rise.
   Dec. 20-21 _ At the first part of a party plenum, Central
Committee members are instructed to poll the party rank-and-file for
their attitude toward Solidarity.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1989</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 4 _ The government plans price increases of 20 percent and
hopes to hold overall inflation to 50 percent.
   Jan. 13 _ A party source says the government is willing to
restore Solidarity's legal status if it joins in political and
economic reforms.
   Jan. 16 _ At the second part of a party plenum, Central Committee
members debate whether Poland's future includes trade union
pluralism.
   Jan. 17 _ Rakowski urges the party to legalize Solidarity on
condition it not be a government opponent that would ``pull the
country into anarchy.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
