<DOCNO> AP890117-0099 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 1234EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SlidingHouse     01-17 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sliding House,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mudslide Knocks House Off Foundations; Others Evacuated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. ALBANS, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An early morning mudslide that ``looked
like lava'' pushed a house 10 feet off its foundation Tuesday and
forced authorities to evacuate 10 other homes, officials said.
   ``I've got chest-high mud in what used to be my back yard,'' said
Robey Kaufman, whose $100,000 home was destroyed.
   The hill into which the house was built began shifting late
Monday night for reasons still unclear Tuesday, but water from a
broken main behind the house might have loosened the mud, said
Kanawha County Public Safety Director Mark Wolford.
   ``It was like a wall of mud,'' Wolford said. ``The fire chief out
there said it looked like lava.''
   Mud from the hill piled up against the back of the house and the
pressure collapsed the basement, slowly pushing the house off its
foundation and into the front yard, Wolford said.
   The Kaufmans ``apparently heard the house making some unusual
popping and cracking noises. They finally decided they should get
out of there,'' he said.
   By the time authorities were called, 12:30 a.m., the house was
off its foundation. Gas, water and electical lines had been severed,
Wolford said.
   As a precaution, authorities asked people living in the 10 other
houses on the dead-end street to leave for a few hours.
   The Kaufmans are staying with neighbors, Wolford said.
</TEXT>
