<DOCNO> AP890117-0100 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 1238EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-BakerConfirmation 3rLd-Writethru a0561 01-17 0923</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Baker Confirmation, 3rLd-Writethru, a0561,850</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Says US Should Aim to Keep Soviets on Constructive Track</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Restructures top, picks up 5th graf pvs, ``Bipartisanship</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State-designate James A. Baker III
called today for a renewal of bipartisanship in foreign policy and a
joint effort with Congress to ensure that ``a more responsible,
constructive policy'' emerges from the changes reshaping the Soviet
system.
   ``Yes, this is an appeal for a kinder, gentler Congress,'' Baker
said at a hearing by the Senate Foreign Relations Committee on his
nomination to take over the State Department after President-elect
Bush takes office. Baker was the first of Bush's Cabinet choices to
start then confirmation process.
   Baker also said the United States cannot abandon the Contra
rebels opposing Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government.
   ``We must stand by them until our mutual goals are achieved,''
Baker said, adding that the United States must insist on protection
for human rights not only in Nicaragua but in El Salvador and other
Central American nations as well.
   He said the premier task of U.S. policy must be make certain that
the Soviets move toward positive changes.
   ``Our task is to arrange affairs so that whatever the outcome of
perestroika, a more responsible, constructive Soviet policy will
remain in Moscow's interest,'' Baker said.
   Sketching a broad outline of the foreign policy goals of the
incoming administration, Baker said experience has shown that a
bipartisan foreign policy is an indispensable ingredient of success
as the nation faces the problems and turmoil of an increasingly
complex world.
   ``Bipartisanship does not mean that we must always agree,'' Baker
said. ``There are and always will be differences in approach and
substance.''
   ``But eventually we must proceed,'' he said. ``And when we do it
is best that we do so together if we are to achieve the national
interest.''
   ``Yes, this is an appeal for a kinder, gentler Congress,'' Baker
said. ``Bipartisanship ... is the lubricant that enables the
branches of government to overcome their natural constitutionally
designed friction, a friction that arises from our differences of
perspectives and our different responsibilities.''
   ``As a realist, I know we need bipartisanship to succeed,'' Baker
said. ``In order to succeed we must work together.''
   The first order of business between the Republican administration
and the Democratic-run Congress, he suggested, is a ``meeting of our
minds on how to proceed with a changing Soviet Union.''
   Baker suggested that if that happens, conclusions will include
the need to modernize U.S. conventional and nuclear weapons, to set
``realistic and prudent standards'' for conventional arms control
and to reach a common approach on the issue of loans and credits to
the Soviet Union.
   ``Realism forces us to be prudent,'' Baker said. ``However
fascinating the twists and turns of perestroika (economic
restructuring) may be and however riveting the details of decline as
reported in Soviet newspapers, the Soviet Union remains a heavily
armed superpower.''
   ``The talk is different but the force structure and policies that
support far-reaching interests and clients have not changed
commensurately,'' the nominee said. ``Many of those policies and
those clients are hostile to American values and threaten our
interests. That's a reality.''
   Baker proposed a multi-step approach to Soviet President Mikhail
S. Gorbachev's new policies, among them:
   _Continue to welcome reform and changes.
   _Recognize that U.S. policies and strength have contributed to
Moscow's new sense of realism.
   _Continue to probe the Soviets on arms control, human rights,
regional conflicts and overall relations.
   _Place additional emphasis on ending regional conflicts in Asia,
Africa and Central America and ``not allow the rhetoric of restraint
to become a substituter for restraint itself.''
   _Seek help from the Soviets in dealing with such global problems
as drugs, terrorism and the environment and if it is not
forthcoming, find out why.
   As the hearings opened, many senators were hoping to learn in
what areas of foreign policy the Bush administration will differ
from the often ideologically rigid positions pursued by the Reagan
administration in the last eight years.
   But Baker, a friend of the president-elect and pragmatic
political ally of longstanding, may be hindered in his responses by
his lack of direct foreign policy experience. Baker, Reagan's former
chief of staff and secretary of the treasury, did obtain experience
dealing with the world's financial leaders during his years at the
Treasury in Reagan's first term.
   He drew up the Baker plan to deal with Latin American debt. The
plan calls for increased lending by commercial banks to Latin
America in return for economic restructuring.
   Some expect Bush, who served as U.S. liaison officer to China and
director of the Central Intelligence Agency, will seek to set his
administration's foreign policy direction himself, leaving Baker to
manage it.
   Baker does, in fact, possess skill as a tactical policy manager
and a clear ability to deal easily with Congress.
   While senators will seek to learn exactly what Baker will be
asked to manage, some are dubious about obtaining concrete results,
at least this early in the game.
   ``Baker will duck every substantive question,'' was the flat
prediction of one Democrtic staff member who helped plan the two
days of confirmation hearings and who asked not to be identified by
name.
   Still, the Senate is almost certain to confirm Baker, possibly
before the end of the month. But before it does, lawmakers will seek
Baker's public agreement to consult widely with Congress as events
and policies unfold and to link hands in a search for a bipartisan
foreign policy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
