<DOCNO> AP890117-0104 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 1250EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Networks-Inauguration     01-17 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Networks-Inauguration,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Networks Will Pre-Empt for Live Coverage of Inauguration</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Inuagural Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Television networks will pre-empt regular
programming during the day Friday for live coverage of the
presidential inauguration and most will present late-night specials
with highlights of the day's events.
   CBS and NBC plan to begin live coverage at 10 a.m. EST and
conclude at about 4 p.m. EST. ABC will begin at 10:30 and conclude
around 3 p.m.
   Public television stations will have live coverage of the
inauguration ceremony from 11:30-12:30. CNN will have live coverage
from 11 a.m. until 5 p.m.
   NBC and ABC's ``Nightline'' will have half-hour wrapups on the
inauguration, the parade and coverage of the inaugural balls at
11:30 p.m. CNN's late wrapup will begin at 10 p.m. PBS will have
highlights at 11 p.m.
   Most network news programs are originating from Washington this
week, including the ``CBS Evening News'' and ``ABC World News
Tonight'' Wednesday through Friday; ``NBC Nightly News'' and
``Today'' Thursday and Friday; ``CBS This Morning'' and ``Good
Morning America'' on Friday morning; and ABC's ``20-20'' Friday
night.
   Bernard Shaw and Mary Alice Williams will anchor CNN's daytime
coverage. Reid Collins will anchor at night.
   Paul Duke, moderator of ``Washington Week in Review,'' will
anchor the Public Broadcasting Service coverage.
   NBC's Tom Brokaw will be joined by Bryant Gumbel during the
morning. Jane Pauley will join Brokaw in the afternoon. The special
that night will be anchored by Brokaw and Connie Chung.
   CBS's coverage will be anchored by Dan Rather and Charles Kuralt.
ABC will have Peter Jennings and David Brinkley, joined by Barbara
Walters in the afternoon.
   Walters' interview with George and Barbara Bush will air on ABC's
``20-20'' that night, which will also include live coverage from the
inaugural balls.
</TEXT>
