<FIRST>u a PM-BentsenFatherKilled 1stLd-Writethru a0569 01-17 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bentsen Father Killed, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0569,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senator's Father Killed In Auto Accident</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `According to ...,' to clarify that intersection
had a stop sign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDINBURG, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lloyd Bentsen Sr., the father of Sen.
Lloyd Bentsen, was killed in a traffic accident near this south
Texas town this morning, police said. He was 92.
   The senior Bentsen was killed when his car collided with another
car at a rural intersection between Edinburg and Mission, a
neighboring town just north of the Mexican border, said police Chief
A.C. Gonzales.
   Bentsen's ranch, the Arrowhead, is about 30 miles northwest of
the intersection.
   Two people in the second car were injured, neither critically.
   According to David Wells, a spokesman for the Texas Department of
Public Safety, the accident occurred when Bentsen failed to yield
the right of way at the intersection. Bentsen had a stop sign; the
other car did not, Wells said.
   ``I do not know if he stopped and then pulled out in front of
this oncoming vehicle or didn't stop,'' Wells said.
   Wells said Bentsen was pronounced dead at the scene by Mission
Justice of the Peace Juan Rosel.
   The occupants of the second car were identified as driver Ramiro
Rosales and his sister, Margarita Rosales. Both taken to Mission
Hospital in McAllen, where Ms. Rosales was listed in stable
condition pending surgery; her brother was scheduled to be released
after treatment for cuts and bruises.
   Bentsen managed about 42,000 acres of farms and six ranches
scattered over a south Texas empire he started carving out of the
brush and thorn forest in 1920.
   He and his wife Dolly, who died in 1977, had three other
children: Kenneth, a Houston architect; Don, a McAllen businessman;
and Betty, the wife of Rio Grande Valley businessman Dan Winn.
   Lloyd Bentsen Jr. won re-election to his U.S. Senate seat last
November, when he also lost a run for vice president on the
Democratic ticket with Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis.
   His office in Washington declined to comment on reports of the
death.
</TEXT>
