<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Turkey-Detention     01-17 0155</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Turkey-Detention,0159</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ethnic Kurds Detained in Southeastern Turkey</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security officials have detained at least
200 people in the southeast in the past two weeks on charges of
collaborating with Kurdish guerrillas, officials said Tuesday.
   Fuat Atalay, a deputy from the main opposition Social Democrat
Populist Party, told The Associated Press that more than 200 people
of Kurdish origin had been detained in the province of Diyarbakir.
   Other sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said about 200
others were rounded up in nearby Siirt province.
   Kurdish guerrillas operating in the southeast are affiliated with
the Kurdish Labor Party, which seeks to establish a Marxist state in
parts of southeastern and eastern Turkey.
   About 800 civilians and military personnel and an equal number of
Kurdish rebels have been killed since the party began attacking
military targets and villages in 1984. Ethnic Kurds make up about
one-fifth of Turkey's population of 55 million.
</TEXT>
