<FIRST>r a PM-NorCalQuake 1stLd-Writethru a0467 01-17 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NorCal Quake, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0467,0208</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mild Quakes Rattle Northern California, Seattle</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 3rd graf, `The National ... ,' to ADD
Seattle quakes.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ARCATA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mild earthquake rattled Northern
California's coast, but there were no reports of injuries or damage,
officials said.
   The temblor struck at 9:05 p.m. Monday and was centered 15 miles
east of Arcata, about 220 miles north of San Francisco, the state
Office of Emergency Services said.
   The National Earthquake Information Center in Golden, Colo.,
measured the quake at 3.4 on the Richter Scale.
   Early today, another minor earthquake jolted parts of Seattle and
its eastern suburbs.
   The 5:55 a.m. temblor registered 3.3 on the Richter scale, said
Chris Jonientz-Trisler, seismic analyst with the University of
Washington.
   Late last week, about 10 small quakes, the largest registering
2.2, were recorded beneath Mercer Island in Lake Washington, east of
Seattle. The temblors were widely felt in Kirkland and other suburbs
east of the city.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude.
   An earthquake of 3.5 on the Richter scale can cause slight damage
in the local area.
</TEXT>
