<FIRST>r w AM-CarcassImports     01-17 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Carcass Imports,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rule Proposed to Ease Rule on Imported Meat Carcasses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department on Tuesday proposed
a change in federal meat inspection regulations to allow importation
of slaughtered livestock carcasses with certain tissues removed.
   Current regulations require imported cascasses of cattle, sheep,
swine and goats to include internal tissues such as the pleura,
peritoneum and body or portal lymph nodes to help inspectors spot
disease or other abnormalities, said Lester M. Crawford,
administrator of the department's Food Safety and Inspection Service.
   But these requirements began many years ago when foreign
countries' exporting practices were much different, he said.
   ``Today all countries which are certified as eligible to export
meat to the United States must have an inspection system that is
equal to ours,'' Crawford said. ``This means that the carcasses,
including these specific tissues, have already been inspected in
that country.''
   The proposal, which is in response to a petition from Cloverdale
Foods Co., Minot, N.D., will be open for public comment through Feb.
16. Comments can be sent to: Policy Office, Attn. Linda Carey, FSIS
Hearing Clerk, Room 3171-S, USDA, Washington, D.C. 20250.
</TEXT>
