<FIRST>r w AM-CapitalCity     01-17 0623</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Capital City,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Capital Glows, but Not All of the City Within</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Inauguration Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA M. HAMM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's capital will be trying to cover a
ragged image with its Sunday best when the nation turns its eyes
this way for the inauguration of George Bush.
   Police spokesman Lt. Reginald Smith said officers would be
working to keep the streets clear of crime and vice while Washington
is full of visitors celebrating the installation of a new president.
   ``We're going to intensify our efforts to abate many of the
nuisances throughout the city,'' said Smith, specifically mentioning
increased efforts against prostitution and drug sales.
   Washington's facade, with its historic monuments and powerful
residents, has cracked lately.
   The festivities come at a time when the city is dismayed by its
murder rate _ 371 slayings last year, mostly due to drug wars _ and
embarrassed by its mayor, Marion Barry, the subject of two
investigations recently into his social ties with people who were
the subjects of drug probes.
   ``Much has been said about the mayor and the city's image,''
William Sinclair, the new president of the Greater Washington Board
of Trade, said recently. ``Obviously, in the short term, this
doesn't help (business in the district).''
   The federal government has provided the D.C. Inaugural Committee
with $2.3 million to pay for police and fire protection, medical and
ambulance service, traffic control, supervision of construction of
stands along the parade route, food inspection and issuance of
``official inaugural maps,'' according to Cecilia Perry of the
Office of Emergency Preparedness.
   Ms. Perry said the city had made no plans to shove its homeless
residents out of sight. Estimates of their numbers run from 7,500 to
twice that figure.
   ``There's nothing that can be done,'' she said. ``It
(homelessness) is a problem in the city. They have a right to watch
the parade just like everyone else.''
   But homeless-rights activist Mitch Snyder, whose Community for
Creative Non-Violence operates a shelter three blocks from the
inaugural parade route, said police usually force the homeless out
of sight by threatening to drive them far from town and leave them
there.
   ``It happened to me in 1980,'' Snyder said. ``I was homeless.
Police came by about 5:30 in the morning and said, `If you're not
off this grate within half an hour, we'll take you somewhere and
drop you off.' Most people realize what the police want. They want
you to drop from sight. So you do.''
   ``It's fairly common for homeless people to be hassled by police
and by other officials on the street, told to move on, told that
they're loitering, told that they are not to be there,'' said Maria
Foscarinis, counsel for the National Coalition for the Homeless.
``It's not an unusual experience for homeless people. And what
happens around times like inauguration is that those kinds of
methods are greatly stepped up.''
   At inauguration time in January 1985, image issues took a back
seat to the homeless population's welfare because the district was
locked in a dangerous cold wave.
   City police denied any role in moving homeless people this year.
   About a dozen people, many of them homeless, demonstrate daily in
Lafayette Park across from the White House. Most of that park will
be used for media coverage of the inaugural events, according to
National Park Service spokeswoman Sandra Alley, but a section has
been set aside for protesters.
   U.S. Capitol Police spokesman Dan Nichols said homelessness isn't
a problem on the Capitol grounds, which encompass 180 acres of parks
and congressional office buildings.
   ``It's against the law to sleep in the Capitol grounds
outdoors,'' Nichols said, ``and homeless people are aware of that.''
</TEXT>
