<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 1436EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ShuttleTest     01-17 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shuttle Test,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shuttle Booster Test Delayed Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIGHAM CITY, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Morton Thiokol Inc. has postponed its
final full-scale test of the redesigned space shuttle booster a
third time, citing delays in the rocket's preparation.
   The test, the sixth and last to formally qualify major design
features of the 126-foot-long solid-fuel rocket, had been originally
set for Tuesday, then moved back to Wednesday and Thursday.
   ``The test is now set for Friday. There's no one main reason for
that, just an accumulation of minor delays that put us back a day,''
said Morton Thiokol spokesman Rocky Raab.
   On the two earlier postponements, the company said engineers had
requested more time to adequately chill the solid-fuel motor's 1.1
million pounds of propellant.
   While Friday's test is the last of six formal qualifying firings,
the redesigned booster already has been successfully used on two
shuttle launches Sept. 29 and Dec. 2. In both cases, the boosters
performed without a hitch.
   Raab said only five of the six scheduled test-firings, the last
of which was held Aug. 18, were required prior to launch.
   The final test is to determine how the rocket performs with
propellant cooled to 40 degrees Fahrenheit _ established by
engineers as the lowest operating temperature for the redesigned
booster, Raab said.
   NASA ordered the rocket redesigned after a presidential
commission blamed a faulty seal on one of the Challenger's boosters
for the spacecraft's Jan. 28, 1986, explosion that killed the seven
people aboard.
</TEXT>
