<HEAD>Baker Promises to Investigate Reports of Chemical Weapons in Angola</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Baker-Confirmation Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James A. Baker III, President-elect Bush's
choice to be secretary of state, promised on Tuesday to investigate
a senator's contention that Soviet chemical weapons have been
stockpiled by Cuban troops in Angola.
   Baker, answering questions at his Senate confirmation hearing,
responded to Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., who expressed concern about
the just-signed agreement mediated by the United States for the
pullout of Cuban troops from Angola.
   Helms said he was worried that the agreement would abandon Jonas
Savimbi, leader of the U.S.-backed Union for the Total Independence
of Angola (UNITA), to the mercies of the Cubans and Marxist allies
in the Angolan government.
   The senator said he had sent staff members to Angola to discuss
the pullout agreement with Savimbi.
   ``I have some concern that he wasn't consulted. I don't
understand that kind of mediation _ negotiation,'' Helms said.
   Helms said his staff members found that in three battles last
year the Cubans used poison gas against UNITA, paralyzing 300
soldiers and killing 120.
   He said the staff members brought back reports that ``tons of
poison gas have arrived in Angola in Soviet transports within the
past few months and have been stored.''
   Baker said he had not known about such a development, adding,
``All I can promise you to do is to look into it immediately.''
   In response to a question, Baker said the United States had not
obtained any commitment that the Cubans would abstain from attacking
Savimbi's forces during their seven-month pullout.
   Baker reiterated the pledge made by Bush of continuing U.S.
support for Savimbi.
