<HEAD>Hatcher Says Won't Appear By Thursday Deadline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUMBERTON, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indian activist Eddie Hatcher failed to
appear for arraignment Tuesday on kidnapping charges stemming from
the takeover of a newspaper last February.
   Robeson County Superior Court Juge Anthony Brannon gave Hatcher
until Thursday to surrender, but Hatcher said he wouldn't come to
court.
   ``I am not going back to Robeson County,'' Hatcher said in a
telephone interview from the Fort Hall Indian Reservation in Idaho.
``I have appeared before a tribal judge here and they will have to
go through the tribal court now to get me back.''
   Brannon said Hatcher would forfeit the $25,000 bond posted by the
National Council of Churches if he failed to appear by Thursday.
   Hatcher is charged with 14 counts of second-degree kidnapping in
the 10-hour takeover of The Robesonian newspaper offices.
   He and another man, Timothy Jacobs, both Tuscarora Indians from
Pembroke, N.C., allegedly held up to 20 people hostage while Hatcher
demanded an investigation into alleged corruption and drug
trafficking in local government.
   The siege ended when Gov. Jim Martin agreed to establish a task
force to investigate the allegations. He did so, but later said the
panel found only ``rumors and gossip.''
   Hatcher and Jacobs were indicted by a Robeson County grand jury
in December. The state charges were filed after the two were
acquitted Oct. 14 on federal hostage-taking and firearms charges.
   Jacobs left Robeson County shortly after the indictments were
issued. He fled to the Onondaga Indian reservation in New York, but
was arrested off the reservation and is in an extradition battle.
