<SECOND>AM-Stolen Animals,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snakes and Iguanas and Cockatoos, Oh My!</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINEOLA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Someone is stealing the pricey pets of Long
Island.
   Ten snakes, two iguanas and a $1,400 cockatoo have been snatched
from two pet shops in Nassau County, police said Tuesday. It was not
known if the thefts were related.
   One man was arrested in the cockatoo caper, but the bird, the
lizards and the snakes, as well as at least one other robber, were
at large.
   On Monday, police said, Diane Rafferty was working at the shop
called Birds of a Higher Feather in Mineola when two men entered.
She told police one of the men engaged her in conversation while the
other apparently took a white Soffin cockatoo.
   She said she noticed the bird was missing after the men left.
   When police arrived, she told them that the man who talked to her
had asked the location of another pet store a mile away. Police went
there and arrested Rudolph Montoya, 19, who fit the description of
the man who spoke with Ms. Rafferty.
   Montoya was charged with grand larceny.
   In Farmingdale, the owner of Paul's Exotic Pet Store said he
found the snakes and iguanas missing when he opened the store
Monday. All were believed to be non-poisonous, said Officer Richard
Scabilia.
   The reptiles cost a total of about $1,500.
