<FIRST>r a AM-Students-Bush     01-17 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Students-Bush,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Want Bush To Solve Drug Problem</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drugs seem to have replaced nuclear war as the
top concern of elementary school children.
   ``Please do something about the bad people who sell drugs to
little children. Put them in jail,'' pleaded a third-grader from
Rosedale, N.Y., in one of more than 60,000 letters written to
President-elect George Bush at the invitation of Scholastic News, a
classroom newsweekly read by 5 million students.
   Three-quarters of the letters written by the children in grades
three through six mentioned drugs as one of the country's biggest
problems, said Jeanne Krier, public relations director for
Scholastic News.
   Four years ago, the magazine's young readers advised President
Reagan that nuclear war was their top worry.
   ``Our young readers today are more concerned about drugs,
poverty, the homeless and pollution,'' said John Lent, Scholastic
News publisher.
   One fourth-grader from Harrisburg, Pa., wrote: ``I think the most
important issue in our country is drugs. It is killing people and
teen-agers and it is also interfering with our health. If you went
to the schools and educated the kids about drugs, it would help
solve all the problems.'
   Krier plans to send 25 letters to Bush along with a three-page
sampling of excerpts from others.
   A fifth-grader from McLean, Va., wrote: ``I think you should see
how much effect the war on drugs has on teen-agers. You should also
try to get the kids who stopped using drugs to encourage other
people to stop.''
   ``If anyone gets caught selling drugs, they should be put in
prison for five years _ child or adult,'' said a fifth-grader from
Pontiac, Ill.
   On poverty and the homeless, a fifth-grader from Atwater, Calif.,
wrote: ``There are a lot of people in this country without jobs and
people that sleep on park benches. America does not seem like a very
free country if we have people using garbage cans and boxes as a
home.''
   Other forums giving youngsters a chance to advise the
president-elect also showed social issues are primary concerns.
   Tips about caring for the homeless, helping Vietnam veterans and
feeding the world's starving people were in 900 letters sent to Bush
from elementary and middle school pupils in Columbus, Ohio.
   Products of the Election Day 1988 ``Tips for the President''
essay contest were presented to U.S. Rep. John Kasich for delivery
to the White House.
   Hattie White, 13, an eighth-grader at Hilltonia Alternative
Middle School, said she was glad the whales off of the Alaska coast
were freed, but, ``How many people will freeze to death without
shelter? Will you work as hard for the people as you did for the
whales?''
   Some kindergarten students in Chicago had more immediate concerns.
   ``If bad kids beat up good kids, the president should take them
to their moms,'' said Sarah.
   Perhaps the most enigmatic advice to Bush came from a boy named
Matt, who said: ``Be a woman, put sharks in cages and kill all bees
in the world.''
</TEXT>
