<FIRST>r i AM-Czechoslovakia     01-17 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia,0604</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Drive Crowds from Prague Square for Third Day</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East-West Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND PRINZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Czechoslovak police drove crowds from
Prague's main square with water cannons for a third day Tuesday,
although no protest was being held, and 14 activists may be
prosecuted, dissidents and witnesses said.
   Fourteen dissidents were detained Monday, including playwright
Vaclav Havel, whose works are banned.
   They had tried to lay flowers in Wenceslas Square to honor Jan
Palach, a 20-year-old student who burned himself alive 20 years ago
to protest the Soviet-led invasion that ended the liberal ``Prague
Spring'' in August 1968.
   A prosecutor told relatives Dana Nemcova, spokeswoman for the
human rights group Charter 77, and Sasha Vondra, a Charter 77
spokesman, would stay in custody for an unspecified period, a
dissident source said by telephone phone from Prague.
   Ms. Nemcova's son, David, who was married Saturday, also was
among the 14 arrested Monday along with Jana Sternova, a former
Charter 77 spokeswoman who met with President Reagan last year in
Washington.
   Emigre sources said privately that David Nemcova's wife Michaela
and Vondra's wife Martina were told their relatives would be charged
under Article 156, Section A, of the criminal code, on obstructing
the duty of a public official. The maximum jail sentence on
conviction is six months.
   Whether charges would be pressed against any or all of the 14 was
not clear, the informants said.
   Witnesses said police had at least four water cannons Tuesday and
sprayed people in the square indiscriminately.
   About two dozen vans of police rushed into the square in what
appeared to be a preventive measure, since no demonstration was
being conducted. Except for several hundred young people, most of
those in the square appeared to be people passing through on normal
daily business, the witnesses said.
   The witnesses, speaking by telephone from Prague, said people ran
from the square to keep from being drenched and it was quiet after
about two hours, with police patrolling constantly.
   CTK, the official Czechoslovak news agency, said 91 people were
detained Sunday at a rally of at least 5,000 people in Palach's
honor.
   An emigre source said 89 were released later Sunday, but a
dissident source in Prague quoted one of those freed as saying the
number detained appeared to be much higher than reported by the
agency.
   No official comment was available on the numbers of people
arrested or released. The home telephone of government spokesman
Miroslav Pavel was not answered Tuesday.
   An Associated Press reporter saw police beat several people at
the Sunday rally. At least one man was so badly hurt that other
demonstrators called for an ambulance.
   Several ambulances were seen rushing through the streets of
Prague on Sunday.
   Palach Press, an emigre publishing house in London, said a
59-year-old suffered a skull fracture.
   Jan Kavan of Palach Press said it was not clear from his source
whether the injury occurred Sunday or Monday, or whether the man was
a demonstrator or bystander.
   Also among the 14 is Jana Sternova, a former Charter 77
spokeswoman who met with President Reagan last year in Washington.
   After police cleared Wenceslas Square on Monday with tear gas and
water cannon, CTK carried a dispatch referring to ``groups of
anti-state elements, organized under the pretext of an anniversary
of Jan Palach's suicide,'' who had ``attempted to continue Sunday's
provocation.''
   ``The provocateurs disrupted public order with their aggressive
behavior even despite repeated appeals to disperse,'' the agency
said.
</TEXT>
