<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Wilson     01-17 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Wilson,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>Actor Trey Wilson Dies At Age 40</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trey Wilson, a character actor who appeared on
stage and screen in recent hits from ``Raising Arizona'' to ``Bull
Durham,'' has died of a cerebral hemorrhage. He was 40.
   Wilson, a native of Houston and graduate of the University of
Houston, died Monday at New York Hospital.
   Donna Massetti, spokeswoman for his manager, said Wilson was at
home in New York on Sunday when he complained of a headache, and
then lost consciousness.
   He was about to depart for New Orleans to play a role that was
written especially for him in ``Miller's Crossing,'' a new film by
Joel and Ethan Coen, the brothers responsible for ``Raising
Arizona.''
   In that film, Wilson played Nathan Arizona, the father of
quintuplets, one of whom is stolen by a childless couple. Wilson
also played the manager in ``Bull Durham''; an FBI boss in ``Married
to the Mob'; a wealthy Texan in ``Twins.''
   He also appeared in ``A Soldier's Story,'' ``F-X'' and ``The
House on Carroll Street.''
   Two other films _ ``Welcome Home'' and ``Miss Firecracker'' _
have not yet been released, along with the just-completed ``Great
Balls of Fire,'' the Jerry Lee Lewis story in which Wilson plays Sam
Phillips, owner of Sun Records.
   He also appeared on stage in ``The Front Page'' at Lincoln
Center, ``Custom of the Country'' at the Second Stage and ``The
Debutante Ball'' at Manhattan Theater Club.
   His Broadway credits include ``Peter Pan,'' ``Tintypes,'' ``The
First'' and ``Foxfire.''
   He is survived by his wife, Judy Blye; a stepson, Eric Meadows of
New York; his mother, Mitzie Norman; and his stepfather, W.F.
Norman, both of Houston.
   Burial was scheduled for Saturday in Houston. A memorial service
would be held later in New York, Ms. Massetti said.
</TEXT>
