<FIRST>r i AM-China-Fresco     01-17 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Fresco,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cave Paintings Stolen From Famous Buddhist Shrine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thieves cut a 700-year-old fresco from the wall of
one of northwestern China's famous Dunhuang caves, one-time Buddhist
shrines filled with magnificent paintings and statues, the People's
Daily reported Tuesday.
   The theft, from a cave that was not open to the public, was
discovered Friday, the paper said. The thieves cut the
10-square-foot fresco into five pieces for easy removal, but one
piece broke, the report said.
   The report did not describe the painting or comment on how the
thieves got into the cave. It said a fresco also was stolen from
Dunhuang in 1986 and the thieves have not been found.
   In the fourth century, monks who first introduced Buddhism to
China from India opened cave temples in Dunhuang, along ancient
trading routes in what is now Gansu province. Over the next few
centuries, hundreds of caves were dug out of the arid hillsides of
Dunhuang and their walls covered with religious murals.
   When the trade routes fell into disuse, the caves were abandoned
and forgotten. They were rediscovered in about 1900 and found to
contain thousands of priceless manuscripts and terra cotta statues.
   Only a few dozen of the caves are open to the public now as a
tourist attraction.
   Millions of dollars' worth of ancient artifacts are smuggled out
of China each year, officials estimate, most through Hong Kong.
</TEXT>
