<FIRST>r i AM-Shultz     01-17 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shultz,0628</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shultz Chides East Europeans on Human Rights</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz
criticized four East European nations Tuesday about human rights and
said ``dark areas remain'' in the Soviet Union, but an aide reported
Kremlin assurances of improvement.
   A senior State Department official said a ranking member of the
Soviet delegation to the 35-nation Helsinki review conference told
him during Shultz's last mission abroad ``the whole process will
move ahead'' during the Bush administration.
   According to the official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
the Soviet delegate said the cases of 20 more Jews who want to
emigrate have been resolved and relatives of citizens who apply for
exit visas no longer will be urged to object.
   Family objections have been used by Soviet authorities to reject
applications.
   ``I really believe them,'' the U.S. official said. ``All these
things are being volunteered.''
   Shultz praised the Soviets and two East European allies, Poland
and Hungary, for taking steps to implement the 1975 Helsinki
agreements on European security and cooperation.
   He called Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev ``strong and
creative,'' and credited him with improving human rights.
   Signed by the United States, the Soviet Union, Canada and all
European nations except Albania, the Helsinki agreemenrference
late last year.
   At a news conference, he called for the destruction of the Berlin
Wall, built in 1961 to keep East Germans from fleeing to the West.
   ``There has been tremendous progress but the Berlin Wall remains,
as a symbol of the division of Europe, an inhumane structure and
something that functionally separates people,'' he said. ``So, in
the end that sort of thing has to come down.''
   Shultz criticized Romania for reserving the right to select which
provisions of Sunday's declaration it would observe, although he had
not done so in his address.
   Romania told delegates Sunday, before adoption of the final
document, that it would not honor provisions on greater religious
freedom and emigration.
   One provision of the document is a mandate for new negotiations,
scheduled to begin March 9, on reducing conventional military forces
in Europe.
   ``I have some genuine optimism about the prospects,'' Shultz said.
   His last trip as secretary of state was one of the shortest. He
was in Vienna for 32 hours, then flew home to prepare to relinquish
his office Friday.
</TEXT>
