<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Korea-Intelligence     01-17 0150</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Korea-Intelligence,0153</SECOND>
<HEAD>Law To Be Revised To Ensure Security Agency's Political Neutrality</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A revised law will prevent the main
government intelligence agency from engaging in political activity,
the agency's chief said Tuesday.
   Park Seh-jik, director of the Agency for National Security, told
a National Assembly subcommittee the government would add a clause
to the law governing the agency that would ban political activity.
But he rejected an opposition demand that the agency's activity be
limited to gathering information on North Korea and other foreign
countries.
   ``In our reality, it is difficult to separate domestic
intelligence from that on North Korea,'' he said.
   The Agency for National Security, formerly the Korea Central
Intelligence Agency, has been a target of public criticism for its
active involvement in politics.
   Political neutrality for the agency was a campaign pledge of
President Roh Tae-woo in the December 1987 elections.
</TEXT>
