<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 1928EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-TeenShooting     01-17 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Teen Shooting,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Chase Armed Teen Through High School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police chased a 16-year-old boy armed with a
pistol through the halls and across the roof of a high school
Tuesday after the boy fired two shots at school employees,
authorities said.
   ``There were no injuries and no shots were fired in the school,''
Officer John Bryson said.
   A security guard at Kennedy High School noticed the boy, armed
with a .38-caliber handgun, in the school at noon, school
spokeswoman Tina Parent said. The guard and Assistant Principal
Richard Jackson chased the boy from the school and into Bayou St.
John across the street, she said.
   When cornered in the bayou, Parent said the boy drew a gun and
fired at Jackson and the security guard.
   Police joined school security in chasing the teen-ager, who ran
back into school and through the halls with the gun, Bryson said.
   At one point, Bryson said, the boy pointed the weapon at a police
sergeant who also had his weapon drawn. ``The sergeant ordered him
to drop it, but he ran away instead,'' Bryson said.
   The boy climbed through a vent and onto the top of the
three-story building, running back and forth across the roof before
climbing down and being cornered outside the gymnasium, Bryson said.
   ``Police ordered him to drop the weapon that was pointed at
several officers. After about 10 seconds he did so,'' Bryson said.
   The boy, who was not identified by name, is a student at another
school, and police said they did not know why he was at Kennedy.
   The boy was booked on several counts including attempted murder,
Bryson said.
   Parent said students were kept in their rooms during the incident
and classes continued.
</TEXT>
