<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 2123EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SoccerRiotTrial     01-17 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soccer Riot Trial,0374</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Demands Conviction of State Police Officials</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prosecutor in the Heysel soccer
riots trial demanded Tuesday that two Belgian police officials be
convicted for failing to maintain security at the 1985 European
Champions' Cup match.
   Prosecutor Pierre Erauw was more lenient with two city officials
and two top European soccer officials who were sued by relatives of
the 39 people who died and hundreds who were injured in Europe's
worst soccer riot. They should not be punished, he said.
   On Wednesday Erauw is expected to call for severe sentences for
26 British suspects who face up to 10 years imprisonment on
involuntary manslaughter charges of instigating the riot before the
May 29, 1985, final between FC Liverpool and Juventus Turin.
   Twenty of the 26 Britons returned to Belgium this week for a
mandatory appearance during Erauw's final arguments. They probably
will be allowed to return home to await the end of the trial,
expected in March.
   On Monday, Erauw said Albert Roosens, secretary-general of the
Belgian soccer federation at the time of the tragedy, should be
blamed for poorly organizing the match.
   On Tuesday, he accused state police officials Johan Mahieu and
Michel Kensier of poorly organizing security at the match and not
taking sufficient action to halt the riot. He was particularly harsh
on Mahieu, who was responsible for security in the stands where the
riots occurred.
   ``Whatever, punish Kensier and Mahieu for what they did, or
rather for what they didn't do,'' Erauw told the court.
   But he did not call for punishment of Herve Brouhon, mayor of
Brussels city, which owns the stadium. Jacques Georges and Hans
Bangerter, chairman and secretary-general of the ruling body of
European soccer also were not accused.
   Just before the match at the Heysel Stadium, British fans charged
into an adjacent stand of Italian supporters, and 39 people were
trampled to death in the ensuing panic. Almost 500 were injured.
   Erauw is expected to end his final arguments Wednesday.
   The British suspects were extradited to Belgium after being
identified from video footage and photographs. The extradition was
exceptional and indicated Britain's resolve to stamp out soccer
hooliganism.
</TEXT>
