<FIRST>u i AM-Yugoslavia     01-17 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Newspaper Says Leadership Can't Control Country</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A deeply divided communist leadership
is unable to control the country's economic and political crisis,
and further social upheaval is imminent, a state-run newspaper said
Tuesday.
   ``The following is clear: this country is not being run by
anyone,'' the leading official daily Borba said in an editorial.
   ``More precisely, it is being run by divided, dangerously
antagonistic republican leaderships with different ideological
concepts, creating chaos in politics and economy,'' Borba said.
   Meanwhile, the ruling 23-member Politburo announced that on Jan.
25 the policy-setting Central Committee will ``discuss the political
situation in the country, relations within the party and the
functioning and responsibility of the Central Committee and its
Politburo.''
   The wording of the announcement, carried by the state Tanjug news
agency, indicated the session might result in leadership changes.
   In an apparent attempt to bridge the growing rifts between
Yugoslavia's republics, the nine-member state presidency on Tuesday
appealed to opposing leaderships ``to settle their differences by
dialogue.''
   Public discontent after years of rising inflation and falling
living standards, Borba said, ``is turning into a full-scale
revolt,'' threatening the very foundations of the communist system.
   ``The crisis is so deep that it can, at any moment, cause even
greater social upheavals, which would force the country into a
completely unwanted direction,'' the paper said.
   The most liberal republics of Slovenia and Croatia favor
political pluralism and more democracy as a solution to the
country's woes, but southern regions led by the country's largest
republic of Serbia advocate more central control and a greater role
for the Communist Party.
   The choice of a new premier later this week may cause yet another
sharp clash between the country's liberal and conservative regions.
   Tanjug said the worsening crisis calls for an emergency party
congress meeting to resolve conflicts and elect a completly new
leadership.
   ``It is better to have an extraordinary congress than to be
forced to introduce extraordinary measures,'' Tanjug said.
   The country's six republics and two provinces have wide autonomy
in political and economic affairs, creating eight virtually
self-ruling states that must reach consensus when passing important
new laws. That often leads to watered-down compromises.
   Yugoslavia is faced with confusion sometimes bordering on
``political chaos,'' Borba said.
   Unable to control the economic crisis, the federal Cabinet
resigned last month, leaving the country virtually ungoverned, the
Vecernje Novosti daily said.
   In addition, under pressure from hard-line Serbian Communist
Party chief Slobodan Milosevic and other Serbian leaders, the party
elites in the provinces of Vojvodina and Kosovo and in the republic
of Montenegro have been ousted and only interim leaderships have
been left in charge of the regions.
   The ouster of the entire Montenegrin ruling elite came after more
than 120,000 people demonstrated last week in Titograd, the region's
capital, demanding the leadership step down because of the
disastrous state of the republic's economy.
   The action was applauded by Serbia's state-controlled media.
   But the mass demonstrations in Montenegro were denounced in the
liberal northern republics of Slovenia and Croatia and described as
being covertly ``orchestrated'' by followers of Milosevic, who is
alleged to have federal leadership ambitions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
