<FIRST>u w AM-Reagan-Pardons 1stLd-Writethru a0676 01-17 0723</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reagan-Pardons, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0676,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reagan Faces Decisions on Pardon Pleas</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: First 4 grafs new with pardon grants; picks up 2nd graf pvs,
``It's certainly, but inserts 2 grafs further after 9th graf pvs, Fitzwater
said. Inserts byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan has approved 10 pardons in
recent days, but has not yet decided whether to grant such relief to
newspaper heiress Patty Hearst Shaw and industrialist Armand Hammer,
an administration source said Tuesday.
   The source, discussing the subject on the grounds of anonymity,
said ``there are no big names'' among those for whom Reagan had
approved pardons. But the source would not identify the recipients.
   ``There may be as many as a couple of dozen that are before the
president,'' the official said, adding that consideration of pardons
for Shaw and Hammer is ``well along in the process.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater, questioned earlier in the
day about the status of the Shaw case, said only that Reagan was
considering several pardon requests.
   ``It's certainly possible that a decision could be made before he
leaves,'' he said when asked whether Reagan would grant pardons
before he leaves office Friday.
   Although Fitzwater would not identify who had applied for
pardons, Reagan himself told reporters Sunday that he had asked
staff aides ``to look into the question'' of a possible pardon for
newspaper heiress Patty Hearst.
   Ms. Hearst was sentenced to seven years in a federal prison for
her role in the 1974 armed robbery of a San Francisco bank.
   She now is married and living in Connecticut under the married
name of Patty Hearst Shaw.
   There's also a longstanding pardon request by industrialist
Armand Hammer, the head of Occidental Petroleum Corp., who was fined
$3,000 and placed on a year's probation in connection with his
guilty plea to three misdemeanor charges in connection with the
Watergate scandal of the early 1970s.
   Fitzwater said that several pardon requests, with recommendations
for action, had been sent to the White House by the Justice
Department in recent months. He wouldn't say how many are pending at
the White House.
   ``I won't comment on any individuals that are in this category,''
the spokesman said. ``Some of them are recent. Some of them, we've
had for weeks or for months.''
   Fitzwater said he had been told that Reagan ``doesn't have any of
these on his desk'' at this time.
   The administration official who spoke on the condition of
anonymity said that the pardon approvals ``tend to trickle over. ...
We got 10 back from the White House, approved, last week.''
   Under routine procedure, the Justice Department's pardons office
would contact the person getting a pardon or that person's attorney,
he said.
   Returning from the presidential retreat at Camp David, Md.,
Sunday, Reagan was asked by reporters if he was going to grant a
last-minute pardon to Shaw.
   ``All of this thing, I have asked everybody to look into this for
me,'' he replied.
   Shaw, granddaughter of newspaper tycoon William Randolph Hearst,
last August quietly asked for a pardon for her role in the robbery.
She has maintained she was brainwashed by the radical Symbionese
Liberation Army, a group of self-styled revolutionaries who abducted
her in Berkeley, Calif., in February 1974 and orchestrated the bank
heist.
   Shaw was convicted of charges connected with the robbery and
sentenced to seven years in prison. Her sentence was commuted by
Reagan's predecessor, President Carter and she was released from
prison on Feb. 1, 1979, after serving 23 months.
   In an interview Monday with The Advocate of Stamford at her
Westport, Conn., home, Shaw was asked whether she thought Reagan's
expression of interest in her case might result in a pardon.
   ``I don't know,'' she replied. ``It's a little premature for
anything like that. If he (Reagan) doesn't approve it, it would go
to the next administration.''
   Shaw, now 34, lives in Westport with her husband and two
daughters.
   Reagan has steadfastly insisted that he is not considering a
pardon for former National Security Council aide Oliver L. North,
who is scheduled to go on trial late this month on a variety of
charges related to the Iran-Contra affair. A federal judge late last
week granted a motion by independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh
asking that two central charges against North be dropped.
</TEXT>
