<FIRST>r w AM-Reagan-Parr     01-17 0144</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reagan-Parr,130</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-Agent In Line For Advisory Committee Appointment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan intends to appoint Jerry S.
Parr, a former member of his Secret Service detail, as a member of
the advisory committee of the White House Conference on Library and
Information Services, the White House announced Tuesday.
   Parr, now the president of a private security consulting firm,
was the agent who pushed Reagan into his limousine after he was been
shot by John W. Hinckley on March 30, 1981.
   In recent weeks, the president has given key staff aides a number
of appointments to various government boards and commissions.
   Parr was credited with saving Reagan's life by ordering the
president's driver to take him to George Washington University
Hospital. Only after Reagan was examined by physicians did they
discover that Hinckley's bullet had lodged within inches of the
president's heart.
</TEXT>
