<DOCNO> AP890117-0170 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 1746EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Quayle Bjt   01-17 0751</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quayle, Bjt,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayle Gives Unqualified Support To Controversial Pay Raise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President-elect Dan Quayle gave
unqualified support Tuesday to the controversial 50 percent pay
raise for Congress, federal judges and the Cabinet, acknowledging
however, ``I know it's a lot.''
   Quayle made his comments in an interview with The Associated
Press as a Washington Post poll showed that eight out of 10
Americans oppose raising the salaries of members of Congress from
$89,500 to $135,000.
   Quayle, who served four years in the House and eight years in the
Senate, appeared to take a somewhat different stand than his new
boss, President-elect Bush. On Jan. 6, Bush said he supported
President Reagan's endorsement of the 50 percent pay raise but added
he may take another look at the issue after becoming president.
   Bush, asked if the nation could afford such a big pay increase at
a time of huge deficits, said, ``Well, I don't know whether we can
afford anything than to get this deficit under control.''
   Quayle did not qualify his endorsement. ``I support President
Reagan's decision to send that up to Capitol Hill. I know it's a lot
but I think he thought long and hard. I support his decision.''
   The pay raise plan will take effect next month unless Congress
vetoes or modifies it.
   Under the proposal that Reagan endorsed, the president's salary
would rise from $200,000 to $350,000 and the vice president's would
go up from $115,000 to $175,000. However, the Constitution prevents
Bush from getting an increase for the term to which he was elected,
and presumably Quayle would be covered by the same prohibition.
   Quayle will be sworn in with Bush in ceremonies Friday. Quayle
said he will model his job after the way Bush performed it, refusing
to discuss publicly what they talk about in private. He said he
would not speak up in Cabinet meetings or when other people are
present, giving his views to Bush alone.
   ``He's going to rely on me for advice on things that he thinks
are important,'' Quayle said.
   He said everyone he's talked to who has been vice president _
including Bush _ said, ``don't get bogged down with trivia. Don't
get tied down with line-item assignments early on. There's always
going to be someone who says, `Well, this issue has come up, what
shall we do with it?' Someone will suggest, `Well, let's give it to
the vice president.'''
   Quayle said the assignments he takes on ``will be of substance,
stature and of importance to the president, and those assignments
will be forthcoming.''
   He said one thing he wants to do is to try to change the
stereotype image of the Republican Party as insensitive to the
plight of the poor and minorities. He said he would travel to inner
city neighborhoods, ``to hear them out, to get a feel, a
sensitivity'' about their problems.
   Acknowleding that the budget deficit will prevent new spending
programs, Quayle said, ``money's not everything.'' He said he would
use the tools of leadership and persuasion.
   Bush administration officials say the key foreign policy issue
facing the new president will be devising a strategy for dealing
with a Soviet Union that is rapidly changing under Mikhail Gorbachev.
   ``My personal viewpoint is that Gorbachev is in a much stronger
position than (seen by) the conventional wisdom in this country,''
Quayle said. ``I think there are a lot of skeptics in this country
about him. I think he's in a very strong position.
   ``He's consolidated power much quicker than any other Soviet
general secretary. He's way ahead of (the late Leonid) Brezhnev. He
(Gorbachev) consolidated power in three years which took Brezhnev 10
years to do.''
   Quayle said he had not met Gorbachev but considers him ``a very
effective, capable leader (who) has an opportunity to do something.''
   Talking about Gorbachev's twin programs of ``glasnost,'' or
openness, and ``perestroika,'' or economic reform, Quayle said, ``I
think glasnost is for real. I happen to think that the Soviet
society today is more open than it has been in the past, that you
read publications today that you would not have read five years ago,
three years ago, 10 years ago. ...
   ``Perestroika on the other hand I'm personally a bit more
skeptical of. I think perestroika _ anytime someone tries to reform
the system, particularly that system, is just a consolidation of
power. I think Gorbachev's been very effective in the consolidation
of power.''
</TEXT>
