<FIRST>r w AM-US-Arafat     01-17 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Arafat,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arab Americans Invited To State Department To Discuss Arafat Visa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Arab American officials have been invited
to the State Department to discuss the possibility of granting a
visa for PLO chief Yasser Arafat to visit the United States, an
Arab-American group said Tuesday.
   The president of the American-Arab Anti-Discrimination Committee,
Abdeen Jabara, and the chairman of its board, former senator James
Abourezk, were asked to meet next Monday with an aide to Assistant
Secretary of State Richard Murphy, said the group's spokesman, Faris
Bouhafa. The aide, Ned Walker, deals in Middle Eastern affairs.
   ``The stated purpose of the invitation was to discuss an Arafat
visa,'' Bouhafa said.
   State Department officials confirmed that such a meeting had been
set to discuss the results of Abourezk's meeting with Arafat last
week, but declined to discuss the question of a visa for the PLO
chief.
   Arafat last Friday accepted an invitation from Abourezk to
address the ADC's annual convention on April 13 in Washington, the
ADC said. Abourezk met in Tunis, the PLO headquarters, with Arafat
as well as with the PLO's executive committee.
   He also met with U.S. Ambassador Robert H. Pelletreau, who has
been conducting a newly launched dialogue with the PLO.
   The State Department and the White House said Tuesday they had
not received any applicationfrom Arafat for a visa. If it comes,
said White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater, ``we will consider it
very carefully. We won't say in advance what we'll do.''
   Secretary of State George Shultz rejected a visa request from
Arafat last November, citing concerns about the PLO's involvement in
terrorism. But subsequently, President Reagan authorized a dialogue
with the PLO when it recognized Israel's right to exist and
renounced the use of terrorism.
   Arafat has visited the United States only once _ in 1974 to
address the United Nations. His visa at the time was limited to New
York.
   Washington's prestigious National Press Club last year extended
an invitation to Arafat to address the forum, but the PLO said it
could not obtain a visa for him to come to Washington.
</TEXT>
