<HEAD>Shultz, Mansfield to Receive Presidential Medals</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 2 grafs with additional presentations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan will award the Presidential
Medal of Freedom to former U.S. Ambassador Mike Mansfield and to
Secretary of State George Shultz, a White House spokesman said
Tuesday.
   Reagan will present the awards at a White House luncheon on
Wednesday, said Marlin Fitzwater.
   Mansfield, recently retired as ambassador to Japan, and Shultz
``are being honored for their many significant contributions in the
fields of national interests, public services and world peace to the
United States,'' Fitzwater said.
   The medal is the highest civilian award of the U.S. government
and is awarded to people who have made ``especially meritorious
contributions,'' Fitzwater said.
   The president will also award the Presidential Citizens Medal to
three Republican members of Congress on Wednesday, the spokesman
added.
   Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole of Kansas, House Minority Leader
Robert Michel of Illinois and Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., will
receive the medals Wednesday morning at a White House ceremony,
Fitzwater said.
   The medals recognize citizens ``who have performed exemplary
deeds of service for their country or their fellow citizens,''
Fitzwater said.
   Later in the day, the White House released the following list of
citizens who will also receive the Citizens Award, including
Reagan's chief of staff Kenneth Duberstein, his national security
advisor Colin Powell and actor Charton Heston. The others include:
   David Abshire; Richard Armitage; Arnold O. Beckman; James Scott
Brady; William F. Buckley; Chester A. Crocker; Arthur B. Culvahouse,
Jr.; Edwin J. Feulner, Jr.; Max Fisher; Malcom S. Forbes; Donald R.
Fortier (posthumously); Dorothy I. Height; John S. Herrington; Don
Hodel; Herman Kahn (posthumously); Max M. Kampelman; Russell Kirk;
John O. Marsh, Jr.; Ann McLaughlin; Samuel R. Pierce, Jr.; Arnold
Lewis Raphel (posthumously); Rozanne L. Ridgway; Edward L. Rowny;
Stuart K. Spencer; William H. Taft, IV; Edward Teller; Richard H.
Truly; Armando Valladares; Vernon A. Walters; John C. Whitehead;
Charles Z. Wick; Joseph R. Wright, Jr.
