<DOCNO> AP890117-0180 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 2157EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-SBA     01-17 0110</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-SBA,110</SECOND>
<HEAD>Engleiter Likely to Head SBA</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Susan Engeleiter, a Wisconsin legislator and
former Republican Senate candidate, is the leading contender to head
the Small Business Administration, sources close to President-elect
Bush said Tuesday.
   Ms. Engeleiter, 36, of Brookfield, Wis., was defeated last
November by Democrat Herbert Kohl in the race for the Senate seat
vacated by former Sen. William Proxmire.
   An attorney and former teacher, she has been a member of the
Wisconsin state Senate since 1980 and is that chamber's former
minority leader.
   The SBA administrator's job is expected to be among a series of
sub-Cabinet appointments to be announced by Bush on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
