<FIRST>u a AM-AdmissionQuotas     01-17 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Admission Quotas,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>Education Department Investigating Whether Harvard, UCLA Use Asian
Quotas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal investigators are exploring whether Harvard
and the University of California at Los Angeles use illegal quotas
to restrict the number of Asian-American students they admit, an
official said Tuesday.
   The U.S. Department of Education has been collecting and
analyzing statistical information on admissions at the two schools
since last fall, said department spokesman Mahlon G. Anderson.
   He declined to say what sparked the probe. No conclusions have
been reached, he said.
   Both Harvard and UCLA deny using quotas for any ethnic groups,
and both schools point to a significant rise in enrollment of
Asian-American students.
   At UCLA, Asian-Americans make up 22.9 percent of the freshman
class, up from 17.8 percent in 1980. At Harvard, the number of
Asian-American freshmen roughly tripled over the past decade, from
4.8 percent in 1978 to 14.2 percent this year.
   By comparison, the U.S. population is only about 2 percent Asian.
However, Education Department officials say Asian-Americans tend to
be high academic achievers and have been applying to top colleges
and universities in rising numbers.
   ``The real issue is not whether the number of Asian students is
going up, but what percentage of qualified applicants is being
accepted,'' said Frederick H. Dow, director of the Asian-American
Resource Workshop, a non-profit educational group in Boston.
   Harvard, for example, acknowledged last year that over the past
decade it had admitted an average of 17 percent of all white
applicants, but 13.3 percent of Asians applicants.
   Anderson said the Education Department will review the data and
send investigators to question officials on both campuses, probably
before the end of the current school year.
   ``Statistics alone don't always tell the story,'' he said. ``...
When you talk to admissions officers, you understand there may be
non-discriminatory policies that are driving the data and creating
certain patterns.''
   William Fitzsimmons, Harvard's director of admissions, said
Asians tend to be slightly stronger than whites on academic criteria
and slightly weaker on extracurricular activities, which can count
against them because Harvard seeks students with diverse talents,
such as music, art and leadership.
   In addition, he said, relatively few Asians in the applicant pool
are children of alumni or prospective varsity athletes. ``When all
those factors are taken into account, the difference in admission
rates for the two groups disappears,'' he said.
   Eva Lum, a Harvard senior and co-president of the Asian-American
Association on campus, said Harvard has had Asian students working
in the admissions office to recruit Asian-Americans, especially from
low-income families, for four years.
   ``It would be counterproductive to do that and impose quotas at
the same time,'' she said.
   UCLA stopped qualifying Asian-Americans for affirmative action
when it became clear that they were overrepresented, not
underrepresented, in proportion to population, said Thomas Lifka, an
assistant vice chancellor responsible for admissions.
   Lifka said 35 percent of Asian applicants were admitted in 1988,
compared with 32 percent of whites.
   ``We are convinced that if the Department of Education looks at
the data carefully ... they will conclude that there is no
discrimination.''
   If the department determines a college or university
discriminates on the basis of race or ethnicity, it can block
federal grants and guaranteed student loans which amount to hundreds
of millions of dollars for major schools.
   But Anderson said the schools are first given an opportunity to
change their disputed practices, and most do so.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
