<FIRST>r a AM-People SUB a0639 01-17 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People, SUB, a0639,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS the BELLINGHAM, Wash.-dated 5th item to recast lead and
fix typo in 4th graf.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELLINGHAM, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Linda Marchiano, known as Linda Lovelace
when she appeared in ``Deep Throat'' and other hard-core sex films,
is supporting a local anti-pornography law facing a federal
challenge.
   Marchiano has claimed in her book ``Ordeal'' that she suffered 2{
years of physical, sexual and mental abuse while being coerced into
performing sex acts and appearing in sex films.
   The Bellingham law that Ms. Marchiano supports says pornography
violates the civil rights of women when it portrays them as
dehumanized sexual objects. It differs from many anti-pornography
statutes in that it sets up civil remedies instead of criminal
penalties.
   The law is being challenged by a local bookstore, three
Bellingham residents and others who argue that it is vaguely written
and would have an overly broad impact on work protected by the First
Amendment.
   In a Jan. 6 affidavit, Ms. Marchiano said she wants to file a
lawsuit in Whatcom County seeking damages and an injunction against
any showing of her films there.
   ``Every time someone watches those films, they are watching me
being raped,'' Ms. Marchiano's affidavit said. ``Every time I am
recognized from those films, I am violated again.''
   In the hope of preserving her chance to file a lawsuit in
Bellingham, Ms. Marchiano, a New York state resident, is asking U.S.
District Judge Carolyn Dimmick to let her join the defendants in the
federal court lawsuit.
</TEXT>
