<FIRST>r i AM-Salvador     01-17 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Attack In Northern Province</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas Tuesday
launched coordinated attacks on military positions in six northern
towns, the armed forces and the rebels reported.
   The armed forces said three rebels were killed and three soldiers
wounded in the battles before dawn in the northern province of
Chalatenango. The guerrillas said they caused 25 casualties among
army troops, but did not specify the number of dead and wounded.
   The rebels, who commented on the clandestine Radio Farbundo
Marti, did not mention their own losses. The radio, like the
Marxist-led Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front that has been
battling the U.S.-backed government for nine years, is named for a
1930s revolutionary.
   The armed forces press office, as well as the clandestine
guerrilla radio, reported fighting in and around the towns of Dulce
Nombre de Maria, El Refugio, La Laguna, San Ignacio and San Miguel
de Mercedes. The rebels also staged what the army called
``harassment'' attacks on positions around the 4th Infantry Brigade
headquarters at El Paraiso, 28 miles north of San Salvador, the
capital.
   The insurgents said the coordinated attacks were part of an
operation called ``In response to repression, the people and
militias prepare the insurrection.''
   Rebel forces also blew up three utility posts near Apopa, seven
miles north of the capital, causing temporary blackouts in the
capital and some northern sectors of the country.
</TEXT>
