<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     01-17 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>High Winds in West, Some Flooding in South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Winds gusted to 90 mph in the Colorado Rockies on Tuesday, while
some flooding was reported in Arkansas.
   Morning winds gusted to 63 mph near Denver, 65 mph at Ames
Monument, Wyo., 69 mph at Squaw Mountain, Colo., and 90 mph just
south of Rollinsville, Colo.
   Snow showers continued in northern New York and Vermont into New
Hampshire. Snow, with blowing and drifting snow, fell over eastern
Upper Michigan and northern Lower Michigan, extending to the
northern half of Minnesota.
   A few rivers were flooding or threatening to flood. The Angelina
River in eastern Texas was expected to crest near Lufkin. Lowland
flooding continued along the Ouachita River at Camden, Ark., and
along the Cache River near Patterson, Ark. The St. Francis River at
Lake City, Ark., was more than 3 feet over its banks, but the river
level was falling.
   West Palm Beach, Fla., tied a record high for the date of 85
degrees. Des Moines, Iowa, reached 56 degrees to break its high
temperature record for the date.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 1 degree
above zero at Gunnison, Colo., to 82 degrees at Fort Myers, Fla.,
Miami and West Palm Beach, Fla. The low temperature for the nation
Tuesday morning was 27 degrees below zero at Gunnison, Colo.
   For Wednesday, the forecast called for snow squalls over the
lower Great Lakes, northern Indiana, lower Michigan and eastern
Upper Michigan. Rain was expected to be scattered along the Texas
Gulf Coast. Snow showers over northwest Montana were to turn into
rain in the lower elevations and reach across the northern Pacific
coast. Winds were to be strong and gusty over the northern Rockies.
   High temperatures were expected to be near 20 degrees over
northern Maine; in the 20s over Upper Michigan, northern Minnesota,
eastern North Dakota and the central Rockies; in the 30s and 40s
from southern Maine across Maryland, the northern Appalachians, the
lower Ohio Valley, the remainder of the Great Lakes, southern
Minnesota to northern Missouri, the remainder of North Dakota across
northern Kansas and the upper Missouri Valley, over the remainder of
the Rockies, through the plateau and the northern Pacific coast; in
the 70s over much of the Florida Peninsula, the lower Texas Gulf
Coast and from southern Arizona across southwest California. High
temperatures over much of the remainder of the nation were to be
generally in the 50s and 60s.
</TEXT>
