<FIRST>u i AM-Poland-Opposition     01-17 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Opposition,0631</SECOND>
<HEAD>Solidarity Ready to Resume Legal Activity</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a small apartment about a mile from
Communist Party headquarters in Warsaw, two excited Solidarity
activists tuned into the latest TV reports of a party meeting they
believed would result in a decision to legalize the banned labor
federation.
   Rarely have the long speeches at a Central Committee plenum
commanded such close attention from Solidarity, which for seven
years has tried the party's patience by refusing to abandon the
fight for legal existence.
   ``Are they registering Solidarity yet?'' yelled Jan Litynski,
spokesman for the Warsaw region of Solidarity, to former underground
Solidarity leader Zbigniew Bujak.
   Bujak had just flipped on the television switch in another room
on the first day of the party debate on the future of Solidarity. He
did not reply.
   The answer was not immediately forthcoming as party members
heatedly debated for hours on Monday and Tuesday over a move to
legalize Solidarity.
   The party had reason to be nervous. In 1980-81, during
Solidarity's legal existence, an estimated 1 million party members
joined the independent union movement. Thousands more turned in
their party cards in disgust when Poland's leader, Gen. Wojciech
Jaruzelski, imposed martial law on Dec. 13, 1981.
   But on Tuesday Prime Minister Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski urged the
party to legalize the banned union on condition that it be ``a
partner,'' not an opponent that would ``pull the country into
anarchy.''
   Rakowski had vigorously defended the martial law decision in the
early 1980s.
   The reversal in policy arises from the party's failure to
eradicate Solidarity after the martial law crackdown and reflects
the authorities' need to gain support from society to push through a
program of radical economic reform.
   ``They (party leaders) are doing this because they realize they
have to and it was obvious they had to,'' said Litynski, a veteran
opposition activist who advised striking miners during Poland's
worst labor unrest in seven years last August.
   Although the shift in the party's attitude is welcome, some
Solidarity activists believe the union must proceed with caution
because the change results from necessity rather than good will.
   ``The authorities will do whatever that have to do to stay on
top. Let's wait and see what they have to say and read the fine
print carefully,'' said Maciej Jankowski, a Solidarity leader at
Warsaw University.
   Solidarity activists do not foresee a return to the heady days of
1980-81, when union work was a round-the-clock passion for many. But
they acknowledge that a return of legal existence would change their
lives.
   ``It would be a real tragedy for my family. I don't have any
children now and I won't have time for that with all my union
activities,'' said Bujak, who first drew national attention when he
became leader of Solidarity's Warsaw region in 1980 at the age of 26.
   Litynski, who has long dreamed of visiting the United States,
believes he may have to postpone any visit if Solidarity is
legalized.
   For Jankowski, regulation of the labor federation's status means
he would be able to focus on solving other problems.
   Jankowski spent Tuesday afternoon taking part in a rally at
Warsaw University in support of legalizing the Independent Students'
Union and Solidarity.
   While Solidarity is eager to resume its activities legally, that
status poses challenges to union leaders such as how to organize the
labor federation and how to achieve economic reform.
   But a return to legal existence would mean that many could
finally emerge from the shadows of underground publishing and from
church basement meetings into a more normal way of participating in
public life.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
