<FIRST>u a AM-TurnpikeGunbattle 1stLd-Writethru a0644 01-17 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turnpike Gunbattle, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0644,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gunfire Erupts on Turnpike; One Dead, One Arrested, One Sought</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES thruout with details of scuffle, ID of trooper, quotes,
CORRECTS plates to North Carolina sted South. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TODD RICHISSIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WOODBRIDGE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A passenger of a car pulled over for
speeding on the New Jersey Turnpike was shot and killed Tuesday in a
scuffle with a state trooper, authorities said.
   The driver of the car was arrested, and a second passenger was
being sought by state and local police on foot and in helicopters,
said state police spokesman Capt. Thomas Gallagher.
   Trooper Robert K. Henig, 26, pulled over a luxury car with North
Carolina license plates about 12:30 p.m. because it was speeding,
Gallagher said.
   Henig told one of the passengers to leave the car and asked for
his identification. While the man searched his pockets, Henig
spotted what he believed to be a small bag of marijuana inside, the
spokesman said.
   The man then pushed Henig down and ran toward a marshy highway
median, Gallagher said. Henig caught the man, subdued him and was
putting his gun into his holster when the man kicked him, he said.
   ``There were a number of shots fired,'' said Gallagher. ``When
the weapon was turned toward the trooper, a shot was fired. He then
turned the gun on the suspect and fired.''
   Shortly afterwards, a car was stolen from a restaurant parking
lot less than a half-mile away, said State Police Capt. Thomas Carr.
Police were trying to determine whether the missing man stole the
car, he said.
   Police tentatively identified the dead man as a 46-year-old North
Carolina resident who was on parole for two bank robbery convictions
in that state in 1976 and had moved to Hackensack in October,
Gallagher said. The driver was identified only as a 37-year-old
Greensboro, N.C., man. He was taken into custody, but no charges had
been filed by late Tuesday.
   Police withheld the two men's names while verifying their
identities, Gallagher said.
   The trooper was not injured in the scuffle, Gallagher said.
</TEXT>
