<HEAD>Report Says Hamadi Cheered Pan Am Crash, He Denies It</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The judge called inmates to
testify Tuesday about a report that confessed TWA hijacker Mohammed
Ali Hamadi cheered when told in prison last month that a Pan Am
jetliner had crashed.
   Hamadi denied the report, and the witnesses did not corroborate
it.
   Chief Judge Heiner Mueckenberger called two men from Preungesheim
prison to answer questions about Hamadi's reaction to the Dec. 21
bombing over Scotland of Pan Am Flight 103, which originated in
Frankfurt and changed planes in London. All 259 people aboard and 11
people on the ground were killed.
   Hamadi is charged with air piracy and murder in the June 1985
hijacking of a TWA jet to Beirut, during which U.S. Navy diver
Robert Stethem was killed and 39 Americans were held hostage for 17
days. He has admitted taking part in the hijacking but denies
killing Stethem.
   Mueckenberger said he wanted to clarify a report telephoned to
him by a prison official that Hamadi, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem,
cheered when he heard of the Pan Am crash.
   The first witness, who identified himself as Klaus Wilhelm
Helfinger, said he remembered Hamadi being especially boisterous
after news of the crash.
   ``Hamadi's cell is directly next to mine,'' he said. ``I was in
cell 28 and he occupies 27, and he did a lot of shoan be named this
month.
