<DOCNO> AP890117-0192 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 1945EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-ChemicalWeapons     01-17 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Chemical Weapons,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel Warns Libya Against Use, Hits Germany For Alleged Involvement
In Plant</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Germany-Scandal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel said Tuesday it will do all it can to
stop West German firms from helping Libya build a poison gas plant
and promised massive retaliation if Libya uses chemical weapons on
Israel.
   Finance Minister Shimon Peres planned to raise the issue during a
visit to Bonn beginning Wednesday, a Foreign Ministry spokesman said
on condition of anonymity.
   The United States has charged that West German companies helped
Libya build a chemical weapons factory south of Tripoli. Libya
maintains the plant will make pharmaceuticals.
   Foreign Minister Moshe Arens also said he planned to confront the
Bonn government about the West German companies' suspected
connection to the Libyan plant.
   Arens told Israel radio: ``The fact that Germany has been
involved on such a large scale in supplying equipment ... to be used
to establish a chemical weapons capability in Libya, a country that
insists it is at war with Israel, is an abhorrent thing to us.
   ``We will do everything we can to put an end to it.''
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin said Israel would use every means
to defend itself against Libya, which he described as one of the
Jewish state's most dangerous enemies.
   ``Whoever would dare to use this kind of weapon against Israeli
military units or Israeli civilian targets will be clobbered 100
times if not more. Israel will not tolerate ... the use of this kind
of means against us,'' Rabin told Israel radio.
   West Germany is investigating allegations of West German
involvement in the Libyan plant.
   ``We believe the German government should strengthen supervision
and overcome existing loopholes in dealing with this delicate and
complex matter,'' the Israeli Foreign Ministry spokesman said on
condition of anonymity.
