<FIRST>r a AM-SubwayRapist     01-17 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Subway Rapist,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cardinal Asks Suspected Rapist to Surrender</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE ANDERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal John O'Connor, acting as a police
intermediary, appealed Tuesday for the surrender of a rapist who has
attacked seven women in the subway.
   Police Commissioner Benjamin Ward said O'Connor was asked to make
the public appeal after police received two calls to the 911
emergency line from a man who identified himself as the subway
rapist. The man said he would surrender if a personal appeal from
O'Connor was televised.
   ``Please, please, not only stop what you are doing, but for your
protection and for the protection of possible victims, please turn
yourself in to the police authorities,'' O'Connor said as reporters
and television cameras recorded his words at a hastily called news
conference.
   O'Connor promised the suspect would not be mistreated: ``You have
my word, given me by them, that you will be treated properly and
given complete justice in every respect.''
   Ward said the caller admitted he was a crack addict.
   ``He is apparently a very troubled person. He said he is sorry
for what he did and he said he feels that he is getting a little bit
out of control,'' Ward said.
   Ward said he was convinced the calls, which came in Monday at
12:45 p.m. and Tuesday at 10 a.m., were legitimate.
   Last February, a man claiming to be the bomber of an abortion
clinic made a request for a TV appeal from O'Connor. After
O'Connor's appeal, Dennis Malvasi surrendered and pleaded guilty to
dynamiting a clinic and planting a bomb that was defused before it
exploded at another. He was sentenced to seven years in prison.
   ``Clearly there is hope that this may be a similar situation,''
O'Connor said.
   The suspect now being sought by police is accused of raping or
sodomizing four women and attempting to sexually assault three
others over the past five months.
   In each case, the man forced a woman either off a train or a
subway platform at gunpoint or knife-point and into the subway
tunnel, where the attacks occurred.
</TEXT>
