<HEAD>Chiang Kai-shek's Widow Hospitalized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Madame Chiang Kai-shek, the widow of the
former Nationalist Chinese leader, has been hospitalized for two
weeks with fever and flu, newspapers reported Tuesday.
   The Chinese-language Min Sheng Pao quoted an unidentified doctor
at Veterans General Hospital in Taipei as saying that Madame Chiang,
90, was admitted because she had a ``slight fever and flu.''
   The China Times Express carried a similar report about Madame
Chiang, the former Soong May-ling.
   The hospital's president and vice president both declined comment
on the reports.
   Chiang Kai-shek led the Nationalist government on the Chinese
mainland during World War II but was forced to flee to Taiwan after
losing a civil war to the Communists in 1949. He led the
Nationalists on Taiwan until his death in 1975.
   Madame Chiang once wielded influence in China second only to that
of her husband. She remains widely respected.
