<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 2155EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Soviet-US     01-17 0616</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Soviet-US,0633</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Agree To Ease Currency Restrictions With East Bloc</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS GINSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has agreed to foreign
currency exchange with some East bloc allies and may lower its
domestic exchange rates as a prelude to full convertibility in world
markets, an official said Tuesday.
   The deputy chairman of State Bank of the U.S.S.R, V.A. Pekshev,
told a U.N.-sponsored conference on U.S.-Soviet trade that Soviet
officials acknowledge the need for full convertibility of the ruble
but must proceed slowly.
   ``By Jan. 1, 1990, we would make a 100 percent increase in the
ratio'' of the official domestic exchange rate, Pekshev said, in
effect doubling the amount of rubles exchanged for other currencies.
   ``Is this a currency devaluation?'' he said. ``We won't get into
theoretical arguments on this question.''
   The Soviet Union has several sets of exchange rates for domestic
and foreign products, and it was not known how the proposed increase
would affect the rates. Black market exchange rates are often six to
seven times higher than the official rates.
   More than 100 Americans and Soviets, including U.S. and Soviet
envoys to the world body, began the two-day meeting Tuesday, the
first such conference held under U.N. auspices.
   U.S. and Soviet speakers focused mainly on Soviet economic
reforms and repeatedly expressed optimism about improving relations.
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of
``perestroika,'' or restructuring, has led to an explosion of
cooperative business ventures and the relaxation of some
restrictions on foreign trade.
   But ventures have been stifled by the inconvertibility of the
ruble in foreign exchange markets and by the need to operate through
the Soviet state bank, which takes as much as 60 percent of hard
currency earnings from each transaction.
   Western media have reported the possibility of changes in the
official rate, which currently brings about $1.60 per ruble. One
Soviet official has said convertibility could result in a 10-fold
devaluation in the ruble.
   Pekshev dismissed the 10-fold figure as speculative and said
officials were considering ways to move to full convertibility
``stage by stage.''
   ``We're not in a position today to assert a new value of the
ruble to the dollar,'' he said.
   He said Soviets ``have agreed to partial convertibility'' with
several East European countries and were planning hard currency
``auctions'' for Soviet and East bloc enterprises to buy the foreign
currency needed for trade with the West. Foreign businesses
initially will not be allowed to participate, he said.
   The conference is scheduled to end Wednesday afternoon, two days
before President-elect George Bush's inauguration. Bush aides have
said they are planning a wide-ranging review of U.S. policy toward
the Soviet Union before deciding on a new agenda for relations under
Bush.
   Exports to the United States jumped from $214 million in 1982 to
$446 million the next year and were projected to dip slightly to
$445 million in 1987, according to U.S. figures. U.S. exports to the
Soviet Union decreased from $3.4 billion in 1984 to a projected $1.3
billion in 1987.
   Another statement said the U.S. State Department had agreed to
extend visas for Soviets wishing to continue meeting with American
corporations after the conference ends.
   Among the U.S.-based participants in the meeting were Duco
Akkerman, vice president of Dow Chemical Europe S.A.; Wilhelm
Braxmaier, vice president of Eastern European Motorola Inc.; F.E.
Cassidy, director of international development for the U. S. oil
company Tenneco Inc.; and Harvard University economist John Kenneth
Galbraith.
   Soviet officials also included the deputy minister of external
economic relations and head of the Soviet delegation, Y.N. Chumakov;
Deputy Oil Minister L.I. Filimonov; Viktor Ponomarev, the Soviet
trade representative; and Soviet U.N. Ambassador Alexander Belonogov.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890117-0199 </DOCNO>
