<FIRST>r a AM-CrackKids     01-17 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crack Kids,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>10-Year-Old Ordered Held On Drug-Selling Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAUPPAUGE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 10-year-old boy arrested for selling
crack on a street corner on Long Island was ordered held Tuesday at
a children's shelter because he had failed to show up in court on
two previous arrest warrants.
   The youngster, wearing blue jeans with a rolled-up comic book in
his back pocket, began to cry when court officers led him away in
handcuffs following the 30-minute hearing.
   A 14-year-old accomplice, arrested with him on Sunday on
drug-selling charges, was released in the custody of his mother
following his arraignment Tuesday.
   Suffolk Family Court Judge Donald Auperin ordered the 10-year-old
boy detained despite a plea from his mother that she would see to it
that he returned for his next court appearance.
   Auperin told the woman that her son had failed to show up on two
outstanding arrest warrants even though she also had been subpoenaed.
   The boy's court-appointed attorney, Douglas O'Connor, entered an
innocent plea on the youth's behalf.
   The mother left the courtroom sobbing after watching her son led
away.
   The boy was ordered held at the Nassau County Children's Shelter
in Westbury until his next court hearing on Jan. 20.
   The 14-year-old, who has an outstanding arrest warrant for
allegedly stealing a bicycle, was ordered to appear in court March 2.
   Both youngsters were arrested after they had been observed by
police allegedly dealing drugs on a street corner in Wyandanch, a
town of 18,000 people about 60 miles east of New York City.
   As the youths tried to flee, the 10-year-old dropped a bag
containing three crack vials worth $20 each, police said. One of the
youths also had $226 in cash in his pocket, police said.
   Suffolk police said they are seeking a suspect who is believed to
have hired the boys to sell the drugs.
   Family Court proceedings are usually closed to the public but
Auperin opened the arraignment after reporters argued for the
public's right to know. The judge ordered that the identities be
kept private. He also did not disclose details of the two arrest
warrants against the 10-year-old.
