<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 2118EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Justice-Meese 2ndLd-Writethru a0734 01-17 1136</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Justice-Meese, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0734,1160</SECOND>
<HEAD>Meese Violated Ethical Standards, Justice Department Report Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Adds 2 grafs of reax from Wallach attorney</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department concluded Tuesday that
former Attorney General Edwin Meese III violated federal ethics
standards five times in six years and that his relationship with E.
Robert Wallach ``dictated government action'' in major cases.
   Meese's assistance to scandal-plagued Wedtech Corp. and his
efforts on behalf of a proposed Mideast oil pipeline involved
``three instances in which friendship'' between him and Wallach
caused federal actions, said the report by the department's Office
of Professional Responsibility.
   Wallach, who collected $1.3 million from Wedtech from 1982 to
1986, is awaiting trial in New York on racketeering and other
charges. He is accused of peddling his Meese connection.
   ``As a direct result of the preferential, improper efforts of
Meese and his staff, the Army'' awarded a $32 million
engine-building contract to Wedtech in 1982 while Meese was
counselor to President Reagan, said the ethics report on Meese.
   Meese also violated ethics requirements, the report said, by
failing to report a stock sale on his 1985 federal tax return and by
participating in a Justice Department decision favoring the regional
Bell telephone companies in which he held $14,000 in stock at the
time.
   If Meese were still attorney general, ``we would recommend (to
the next ranking department official) that the president take
disciplinary action,'' the report concluded.
   A department statement said no further action against Meese is
warranted because he is no longer a government employee.
   Independent counsel James McKay decided last summer not to
prosecute Meese, although McKay concluded Meese had probably twice
violated conflict-of-interest laws in connection with his Bell
holdings and had violated tax laws in connection with failing to
report the stock sales.
   McKay's report ``far from vindicates Mr. Meese,'' said the new
Justice Department report. ``It details conduct which should not be
tolerated of any government employee, especially not the attorney
general of the United States.''
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh disagreed with one aspect of the
report, saying that Meese's failure to dispose of his financial
interest in the regional Bell companies resulted from a failure to
get adequate legal advice rather than from intent to violate ethics
standards.
   At the White House, spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said President
Reagan believes ``this report was unnecessary, partly because Mr.
Meese has not been in the office for some time and partly because it
was unwarranted.''
   Fitzwater said Reagan believes his longtime friend did nothing
wrong.
   The former attorney general, who resigned last year, immediately
attacked the report through his attorneys, who called it ``a
travesty of justice.'' Meese spokesman Patrick Korten said there is
an ``emotional undertone'' to the report that seems designed ``to
slam him personally.''
   At a news conference, Thornburgh declined to defend his
department's Office of Professional Responsibility from criticism by
Meese's supporters that the report was a personal attack on Meese.
   ``I think Mr. Meese is entitled to some peace,'' said Thornburgh.
   Thornburgh tried to avoid characterizing the OPR report in any
way, but ultimately called one of its conclusions ``clearly wrong''
and said there is an adequate factual basis for the others.
   Thornburgh disagreed with the conclusion Meese violated ethical
standards when he failed to sell $14,000 in stock of regional Bell
companies while participating in department decisions affecting them.
   He said there is an ``adequate factual basis'' for finding in
four instances that Meese violated ethics standards.
   But Thornburgh said that in regard to the Bell stock, Meese
either didn't get adequate legal advice or didn't follow it.
Thornburgh characterized that as a mistake, saying ``I've done that
myself sometimes. People make mistakes. We're all human.''
   Thornburgh emphasized that the findings in the report were those
of OPR, not of the attorney general.
   Meese, according to the report, violated ethical standards which
require government employees to avoid the appearance of impropriety
when carrying out official duties.
   But Korten said such a requirement is ``a lousy standard.'' He
said appearance is a ``subjective matter. It is not an objective
measure. What appears improper to one person may look OK to
another.''
   ``He had a close personal relationship with Mr. Wallach,'' said
Korten. ``I don't see why you can begrudge somebody of those
friendships.''
   The report notes at least 600 contacts between Meese and Wallach
beginning in 1981. It says that Wallach, a San Francisco personal
injury lawyer, showered Meese with letters and memos on topics
ranging from a ``diet program'' for the stocky presidential
counselor to business arrangements, while meeting with Meese in some
cases twice a day.
   Many of the memos, coming in ``a virtual torrent'' while Meese
was counselor to the president, contain ``a strong undercurrent'' in
which Wallach was ``seeking action'' from Meese and his staff ``in
matters in which he had a financial interest,'' said the report.
   It said the letters and memos from Wallach either confirm a close
personal relationship or ``reveal a level of presumptuousness on the
part of Mr. Wallach which exceeded that which one would think
humanly possible.''
   Wallach suggested in one letter moving United Nations Ambassador
Jeane Kirkpatrick to a new job, with Wallach becoming her
replacement. He also sent Meese a proprosed draft for Reagan's 1983
State of the Union address and suggested in another memo a way to
increase Meese's power. He recommended moving then-White House Chief
of Staff James A Baker III to the CIA and assigning then-CIA
Director William Casey to the National Security Council.
   In addition to the case in which the Army awarded a huge contract
to Wedtech, the report said, ``Meese and his staff injected
themselves ... as a direct result of the friendship between Wallach
and Meese'' into a financial problem Wedtech was having with the
Commerce Department's Economic Development Administration.
   Meese's intervention, including a phone call to then-Commerce
Secretary Malcolm Baldridge, was ``precisely'' the type of activity
prohibited by a federal executive order spelling out ethical
standards for federal employees, the report said.
   On the oil pipeline, Meese, again at Wallach's urging, arranged a
meeting in 1985 for Wallach and his client, Swiss oilman Bruce
Rappaport, with then-White House National Security Adviser Robert
McFarlane in an attempt to help secure an insurance package that
would support the project, the report said.
   George Walker, a lawyer for Wallach, said Wallach simply asked
Meese to ensure that Wedtech was being treated fairly on the Wedtech
engine contract and that Meese ``didn't participate'' in resolving
the problem surrounding Wedtech and the commerce department. Walker
said Meese had little involvement in the pipeline project.
   Walker said in regard to the more than 600 contacts between
Wallach and Meese that ``Wallach put all this in writing. We know
there's nothing wrong,'' emphasizing, ``The report is old news.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
