<FIRST>r i AM-Bolivia     01-17 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bolivia,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands March To Protest Economic Policies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of workers and students marched
through the streets of the capital and other cities Tuesday
demanding wage increases and protesting government economic policies.
   The march in La Paz was preceded by a rally and was called by the
Bolivian Workers Central, which says road blocks and strikes will
follow.
   Similar marches took place in other cities in the interior, radio
stations reported.
   Planning Minister Fernando Romero said the government has
included a 15 percent wage increase in its new budget and cannot
offer more. ``One cannot wring water from rocks,'' he said in
response to Workers Central wage demands.
   Speakers at Tuesday's rally called the government wage program
``inhuman'' and said it spells starvation for many.
   Bolivia's minimum monthly wage is $40, but many food prices are
comparable to those in the United States.
   The conservative government of President Victor Paz Estenssoro
says keeping a lid on wages is essential to the success of its
economic program.
   The government has lowered inflation from 24,000 percent four
years ago to 21 percent by firing 23,000 miners, closing
unproductive mines, imposing strict wage controls and lifting all
price controls.
   Social unrest has been kept in check through an emergency wage
program financed by the World Bank and foreign governments. Tens of
thousands of workers have been employed building roads, schools,
irrigation systems and rural clinics.
</TEXT>
