<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua     01-17 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poor Loot Red Cross Warehouse</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 150 poor people, their problems
multiplied by the national economic crisis, Tuesday looted a Red
Cross warehouse of food and clothing intended for victims of
Hurricane Joan, Red Cross officials said.
   Managua Red Cross Director Omar Cruz said the group broke into
the warehouse through the roof. He said he did not have an estimate
on the value of items taken.
   A police official said on condition of anonymity, ``There were no
arrests because we had limited forces there and it was impossible
for more people to climb up on the warehouse.''
   An AP photogapher who happened to pass the warehouse during the
looting reported seeing people carrying away armfuls of canned food
and clothing.
   Hurricane Joan slammed into the Atlantic coast on Oct. 21,
killing about 100 people and leaving an estimated 200,000 homeless.
Property damage was estimated at more than $700 million.
   Few in the capital were affected. But many of the thousands who
suffered property damages in Nicaragua's rural areas since have
moved to Managua.
   The Sandinista government says the hurricane worsened the
country's economic crisis. It also has blamed the crisis on eight
years of civil war with the U.S.-supported anti-Sandinista rebels,
known as the Contras.
   At the Mercado Oriental in the city's east section, it is common
to see dozens of people rummaging through trash cans for food.
   National inflation last year topped 20,000 percent, and the
government announced numerous devaluations of the official currency,
the cordoba, to keep the country's economy afloat.
   On Jan. 3, the government devalued the cordoba again, this time
by 120 percent. It raised gasoline prices by 125 percent and bus
fares 50-fold.
   The government also announced a spending reduction program that
would lay off thousands of public workers, cut defense spending by
27 percent and slash police services 40 percent.
   The government has not authorized salary increases although
prices on many basic goods have risen as much as 50 percent since
the latest devaluation.
</TEXT>
