<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 2216EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Chile     01-17 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chile,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Officers Indicted In Killing Of Three Dissidents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A civilian court has charged two national
police officers with murdering three family members in a 1986 raid
on the suburban home of a popular leftist folk singer.
   The Appeals Court of Southern Santiago indicted Lt. Sergio
Gajardo and Sgt. Jose Luna on homicide charges Monday in connection
with the midnight raid on June 30, 1986, Santiago newspapers
reported Tuesday. Police Lt. Col. Augusto Sobarzo was charged with
covering up the crime.
   Shot dead were the wife, sister-in-law and 16-year-old son of
Benedicto Salinas, whose songs attack the right-wing military
government of President Augusto Pinochet.
   Police first said the three committed suicide to avoid arrest.
They said they raided the house after being tipped off that it was a
clandestine medical clinic for a leftist urban guerrilla group, the
Manuel Rodriguez Patriotic Front.
   Human rights and dissident groups maintained the three were
gunned down.
   The Appeals Court ruling said information gathered by
investigators indicates ``the deaths of the three victims were
caused by third parties,'' the newspapers reported, and that Gajardo
and Luna ``appear to be the authors of the crime.''
   The ruling reversed a judge's decision not to pursue charges in
the case. The officers were expected to appeal.
   Human rights groups say killings in political raids by police
have occurred repeatedly during Pinochet's 15-year rule. Officers
have been indicted or tried in only a handful of cases and
convictions are extremely rare.
</TEXT>
