<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 2220EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-TeamstersTrial     01-17 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Teamsters Trial,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>Convicted Teamster Officials Face Loss of Union Jobs; Five Others
Indicted</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.R. KROPKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge agreed Tuesday to determine
whether two Teamsters union officials must forfeit their positions
because they were convicted in an embezzlement scheme.
   Lawyers agreed to let Judge George W. White decide the issue, and
the judge set up a two-month timetable for attorneys to submit
motions. The two convicted Teamsters officials, Harold Friedman and
Anthony Hughes, can keep their jobs in the meantime. The two were
convicted Friday.
   In a separate Cleveland Teamsters case, five union members in
Local 436 have been indicted on federal racketeering, theft, and
embezzlement charges, related to the theft of $259,000 from the
local's welfare fund, federal officials said Tuesday.
   Federal prosecutor William Edwards announced the indictment of
Salvatore T. Busacca; his son, Salvatore I. Busacca; Pat Lanese;
Gary Tiboni; and Michael Paventi. No court date has been set.
   The indictments were returned by a special federal grand jury
Dec. 5 but were ordered sealed by U.S. Magistrate Jack Streepy until
after the trial of Friedman and Hughes.
   Friedman, 66, became Ohio's most powerful Teamsters union member
last summer after the death of Teamsters international President
Jackie Presser on July 9. Friedman's numerous union positions
include the international vice presidency and the presidency of the
Ohio Conference of Teamsters. His positions pay more than $500,000 a
year.
   Hughes, 52, holds three union positions that pay about $160,000
annually.
   Presser was indicted May 16, 1986, along with Friedman and
Hughes, but died before going to trial. The indictment listed the
union offices of Presser, Friedman and Hughes as being subject to
forfeiture after a conviction.
   Friedman declined to comment Tuesday after the verdict. Before
leaving the federal court building Tuesday, he shook hands with
Justice Department prosecutor Stephen Jigger and said: ``I know you
had a job to do, and I can appreciate that.''
   Hughes commented publicly for the first time Tuesday on the
verdict.
   ``They explained everything to me and I still don't understand
it. We will continue to fight,'' he said. ``I don't think we are
guilty, and I don't understand how they would come up with a verdict
like that.''
   Jigger told reporters he will try to have Friedman and Hughes
removed from their union positions.
   ``It was a six-year effort and we are pleased with the outcome,''
said Jigger, also commenting publicly for the first time. ``Judge
White gave everyone a full and fair trial, and justice was done. It
shows the system worked.''
   Friedman was convicted of embezzlement, labor racketeering,
conspiracy to commit labor racketeering and filing a false report to
the Department of Labor. He could be sentenced to as many as 46
years in prison and fined up to $70,000.
   Hughes was convicted of embezzlement, labor racketeering and
conspiracy to commit labor racketeering. He faces up to 45 years
imprisonment and a fine of up to $60,000.
   White has not set a sentencing date.
   The jury found Friedman and Hughes guilty of participating in a
payroll padding scheme. The indictment alleged the $700,000
embezzlement took place between 1972 and 1981.
</TEXT>
