<FIRST>r a AM-RiverBoatCrash     01-17 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-River Boat Crash,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tour Boat Hits Sandbar, 14 Injured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEEDLES, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Colorado River tour boat smashed into a
sandbar Tuesday, tossing passengers from their seats and injuring 14
of the 44 on board, authorities said.
   None of the crew or passengers on the two-hour sightseeing tour
appeared to have life-threatening injuries, said San Bernardino
County sheriff's spokesman Jim Bryant. The tour started in Laughlin,
Nev., about 75 miles southeast of Las Vegas.
   The injured were taken to Needles Desert Community Hospital, said
sheriff's spokeswoman Nancy Wegner. Needles is about 20 miles south
of Laughlin, Nev.
   ``The Lord was watching over them, I'll tell you,'' Ms. Wegner
said, adding that when a boat hits a sandbar, ``It's like hitting a
wall.''
   The boat, about 50 feet long, is owned by Laughlin River Tours
Inc., said a company official who refused to give her name or
comment further.
   ``They got down there and were coming back. The water is low now.
The captain saw the sand and sped up the vessel to lift the boat
over the sandbar,'' Bryant said.
   ``But it didn't lift. It was going a pretty good speed. The
people on board in chairs got tossed around like ballast,'' Bryant
said.
   The accident occurred about 2 p.m.
   Sheriff's rescue boats and volunteers in boats took the injured
to the hospital, Ms. Wegner said. She said the captain and steward
on board were not seriously hurt and helped the injured passengers.
   The uninjured passengers were picked up by a sister ship and were
being taken to Lake Havasu City, Ariz., which is 35 miles south of
Needles.
</TEXT>
