<HEAD>Oil Workers Chief Indicted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge formally indicted Oil Workers Union
chief Joaquin Hernandez Galicia on Tuesday on charges of homicide,
illegal weapons possession and resisting arrest, the Attorney
General's Office said.
   Hernandez Galicia is the main target of a government crackdown on
purported corruption in the powerful union.
   He was told of his indictment in closed session by a secretary to
Judge Jose Luis Garcia Vasco of the 8th District Penal Court, said
Rene Hernandez, a spokesman for the Attorney General's Office.
   According to the office, Hernandez Galicia could face up to 40
years in prison if convicted.
   Hernandez Galicia, de facto leader of the union, was arrested
with others in a raid on his house on Jan. 10 in which a government
agent was killed.
   Under Mexican law, the judge has a year to hand down a sentence
or drop the case. Hernandez Galicia will remain in prison unless
bond is set, considered unlikely because of his political position.
   Nearly all of the 45 other oil union leaders, associates and
bodyguards arrested last week have either been indicted or released
on bond.
