<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 2227EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-ReligiousClubs     01-17 0583</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Religious Clubs,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Appeal Court Bars Religious Club Meetings At School</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high school cannot allow students to hold
regular religious meetings in a classroom shortly before the school
day starts, a federal appeals court ruled Tuesday.
   The ruling by the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in a case
from Renton, Wash., has implications for the Equal Access Act, a
1984 federal law that requires public secondary schools to allow
religious clubs to meet at school on the same basis as other
extracurricular clubs.
   The court stopped short of declaring the law unconstitutional,
saying instead that the Renton school system wasn't affected by the
law because it barred all non-curricular clubs from meeting on
campus. But the court also indicated that any on-campus religious
meetings would probably violate the constitutional requirement of
separation of church and state.
   ``The district must exclude organized religious speech because
use of public school facilities for religious purposes violates the
Establishment Clause'' of the Constitution, which forbids a state
establishment of religion, said Judge Jerome Farris in the 3-0
decision.
   If the ruling stands, the Equal Access Act ``has been
functionally rendered impotent and wouldn't apply in virtually any
public high school setting,'' said Steven McFarland, lawyer for a
group of high school students in the Seattle suburb. He said he
would appeal to the Supreme Court.
   Marc Slonim, a lawyer for the American Civil Liberties Union of
Washington, said the ruling may be the first by any federal appeals
court on the issue but is consistent with a number of lower-court
decisions around the nation.
   ``Since early in the 19th century we've had a tradition of trying
to separate religion from public schools so public schools can serve
people of a wide variety of religious beliefs,'' Slonim said.
   He described the ``equal access'' approach as an attempt to avoid
the constitutional ban on preferential treatment of religion, but
said it inevitably ``sends a message of religious partisanship in
the schools.''
   McFarland said about 25 students applied in the fall of 1984 to
use a classroom at Lindbergh High School for before-school meetings
of a non-denominational Christian student group for religious and
moral discussions, Bible readings and prayer.
   The principal and school district denied the request, citing
constitutional standards as well as a district policy that allowed
classroom meetings only if the purposes were ``an extension of a
specific program or course offering.'' The students also were
rejected by U.S. District Judge Walter McGovern, whose ruling was
upheld Tuesday.
   ``Permitting this student religious group to meet in a public
high school just before the start of classes would impermissibly
advance rather than neutrally accommodate religion,'' Farris said in
the appeals court decision.
   He said the meetings would take place ``at a time closely
associated with a highly structured school day,'' creating an
appearance of school sponsorship.
   Although the Supreme Court in 1981 allowed a student religious
group equal access to a university's facilities, the same standards
do not apply to public high schools, Farris said.
   High school students are required to attend school and ``are less
mature and more impressionable than university students,'' Farris
said. ``Teachers at high schools, unlike college professors, are
both educators and authority figures.''
   He also said the meetings would improperly ``entangle'' the
government with religion, because teachers, required by district
policy to supervise all student activities on campus, might either
interfere with or advocate religious activities as the club's
supervisor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890117-0214 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 2314EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-ThiokolFire-Lawsuit     01-17 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thiokol Fire-Lawsuit,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survivors Of Thiokol Fire Victims Seeking $9 Million From Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE SULLIVAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The families of three Morton Thiokol
workers killed in an explosive fire at an MX missile motor assembly
building filed a $9 million negligence suit Tuesday against the
federal government.
   The lawsuit in U.S. District Court seeks $3 million each in
general and specific damages for the wives and children of Jeffrey
Ellis, 29, Richard Goodsell, 36, and Michael Smith, 24.
   The lawsuit, filed jointly by Lorene Ellis, Helen Goodsell and
DiAnna Smith, contends their husbands' deaths resulted from
government negligence in implementing and monitoring safety
standards at the MX facility.
   Specifically cited in the suit were the establishment and
maintenance of mandatory criteria, standards and methods for
procedures involving the manufacturing of the MX motors.
   The plaintiffs also claimed government negligence in holding
regular inspections of the premises to ensure that procedures were
being followed by Morton Thiokol, and that the government neglected
to warn employees or stop work in the event noncompliance was
discovered.
   The victims and two other Thiokol employees had been manually
removing the steel core from a casting of a first-stage missile
motor when 100,000 pounds of solid rocket propellent ignited in a
fireball Dec. 29, 1987, at the company's Wasatch Operations plant 25
miles west of Brigham City.
   Four of the men were killed instantly, and Ellis died 11 hours
later. The Air Force said in a report three months after the
accident that the fire was caused either by friction or static
electricity.
   The Air Force report concluded that Morton Thiokol had failed to
provide an adequate remote-control system or fully implement other
safety measures recommended after a ``near miss'' six months earlier
that consisted of a flash and release of fumes during the same
procedure.
   A telephone call to the U.S. attorney's office in Salt Lake City
after business hours Tuesday for comment on the suit was not
answered.
   Morton Thiokol was cited for six safety violations and fined
$31,700 by the Utah Division of Occupational Safety and Health. The
company vowed to appeal violations alleging serious and willful
deviations from division rules, but company spokesman Rocky Raab
said Tuesday he was not sure if the appeal was filed and the fine
reduced.
</TEXT>
