<TEXT>
   A growing number of countries are suspected
of developing biological weapons, and existing accords are
inadequate to protect against further spread, researchers said
Tuesday.
   The use of biological weapons _ deadly viruses and bacteria _ is
governed by two treaties: The post-World War II Geneva protocol and
the biological weapons convention of 1972.
   Citing Pentagon statistics, Barbara H. Rosenberg of the Memorial
Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center in New York said that 10 nations are
now suspected of developing biological weapons, up from four in 1972
when the biological weapons treaty was adopted.
   ``Something has to be done to assure the international community
that the treaty is not breaking down,'' she said at the annual
meeting of the American Association for the Advancement of Science.
