<FIRST>a a AM_ReligionToday Adv20   01-17 0724</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM_Religion Today, Adv 20,0745</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv20</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri AMs, Jan. 20, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Solo Inaugural Prayer Is By Longtime Bush Buddy, Graham</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Prayer for presidential integrity and courage by evangelist Billy
Graham this Friday brackets George Bush's inauguration. The ceremony
starts with an invocation of divine assistance and ends with a
benediction.
   ``I'm going to ask God to give the new president strength,
courage and wisdom,'' Graham says. ``I'm going to pray that he be
given the wisdom to know what's right, and the courage to do it.''
   Although inaugural ceremonies ordinarily include prayers by a
denominational cross-section of clergy, Bush this time chose for it
only the durable evangelist, a long-time friend and vacation
companion.
   ``I don't know why I'm the only one,'' Graham said when asked
about it. ``I guess he and Barbara must have felt I could represent
the others. I'm honored to have been selected.''
   Graham, who has been a confidant of presidents ever since Dwight
Eisenhower in the 1950's, is particularly close to Bush and his
family, and has been for about a quarter century.
   They regularly spend some time together each year at Bush's
vacation home in Kennebunkport, Maine, and Graham and his wife,
Ruth, also spent a holiday with the Bushes in Mexico before Bush
became vice president.
   ``I knew his father and used to play golf with him,'' Graham
related of the late Sen. Prescott Bush of Connecticut, whose
hospitality drew the Grahams into the Bush orbit in the early 1960's.
   ``We've been close friends of the Bushes for many years,''
related Graham, now 70, who in his half-century, globe-girdling
career has preached directly to more than 100 million people in more
than 65 countries.
   The new president, Graham said, ``has a huge family. There are a
lot of Bushes and Walkers (Bush's mother's maiden name). They're all
very religious people. I know all the children very well. They're
all religious.''
   After dinner at the Kennebunkport weekends, he related, ``we all
gather in the living room and sit around on the floor. I read some
Scipture and the children ask questions about the Bible.''
   Asked why Bush isn't as openly expressive of his faith as
outgoing President Reagan, Graham said, chuckling, ``Well, you see,
he's an Episcopalian.'' Graham himself is a Baptist.
   Of the long line of presidents which Graham has been associated,
he said, ``I think Lyndon Johnson went to church more than any of
them,'' although Jimmy Carter also was a regular church-goer and
taught an adult class.
   ``Ronald Reagan has talked a lot about God,'' Graham observed.
   Graham has scrupulously avoided taking sides in presidential
campaigns, whatever his personal associations, particularly after a
non-committal ceremonial appearance with Richard Nixon caused
accusation of partisanship.
   At last summers national political conventions, Graham led
prayers both at the Democratic and Republican affairs.
   However, while he has been a frequent White House guest and
counselor through a string of eight presidents, he has a special
niche in the Bush retinue because of their background.
   ``I think he'll make a far greater president than some people
give him credit for,'' Graham said. ``Bush probably has more
knowledge of what is going on in the world and more government
experience than any man that has ever occupied the White House.''
   Graham, who in recent years has condemned the nuclear arms
buildup, said the developing friendlier relations between the United
States and the Soviet Union ``is one of the great legacies'' being
passed on by Reagan.
   Graham added, ``I definitely think Bush will advance this new
warmth between our two countries.''
   In the inaugural prayer, Graham said he would quote George
Washington as saying that ``America stands on two great pillars _
faith and morality. Without these, our foundation crumbles.
   ``Sometimes, this seems to be happening, but there also are signs
that a new spiritual tide is running in this nation. I'm going to
thank God for America, and all it stands for.
   ``I'm also going to say that humantity's promotion comes neither
from the East or the West, but from God.''
   Graham said his inaugural prayer also would ask blessings on Dan
Quayle as Vice President, on his wife, Marilyn, and for the coninued
``health and service'' of Reagan and his wife, Nancy.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, Jan 20</NOTE>
</DOC>
