<DOCNO> AP890117-0229 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 0106EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-RetailPredictions Bjt   01-17 0598</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Retail Predictions, Bjt,0616</SECOND>
<HEAD>Few Surprises in Retail Forecasts: More Slow Sales In 1989</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retailers from across the country, gathered for
their annual convention, have heard an unsurprising forecast from
industry watchers: Sales will remain sluggish in 1989.
   Rosalind Wells, chief economist of the National Retail Merchants
Association told storeowners Monday that consumers are optimistic
and confident about the economy, but retail sales will increase only
6 percent _ 2.75 percent after inflation.
   Americans have already put a lot of big purchases behind them,
and ``there's much less pent-up demand,'' she said.
   Ms. Wells and Lyle Gramley, chief economist with the Mortgage
Bankers Association of America, were upbeat about the economy
although they did not expect consumer spending to surge. Gramley
said he saw no signs of a recession this year.
   He did see some negatives ahead, including a slight worsening of
inflation that would help to nudge interest rates higher. But he
said he expected interest rates to peak by mid-year. If significant
steps are taken to cut the federal budget, rates could decline
before year's end, he said.
   The forecasters spoke at the NRMA's four-day convention here. The
delegates included retailers ranging from owners of small shops to
executives of the nation's largest storeowner, Sears, Roebuck and Co.
   The economic forecasting session traditionally is one of the
biggest of the meeting, drawing thousands of retailers away from the
aisles of exhibits set up by cash register manufacturers and credit
card companies.
   Another industry watcher, Stuart Robbins, an analyst with the
investment firm Donaldson Lufkin &amp; Jenrette Securities Corp., said
he expected ``more of the same kind of muddling along'' in the
economy this year, resulting in a mediocre retail environment.
   Robbins said, ``I don't feel good about 5 and 6 percent'' sales
increases, recalling that in past years, retailers enjoyed 9 percent
or 10 percent gains.
   Forecasts of consumer spending are critical for retailers,
because they must adjust their inventories and expenses in line with
how much Americans spend. Economists also watch consumer spending
because it accounts for two-thirds of the gross national product,
the broadest measure of economic health.
   In recent years, consumer spending has increased although retail
sales have risen only slightly. Americans have been channeling more
dollars into buying homes and cars and into necessities such as food
and medical care, leaving less money for discretionary items, which
include clothing and furniture.
   High installment debt has been blamed for some of the retail
sales slump, which is nearly 2 years old.
   But despite the forecasts of higher interest rates, Ms. Wells was
unconcerned about consumer debt. Although they may owe more money,
buying on credit is such a way of life that ``people are more
comfortable with debt,'' she said.
   Gramley and Ms. Wells both expected job growth to slow. That
would affect retailers because new workers have been a primary
source of sales increases in recent years.
   Durable goods, such as cars, furniture and large appliances,
would bear the brunt of consumer hesitance, while non-durables, such
as food, clothing and gasoline, should see pickups, Ms. Wells said.
   Robbins had a warning for the retailers: No matter what sales do,
operating expenses will climb.
   Storeowners have been paring costs in the past few years to
preserve their profits as sales declined. But Robbins said expenses
would spurt higher because as costs of labor, goods and real estate
accelerate.
   The forecasters also said there were many other variables that
may affect business during the year, such as the volatile price of
oil.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
