<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     01-17 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was lower against most major foreign
currencies in moderate European trading today. Gold prices rose.
   Traders in Italy said they expected the dollar to fluctuate
within a tight range ahead of Wednesday's release of U.S. trade
figures for November. The figures are expected to show a slight
widening of the trade gap from October's $10.35 billion.
   They also suggested the market was determined to give U.S.
President-elect George Bush some breathing space in his first few
months in office.
   ``The market can hardly be displeased with the election of the
second straight conservative president, especially one who should be
less of a big spender than Reagan,'' said one trader with an Italian
commercial bank in Milan.
   Traders in Frankfurt said the dollar was also being held in check
by expectations that central banks will attempt a renewed assault on
the currency if it rises.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 1.05 yen to a closing 127.70. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 127.65 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Monday's
rates, included: 1.8474 West German marks, down from 1.8575; 1.5750
Swiss francs, down from 1.5835; 6.3010 French francs, down from
6.3285; 2.0828 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0965; 1,354.25 Italian
lire, down from 1,359.50; and 1.1965 Canadian dollars, unchanged.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7695 today, more expensive
for buyers than 1.7615 Monday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $402.40 a troy ounce, up
from $401.75 bid late Monday. At midmorning, the city's five major
bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $402.10.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $401.50, up from $401.35 bid late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.78 to close at a bid $404.43.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.91 a troy ounce,
up from Monday's $5.89.
</TEXT>
