<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 0735EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     01-17 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises Sharply</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar gained sharply against the Japanese yen
today, reflecting its sharp rise on overseas markets overnight, and
stock prices fell in Tokyo.
   The dollar opened at 127.93 yen and went as high as 128.15 yen in
early trading before easing back to 127.70 yen at the finish, up
1.05 yen from the close of 126.65 yen last Friday, when the dollar
gained 0.53 yen. The market was closed Monday for a national holiday.
   Finance Minister Tatsuo Murayama attributed the dollar's strength
to the difference in key interest rates between Japan and the United
States and to reported statements by West German finance authorities
that the dollar's current level is acceptable.
   He ruled out the possibility of the Bank of Japan intervening to
stem the dollar's rise, saying, ``The situation does not require
immediate countermeasures.''
   Traders noted that on Monday, the dollar closed in London at
128.05 yen and in New York at 128.10. One reason for the gains, they
said, was reduced chances of central bank intervention as Japan
observed a holiday and many U.S. traders were absent from the market
in observance of the Rev. Martin Luther King's birthday.
   ``There had been strong demand for buying the dollar, but
traders' fears over intervention prevented such a move,'' said a
dealer at a major commercial bank, speaking on condition of
anonymity. ``Then when they were freed from such fears, they all
went out to buy the dollar.''
   But the traders added that the dollar was unlikely to continue
gaining while the market awaited U.S. trade reports due Wednesday in
Washington.
   Meanwhile, on the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average
of 225 selected issues dipped 70.86 points, or 0.23 percent, closing
at 31,227.52.
   Dealers said the dollar's steep gain and anxiety over the
upcoming U.S. trade reports contributed to the decline as many
investors pulled back to the sidelines. Prices of export-oriented
issues fell, as did those of steel, railway and petroleum shares.
   ``It appeared the market was taking a break today as the market
anxiously awaits the U.S. trade reports,'' said a dealer at a major
Japanese brokerage. ``But the yen's sharp downslide against the
dollar gave a downward direction and most shares ended up lower.''
   But most dealers appeared to take today's decline as temporary.
   ``The market is still bullish despite today's slip,'' said
Ichitaro Watanabe of Nikko Securities Co. ``I think it still has
potential for further growth.''
</TEXT>
