<FIRST>r f BC-AsianAirlines     01-17 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Asian Airlines,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five Asian Airlines To Become Partners In Regional Computer Reservation
System</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SINGAPORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Asian airlines, China Airlines Ltd.,
Malaysia Airlines System Bhd and Philippine Airlines have signed up
as equity partners in a $100 million regional computer reservation
system, Abacus.
   Together with existing partners, Singapore Airlines Ltd. and
Cathay Pacific Airways Ltd., they plan to develop and market the
system as well as negotiate for links with other similar systems
worldwide, they said in a press release Tuesday.
   The three new partners signed a letter of intent on Tuesday,
giving them a six-month period in which to work out the details of
equity distribution among the five parties.
   A spokesman from Abacus, currently a shell company financed by
loans from SIA and Cathay Pacific, said while nothing has been
finalized, each airline is not expected to own less than 10 percent
of the total equity.
   Abacus is also in the final stages of negotiation for a 10
percent acquisition in a computer reservation system owned by Trans
World Airlines and Northwest called PARS. It also plans to work out
a cooperative agreement with Amadeus, a similar system in Europe.
   When the three phases of the Abacus project are completed,
sometime in the third quarter of 1990, travel agents in Asia will
have direct access to bookings in partcipating airlines, hotels and
car rental services through a core computer to be located in
Singapore.
</TEXT>
