<FIRST>r f PM-Kraft-Stillman 1stLd-Writethru f0028 01-17 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kraft-Stillman, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0028,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kraft To Sell Food Distributor, Layoff Workers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Recasts lead to move up reference to layoffs.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GLENVIEW, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kraft Inc. plans to cut about 250 workers
from its Chicago area operations over the next two months, and to
sell its small Kraft-Sage food operation to a management group,
company officials say.
   The layoffs, which will affect three Chicago facilities, are the
result of the company's recent merger with Philip Morris Cos. Inc.
and Kraft's ongoing productivity improvement program, the company
announced Monday.
   Kraft Inc. spokesman Gene Stevenson said employees will be laid
off from company headquarters in Chicago suburb of Glenview, its
manufacturing research and development unit in Northbrook and the
company's food-service operation in Deerfield.
   He said the layoffs will reduce the company's work force, some
2,800 in the area, by slightly less than 8 percent.
   The move had been expected since October, when Philip Morris took
over Kraft in a $12.9 billion deal, he said.
   ``Kraft just formalized it,'' said Roger Spencer, an analyst with
PaineWebber Inc.
   ``You're seeing the kind of home office cuts you always see in
mergers; you only need so many accountants and tax guys,'' one Kraft
source told the Chicago Tribune. ``But operations aren't much
affected at all.''
   Kraft also announced Monday its intent to sell its Kraft-Sage
operation to the Stillman Acquisition Co. and the Greenberg
Acquisition Co.
   The management of Kraft-Sage, chief executive officer Sheldon
Stillman and president Gary Greenberg, formed the acquisition
companies so they could buy the company.
   Kraft-Sage, located in Des Plaines, Ill., is a specialty
distributor and marketer of foodservice products to the airline
industry.
</TEXT>
