<DOCNO> AP890117-0242 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 1104EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Scotus-Amputee     01-17 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Amputee,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Rules Against Amputee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Kentucky man who lost a leg in a farm
accident lost a Supreme Court bid today to revive his lawsuit
against a farm equipment manufacturer.
   The justices, without comment, rejected arguments that the
lawsuit was dismissed improperly because a stenographer was tardy in
transcribing pretrial statements.
   The accident occurred Oct. 22, 1983, when Eugene McDowell was
unloading corn from a wagon into an old house used for grain
storage. His clothing was caught in the portable conveyor connecting
a tractor to the corn elevator, and his left leg had to be severed.
   U.S. District Judge Scott Reed in Lexington, Ky., threw out the
suit against Dynamics Corporation of America of Bloomington, Ill.,
the conveyor manufacturer.
   McDowell said the conveyor's design was defective and was
inherently dangerous.
   Dynamics Corporation said McDowell's own negligence _ his failure
to stand far enough away from the machine _ caused the accident. The
company also said the machine had been modified since its
manufacture and that Dynamics Corporation ws not responsible for the
changes.
   Reed threw out the suit on June 30, 1987 without reviewing
depositions _ or pretrial statements _ from witnesses for McDowell.
An engineer said in the deposition that the conveyor was defective
because it lacked a guard to prevent such accidents. The engineer
also said any changes in the machinery were minor and had little
bearing on the accident.
   The 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled last June that it was
McDowell's responsibility to make sure that a transcript of the
statement was provided to the judge.
   ``Without the deposition testimony, (McDowell) has presented no
evidence of design defect,'' the appeals court said.
   McDowell's lawyers said the stenographer, called a court
reporter, violated federal court rules by failing to supply the
judge with the statement.
   The lawyers said, unbeknownst to them, the stenographer sent a
transcript of the deposition to attorneys for Dynamics Corporation
but not to Reed.
   McDowell was ``denied his day in court beacuse of the failure of
a court reporter to follow the federal rules,'' attorneys said.
   They also said that federal appeals courts elsewhere in the
nation have reinstated suits in such cases.
   The case is McDowell vs. Dynamics Corporation, 88-758.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
