<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   01-17 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corn Futures Open Lower; Wheat, Soybeans Mostly Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn futures opened sharply lower but wheat prices
advanced and soybeans were mostly higher in early trading today on
the Chicago Board of Trade in the wake of the previous session's
sharp losses.
   Analysts said the wheat and soybean markets were turning higher
on indications that the Soviet Union would need to increase its
grain imports. Among those signals is the Soviets' own estimate that
domestic grain production will fall 40 million tons short of the
target of 235 million tons.
   ``The background stories that they might be coming in for a lot
more U.S. agricultural products have certainly supported the
market,'' said Arthur Parrish, a grain-market analyst with Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   Corn, oat and soybean futures posted dramatic losses Monday in
response to an Agriculture Department report showing
higher-than-expected corn supplies.
   In early trading, wheat was 2\ cents to 4{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.33 a bushel; corn was 3 cents
to 8} cents lower with March at $2.69{ a bushel; oats were 1{ cents
to 2} cents higher with March at $2.34{ a bushel; and soybeans were
3\ cents lower to 7 cents higher with January at $7.72 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mostly higher while pork futures were mostly
lower in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .07 cent to .13 cent higher with February at
74.22 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .07 cent lower to .25 cent
higher with January at 84.95 cents a pound; live hogs were .25 cent
lower to .10 cent higher with February at 44.77 cents a pound; and
frozen pork bellies were .30 cent to .55 cent lower with February at
41.65 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled mixed on Monday while pork futures
finished lower.
</TEXT>
