<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 1223EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-KNEnergy     01-17 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-KN Energy,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>KN Energy Expects Profit Despite $40 Million Writedown Of Assets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKEWOOD, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   KN Energy Inc. plans take a writedown of
$40.1 million in the fourth quarter, but expects its 1988 earnings
to exceed its 1987 net income of $13.3 million.
   The company is marking down the value of its coal, oil and
natural gas resources to reflect current market prices, Charles W.
Battey, KN Energy's chairman and chief executive officer, said
Monday.
   Despite the $40.1 million writedown in the fourth quarter in
1988, gains from a lawsuit settlement and an asset sale should
enable KN's earnings for the year to surpass those of 1987, Battey
said.
   Financial results for 1988 will be announced next month.
   The bulk of the pretax writedown _ $33 million _ reflects a lower
valuation for KN's coal properties, according to Battey. The
valuation of oil and gas assets was reduced by $7.1 million.
   In early January, KN announced a $36.1 million gain from the
settlement of a lawsuit involving the ETSI Coal Slurry Pipeline
Venture. KN was a partner in the 1,000-mile proposed pipeline
project, which never got off the ground mainly because of railroads'
opposition. Settlements of lawsuits against those railroads have
brought millions of dollars to ETSI partners.
   And last June, KN sold its east Texas pipeline subsidiaries for a
pretax gain of $15.7 million.
   Battey said the company plans to increase production later this
year at its Golden Eagle underground coal mine west of Trinidad in
southern Colorado. The mine is operated by Wyoming Fuel Co., a KN
subsidiary.
   ``Our Wyoming Fuel Co. coal subsidiary has a good operating base
in its contract for coal sales to the Arizona Electric Power
Cooperative,'' Battey said. ``After the addition of efficient
long-wall mining equipment, which Wyoming Fuel will lease and have
in operation later this year, we expect to have positive cash flow
and operating income.''
   Meanwhile, Standard &amp; Poor's raised KN's senior debt and
preferred stock rating by one level to A-minus from BBB. The New
York-based credit-rating agency said the improved rating was due to
the improved coal outlook, the use of pipeline litigation income to
reduce debt and to new markets.
</TEXT>
