<DOCNO> AP890117-0250 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 1410EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-USTrade Bjt   01-17 0600</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-US Trade, Bjt,0621</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Says Cheaper Dollar Could Backfire on U.S. Trade Strategy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE KURTENBACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pushing the dollar lower against the Japanese yen to
help shrink the U.S. trade deficit could have the opposite effect in
the long term as Japanese businesses become more competitive, a
senior Finance Ministry official said Tuesday.
   Makoto Utsumi, director general of the Finance Ministry's
International Finance Bureau, also said U.S. businesses were fully
competitive at current exchange rates even though they had problems
competing in foreign arenas.
   ``A further decline in the dollar would not reduce the Japanese
trade surplus,'' Utsumi told reporters at the Foreign Correspondents
Club of Japan.
   ``If the dollar weakens further, Japanese businesses would take
steps to survive by further rationalization of business and
manufacturing, keeping wage increases low, cutting labor further _
economy in every aspect,'' Utsumi said.
   ``After this process of rationalization, Japanese manufacturers
might be still more competitive,'' and paying lower prices in dollar
terms for imported raw materials would give them a further
advantage, he said.
   Japanese manufacturers responded to the first major appreciation
of the yen against the dollar in 1985-1986 by improving efficiency
after the major industrialized nations, including the United States,
Britain, West Germany, France and Japan, agreed to slash the
dollar's value to help shrink the U.S. trade deficit.
   In February 1987, those nations agreed on approximate exchange
rate ranges for the U.S. dollar and other major currencies, seeking
to restore stability to exchange markets, but the dollar continued
to slide from its September 1985 level of 240 yen.
   The dollar closed at 127.70 yen Tuesday in Tokyo. It has ranged
between 120 yen and 135 yen since November 1987.
   Economists remain divided over the actual impact of a cheaper
dollar on trade flows.
   Some say the cheaper dollar has helped narrow the trade gap by
dampening demand for more expensive foreign goods in the United
States and stimulating sales of cheaper American goods overseas.
They also say the dollar would have to drop to 80 yen or lower to
achieve desired reductions in the U.S. trade deficit.
   But Utsumi said further declines in the dollar's value would not
improve American export competitiveness.
   ``The problem is not price competitiveness of U.S. industries,
but the willingness and capacity to export,'' Utsumi said.
   Using exchange rates to boost exports has the disadvantage of
encouraging manufacturers to concentrate on fattening their profit
margins rather than improving productivity, Utsumi stated.
   The senior ministry official urged the incoming administration of
President-elect George Bush to cut the U.S. federal budget deficit
and curb consumer demand.
   ``Then U.S. manufacturers would become more eager to seek out
overseas markets to sell their products,'' he said.
   Utsumi said little remains to be done by Japan's government to
open its markets to foreign exporters. Instead, the question is
``how to crack the ice of the private sector,'' he said.
   He predicted Japan's current account surplus would decline by
several billion dollars in fiscal 1988, which ends March 31, and by
another several billion dollars in fiscal 1989.
   In 1987, Japan's surplus in the current account, which measures
trade in goods and services, flows of short-term interest and
dividends, repatriation of profits and other financial transfers,
was $86.7 billion, up from $85.8 billion in 1986.
   Its surplus with the United States hit a record $59.8 billion in
1987, up from $58.6 billion in 1986.
   In 1986, Japan's current account surplus amounted to 3.6 percent
of its gross national product, and was expected to amount to a
little over 2 percent this year, Utsumi said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
