<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 1520EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-PrimaryDealer     01-17 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Primary Dealer,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>L.F. Rothschild Quits As Primary Dealer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   L.F. Rothschild &amp; Co. Tuesday said it voluntarily
decided to quit as a primary dealer in U.S. government securities
and to discontinue most trading of the securities because the
activities have not been profitable enough.
   The company said in a statement ``the return on capital devoted
to its government securities operations was insufficient to warrant
continuation of the business.''
   Rothschild said it had ample capital to satisfy new guidelines
announced by the Federal Reserve Bank of New York last November and
the decision was made purely on profitability grounds.
   The guidelines announced by the New York Fed Nov. 17 doubled the
minimum capital required for securities companies who have the
coveted title of primary dealer. The minimum was raised to more than
$50 million.
   Primary dealers can buy and sell U.S. government securities
directly from the New York Fed. Through the buying and selling of
the securities, the Federal Reserve System seeks to influence
interest rates.
   Therefore, financial firms with primary dealer status have an
insight into government interest rate policy. Also, primary
dealership is sought-after because some big institutional investors
prefer to conduct their business exclusively through primary dealers.
   The L.F. Rothschild move, which will result in the loss of about
50 employees' jobs, curtails all of the company's sales and trading
activities of U.S. government securities except for proprietary
trading, meaning for its own account. The company had been acting as
a primary dealer for about two years.
   From now on, Rothschild's operations will consist of fixed-income
securities sales and trading as a dealer in mortgage-backed
securites, as well as corporate and high-yield securities. It will
also continue to operate in the investment banking field.
   The withdrawal of L.F. Rothschild, a unit of Franklin Savings
Association based in Ottawa, Kansas, reduces the number of primary
dealers to 44.
   On Friday, County NatWest Government Securities Inc. announced
its departure from the exclusive group. County NatWest, a subsidiary
of Britain's largest bank, National Westminster Bank PLC, had been
under pressure from the New York Fed to boost its capital.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
