<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   01-17 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corn, Soybeans Close Down Sharply; Wheat Gains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and soybean futures posted a second day of
sharp losses Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade, partly in a
continuing reaction to the government's report of
larger-than-expected corn supplies, analysts said.
   Wheat and oat futures closed mostly higher.
   Rumors that the Soviet Union may cancel some soybean or
soybean-meal purchases because of port congestion also contributed
to the decline in soybean futures prices, as did improved growing
conditions for the South American soybean crop, analysts said.
   Intra-day losses in the corn market approached the exchange's
15-cents-a-bushel limit, which was expanded from 10 cents a bushel
following limit declines on Monday. But a late rally brought corn
and soybean futures off their lows of the day.
   Monday's plunge was linked to Friday's Agriculture Department
crop report, which indicated supplies of U.S. corn and soybeans were
larger than most market experts had expected.
   ``The market is searching for support now following the
liquidation as a result of crop report,'' said Ted Mao, a
grain-market analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   At the close, wheat was 1{ cents to 6\ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.37 a bushel; corn was 2 cents
to 10\ cents lower with March at $2.68 a bushel; oats were unchanged
to 2{ cents higher with March at $2.33 a bushel; soybeans were {
cent to 15\ cents lower with March at $7.70 a bushel.
</TEXT>
