<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0526</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market sagged today in moderately
active trading, and traders said there was some apprehension about
economic reports due later in the week.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was off 7.14 points at
2,217.50 with an hour of trading to go.
   Declining issues outnumbered advancing ones 4 to 3 on the New
York Stock Exchange, with 584 up, 769 down and 567 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 118.65 million shares as of 3
p.m. EST.
   ``I think this is a temporary pause,'' said William LeFevre, a
market strategist at Advest Inc.
   Analysts said traders were focusing on such factors as the level
of the dollar and oil prices, Wednesday's report on the nation's
November trade deficit and Thursday's report on December consumer
prices.
   Also on traders' minds is the outlook for fourth-quarter earnings
at International Business Machines, due Wednesday. Profits are
expected to be up because of good minicomputer sales and gains from
an arbitration award from Fujitsu Ltd.
   Business inventories and business sales both rose 0.4 percent in
November after seasonal adjustments, the Commerce Department said
today.
   The dollar weakened slightly in trading today, giving up some of
its recent gains. Oil futures prices continued to rise above the
14-month high reached Tuesday on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   On the trade front, some analysts are predicting a rise in the
trade deficit to about $11 billion in November from $10.4 billion
the previous month.
   Texas Eastern was up 1[ at 46[ on heavy volume. It is being
sought by Coastal for 42 a share, or $2.49 billion. The stock had
soared 14} to 45, above the offering price, on Monday.
   Goodyear sank 2 to 51[, helping drag down the Dow Jones
industrial average, of which it is a component. The company said it
expects to report fourth-quarter earnings from continuing operations
that are down 53 percent from a year earlier.
   Marriott was up | at 34] on rumors, disregarded by some analysts,
that it might be the subject of a takeover offer.
   Among other actively traded NYSE issues, RJR Nabisco was
unchanged at 94} on heavy volume, American Telephone &amp; Telegraph was
up [ at 29[ and Archer Daniels Midland was up ~ at 21} on
stronger-than-expected earnings.
   Among airline stocks, UAL was up 1] at 114 on speculation of a
takeover attempt by Saul Steinberg, who has acquired a 5 percent
stake. NWA was up 2 at 58\ on rumors that UAL might try to buy it as
a defense against a bid by Steinberg.
   In the over-the-counter market, Apple Computer plunged 3[ to 40|
on volume of more than 5 million shares. The personal computer maker
said its earnings rose 16 percent, in line with expectations. But it
also announced a price cut on some products.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
off 0.16 at 159.62. The American Stock Exchange's market value index
was off 0.53 at 316.28.
