<FIRST>r f AM-PaperAcquisition     01-17 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paper Acquisition,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>International Paper To Acquire French Paper Maker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PURCHASE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Directors of Aussedat Rey, one of France's
largest paper companies, on Tuesday approved a $320 million
acquisition offer from International Paper Co.
   The friendly $107 a share offer for all of Aussedat Rey's stock
officially was submitted Monday for approval by French government
and stock market authorities, said International Paper, the world's
largest paper maker.
   The board of Aussedat Rey, which has about 3 million shares
outstanding, unanimously approved the buyout in a meeting at company
headquarters in Velizy, France.
   International Paper stated in a news release that it viewed the
buyout as an important step in its international strategy. The
company also stated it considered Aussedat Rey a good fit with its
own paper businesses, especially its growing reprographic copy paper
business and other activities such as laminated panel production.
   There are no plans to sell any Aussedat Rey operations,
International Paper stated, and the company intends to modernize and
expand Aussedat Rey's pulp and paper facility in Saillat, France.
   John Georges, International Paper's chairman and chief executive,
said his company was confident of Aussedat Rey's long-term growth
prospects and the acquisition would help strengthen IP's competitive
position in Europe.
   Aussedat Rey last year had estimated earnings of 120 million
francs, about $20 million, on sales of 4.48 billion francs, about
$710 million. The company specializes in printing and writing paper
production and holds a 10 percent share of the European reprographic
paper market.
   International Paper, the biggest maker of reprographic paper,
earned $754 million, or $6.57 per share, on sales of $9.5 billion
last year. Earnings for 1987 were $407 million, or $3.68 per share,
on sales of $7.8 billion.
</TEXT>
