<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Rockwell     01-17 0202</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Rockwell,0210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Profit Down 17 Percent in First Quarter; Tax Adjustment Blamed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EL SEGUNDO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rockwell International Corp.'s said
Tuesday its first-quarter profit fell 17 percent from the same
period last year, when profits were boosted by a tax adjustment
related to production of the B-1B bomber.
   The aerospace, electronics and industrial company said it earned
$160 million, or 62 cents a share, in its first quarter of fiscal
1989, down from $192.9 million, or 71 cents a share, in the same
period a year earlier.
   Sales for the quarter ended December 31 were $2.87 billion, up
from $2.68 billion a year earlier.
   The first-quarter profit fell in comparison with the 1988 quarter
because the company recorded a one-time gain of $50.2 million from
tax benefits related to the B-1B programin the earlier period. The
benefit came from deferring taxes on some income in previous years
of the B-1B program until last year, when the tax rate was lower.
   Rockwell delivered the last B-1B to the Air Force in April, and
the end of that program meant decreased sales in the aerospace
division, which also works on the space shuttle.
   Sales rose in the electronics, automotive and graphics divisions.
</TEXT>
