<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 2122EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-PSNHBankruptcy     01-17 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-PSNH Bankruptcy,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shareholders, Creditors dismiss Offer For PSNH</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for shareholders and creditors of
Public Service Co. of New Hampshire on Tuesday dismissed a $2
billion offer for the company by Northeast Utilities as too low.
   Howard Berman, a lawyer representing PSNH's 100,000 shareholders,
said they would urge the company's board to reject Northeast
Utilities' plan ``as totally unsatisfactory.''
   ``The offer doesn't contain anything for shareholders, and we
believe it's inadequate,'' he said.
   Northeast Utilities offered last week to buy PSNH's assets aside
from its share of the Seabrook nuclear power plant for $1.2 billion.
PSNH's 36 percent stake in Seabrook would be spun off to the
company's unsecured creditors, while a Northeast Utilities
subsidiary would buy Seabrook power for $750 million.
   Northeast Utilities, New England's largest power company, also
would pay Public Service's unsecured creditors $300 million in cash,
stock and financial backing, bringing the total cost of the
transaction to $2 billion.
   PSNH was forced into reorganization under federal bankruptcy laws
last year because of rising debts from the $5.8 billion Seabrook
plant, which remains idle in the absence of a federal operating
permit.
   Berman said bidding for PSNH should begin at $2.8 billion and any
buyout plan must include Public Service's share of Seabrook.
   Joel Zweibel, who represents thousands of PSNH junk bond holders
and creditors with claims of about $1 billion, said the Northeast
Utilities offer ``casts too much of the contingent risk as to
whether Seabrook will operate on creditors.''
   The state, which has been negotiating with PSNH on a
reorganization plan for the utility, said Tuesday it was too early
to take a position on the offer from Connecticut-based Northeast
Utilities.
   Senior Assistant Attorney General Larry Smukler said, however,
the offer ``represents a reasonable basis for (further) discussion''
to resolve PSNH's reorganization.
   Smukler noted that the eletric rates Northeast Utilities is
proposing ``are higher than rates the state currently has on the
table.''
   The Northeast Utilities plan calls for annual rate increases of
4.5 percent this year and next followed by five years in which rates
would increase at approximately the inflation rate.
   The state's proposal calls for five consecutive 4 percent rate
increases, while Public Service is seeking a total rate increase of
30 percent to 40 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
