<SECOND>BC-Britain-UPS,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>United Parcel Service Buys European Operations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Parcel Service on Tuesday announced the
acquisition of seven transport companies which will strengthen its
operations in Europe and the Pacific.
   The acquisitions, whose terms were not disclosed, also will
facilitate the privately held company's expansion into the Middle
East and Africa, it said.
   UPS said it was acquiring IML Air Services Group Ltd., a
British-based document and parcel delivery company with annual
revenue of about $37 million. IML owns seven subsidiaries worldwide
and its services extend to 37 countries.
   IML is to continue to operate as an independent company for the
time being, UPS said.
   In addition, UPS has acquired six other parcel delivery
companies. These companies previously were established by leading
freight forwarders to act as service partners to UPS. They now will
serve as the basis for UPS operations in several countries, UPS said.
   The companies are: Road Air Parcel Service SA, Belgium; Danish
Express Parcel Service, Denmark; Nielsen Express OY, Finland; T.T.A.
Express SA, France; Road Air Parcel Service BV, the Netherlands; and
Fracht Air Parcel Service Ltd., Switzerland.
   UPS said its international air network now serves 41 countries.
