<SECOND>AM-Kraft-Layoffs,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kraft To Lay Off 250 In Post-Merger Slimdown</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GLENVIEW, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kraft Inc. said it would cut 250 workers
from its Chicago-area operations over the next two months in a
streamlining move following Philip Morris Cos.' $12.9 billion buyout
of the processed-foods giant.
   The layoffs, which will reduce the company's 2,800-person work
force by slightly less than 8 percent, will affect Kraft operations
in three Chicago suburbs, the company said.
   Employees will be laid off from the company's headquarters in
Glenview, its manufacturing research-and-development unit in
Northbrook and its food-service operation in Deerfield, spokesman
Gene Stevenson said Monday.
   He said the layoffs would be across the board, affecting both
executive and blue-collar employees.
   The move had been expected since October, when Kraft agreed to be
acquired by Philip Morris.
   Roger Spencer, an analyst with PaineWebber Inc., said the layoffs
also were part of Kraft's own productivity improvement program.
   Analysts said the cuts indicated that Kraft Chairman John M.
Richman controls the merged food operations of Kraft and Philip
Morris, which also owns General Foods and Oscar Mayer Foods Corp.
   ``All these moves are Kraft-instigated moves,'' said Ronald B.
Morrow of Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co. ``They indicate that
Richman didn't waste any time taking control.''
   Kraft also announced Monday that it will sell its Kraft-Sage
operation to the Stillman Acquisition Co. and the Greenberg
Acquisition Co.
</TEXT>
