<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     01-17 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Gold Up Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar slipped Tuesday in quiet trading,
reflecting money-dealer reluctance to take risky positions in the
currency prior to the release of the potentially market-moving
monthly trade deficit report.
   Gold prices rose slightly after declining in the previous trading
session. In New York, Republic National Bank quoted bullion at
$402.50 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, up from $401.80 at the same
time Monday.
   Currency strategists said the dollar's decline signaled a
cautious approach by dollar holders toward the Commerce Department's
Wednesday release of the November U.S. merchandise trade deficit
statistics.
   The consensus is for a shortfall of about $11 billion, compared
with $10.35 billion the month before, but the numbers are renowned
for defying predictions.
   A number sharply higher than $11 billion could possibly incite a
big selloff in dollars, while a much smaller number could encourage
a surge in demand for the currency.
   In either case, the uncertainty of whether central banks would
intervene to stabilize the dollar's value with massive purchases or
sales of their own also encouraged caution in the market, currency
traders said.
   ``It was a very quiet day, with people squaring their positions
ahead of the release of the number,'' said Fred Scala, senior
foreign exchange dealer at Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co. in New
York.
   Over the past few years the trade deficit numbers have become a
powerful influence over the foreign-exchange market, because of
their role in U.S. economic policy as well as their unpredictability
from month to month.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose 1.05 yen to 127.70 yen. Later in London
it was quoted at 127.75 yen. By the time trading ended in New York
the dollar was quoted at 127.83 yen, down from 128.10 yen late
Monday.
   In London the British pound strengthened to $1.7680 vs. $1.7615
Monday. In New York the pound fetched $1.7707, more expensive than
its $1.7610 exchange value late Monday.
   Other late-dollar rates in New York compared with rates late
Monday: 1.8495 West German marks, down from 1.8565; 1.5746 Swiss
francs, down from 1.5845; 1.1982 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1979;
6.3065 French francs, down from 6.3245; and 1,355.375 Italian lire,
down from 1,359.50.
   Other late-dollar rates in Europe, compared with late rates
Monday: 1.8505 marks, down from 1.8575; 1.5755 Swiss francs, down
from 1.5835; 6.3085 French francs, down from 6.3285; 2.0855 Dutch
guilders, down from 2.0965; 1,354.00 Italian lire, down from
1,359.50; and 1.1973 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1965.
   In precious metals trading, gold for current delivery rose 50
cents a troy ounce to $402.70 on the New York Commodity Exchange.
Earlier in London, gold rose 50 cents an ounce to $402.25; in Zurich
it rose 80 cents to $402.15; and in Hong Kong it rose $1.78 to
$404.43.
   Silver for current delivery rose 5.4 cents a troy ounce to $5.944
on the New York Comex. In London silver rose 3 cents an ounce to
$5.92.
</TEXT>
