<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 1742EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Earns-Banks     01-17 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Banks,0575</SECOND>
<HEAD>Citicorp, J.P. Morgan, Security Pacific, Wells Fargo Report Higher
Earnings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Citicorp, the nation's largest bank holding company, and three
other big banking concerns reported sharply higher earnings Tuesday
for both the fourth-quarter of 1988 and the whole year.
   Most of the banks, which included J.P. Morgan &amp; Co., Security
Pacific Corp. and Wells Fargo &amp; Co., said they were helped partly by
tighter cost controls and Brazil's resumption of interest payments
on foreign loans.
   The earnings of all four banks were severely hurt in 1987 _ the
peak of the Third World debt crisis _ when Brazil halted interest
payments on bank loans and other economically troubled countries
negotiated to restructure their debt. Citicorp said earnings for the
three months ended Dec. 31 totaled $747 million, or $2.19 a share,
compared with $621 million, or $1.82 a share, in the comparable 1987
quarter.
   For the year, Citicorp's earnings totaled $1.85 billion, or $5.36
a share. That compared with a loss of $1.18 billion in 1987, when
the company decided to increase its provision to cover possible
losses from shaky Third World debt.
   J.P. Morgan, the nation's fourth largest banking company, earned
$258.1 million in the fourth quarter, or $1.38 a share, compared
with the $224.1 million, or $1.21 a share, earned in 1987 fourth
quarter.
   The company's 1988 earnings totaled $1.00 billion, or $5.38 a
share, compared with $83.3 million, or 39 cents a share, in the
previous year.
   Security Pacific, ranked sixth, said quarterly earnings totaled
$169.5 million, or $1.46 a share, vs. a loss of $39.4 million the
previous year.
   Its annual earnings reached $638.9 million, or $5.59 a share, vs.
$15.7 million, or a penny a share, in 1987.
   Wells Fargo, ranked 10th, said fourth quarter earnings were $136
million, or $2.45 a share, up 22 percent from $111.2 million, or
$1.96 a share, in 1987.
   For the year, Wells Fargo's earnings totaled $512.5 million, or
$9.20, vs. $50.8 million, or 52 cents, in 1987.
   Citicorp said all sectors of the company did well partly due to
tighter expense controls.
   The company said quarterly and annual earnings included, among
other things, $436 million from nearly two years of accumulated
Brazilian interest payments and $160 million from tax benefits
stemming from its $3 billion addition in loan-loss reserves in May
1987.
   J.P. Morgan said it received $240 million of past-due interest
from Brazil during the final quarter of 1988. On top of that, its
loan-loss provision shrank, to $200 million for all of 1988 from
$960 million in 1987.
   Security Pacific said the recognition of Brazilian interest
payments accounted for $58 million of the increase in net interest
income. It said results also reflected slow growth in non-interest
expenses.
   Security Pacific said losses on loans to developing companies
totaled $663.6 million in 1988 as a result of loan sales and other
measures that reduced its debt exposure.
   At year's end, the company had reduced non-trade related
developing country debt to $520 million, down from $950 million as
of Sept. 30, 1988, and $1.8 billion at the end of 1987.
   Wells Fargo said the provision for its loan losses in the fourth
quarter was $75 million, down from $114 million a year ago. The
full-year provision was $300 million, compared with $892 million in
1987.
</TEXT>
