<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   01-17 0636</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0662</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices fell for a second day Tuesday as
nervousness over trade deficit figures due Wednesday contributed to
the market's first back-to-back declines of 1989.
   After edging down 1.43 points on Monday, the Dow Jones average of
30 industrial stocks fell an even 10.00 points to 2,214.64.
   Declining issues outnumbered advancing ones by about 4 to 3 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
624 up, 800 down and 545 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 143.93 million
shares, up from 117.38 million in the previous session.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 172.29 million shares.
   Traders worried that the Commerce Department would give the
market an unpleasant surprise with its report on the merchandise
trade deficit for November, said Rodd Anderson, vice president of
equity trading at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Expectations for the gap ranged around $11 billion to $11.5
billion, up from $10.4 billion in October.
   Also weighing on the stock market was a retrenchment in the
dollar, which has run up sharply in recent weeks, and another rise
in oil futures prices, which are at 14-month highs.
   Some analysts said the market seemed healthy in spite of the
successive setbacks.
   ``When the market is concerned, any bad news will kill it. Lately
the market has shaken off bad news,'' said William LeFevre, market
strategist at Advest Inc.
   Analysts said the market could be influenced by the
fourth-quarter earnings report at International Business Machines,
due Wednesday. Profits are expected to be up because of good
minicomputer sales and gains from an arbitration award from Fujitsu
Ltd.
   Apple Computer plunged 3] to 40] on volume of nearly 6.8 million
shares, making it the most actively traded issue on the
over-the-counter market or any market. Apple said its earnings rose
16 percent in the quarter, in line with expectations, but also said
it was cutting prices of some Macintosh computers and components.
   Intel, another over-the-counter issue, fell } to 23\ after
announcing a 10.4 percent decline in quarterly earnings.
   Much of the market's action was related to takeovers or other
special situations.
   Texas Eastern rose 1] to 46] on heavy volume after soaring 14} on
Monday. It is being sought by Coastal for 42 a share, or $2.49
billion.
   Marriott rose [ at 33~ on rumors, discounted by some analysts,
that it might be the subject of a takeover offer.
   Among other actively traded NYSE issues, RJR Nabisco rose { at
95\, American Telephone &amp; Telegraph rose [ to 29[, and IBM fell ] to
123~.
   Among airline stocks, UAL rose 1\ to 113~ on speculation of a
takeover attempt by Saul Steinberg, who has acquired a 5 percent
stake. NWA rose 2} at 59 on rumors that UAL might try to buy it as a
defense against a bid by Steinberg.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks fell relatively
more sharply than other market measures, mainly because one of its
components, Goodyear, fell 2[ to 51. The company said it expects to
report fourth-quarter earnings from continuing operations that are
down 53 percent from a year earlier.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market lost $5.20 billion, or 0.19
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
0.30 to 159.48.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index fell 0.91 to 327.98, and S&amp;P's
500-stock composite index fell 0.59 to 283.55.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market fell
1.31 to 386.05. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 316.57, down 0.24.
</TEXT>
