<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 1805EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     01-17 0811</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0838</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corn Futures Plunge Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn futures prices plunged Tuesday for the second straight day
on the Chicago Board of Trade amid rumors of export cancellations in
a market already weakened by the government's report of
larger-than-expected supplies.
   Soybean futures also fell sharply while wheat and oat futures
finished mostly higher.
   On other other markets, gasoline futures led energy futures
higher; precious metals advanced; livestock and meat futures were
mostly higher; and stock-index futures retreated.
   Wheat settled 2 cents to 6 cents higher with the contract for
delivery in March at $4.36} a bushel; corn was 2 cents to 10{ cents
lower with March at $2.67} a bushel; oats were unchanged to 2{ cents
higher with March at $2.33 a bushel; and soybeans were 14{ cents
lower to 1 cent higher with March at $7.70} a bushel.
   Rumors that port congestion may force the Soviet Union to cancel
some of its purchases of U.S. corn, soybeans or soybean meal weighed
on the futures markets for those commodities, analysts said.
   Under a long-term grain agreement with the United States, the
Soviet Union has so far agreed to purchase more than 10 million tons
of U.S. corn, 1.1 million tons of soybean meal, 450,000 tons of U.S.
soybeans and 370,000 tons of U.S. wheat for 1988-89 delivery.
   The cancellation rumors had the greatest impact in the corn pit,
where intra-day losses approached the 15-cents-a-bushel limit. The
Board of Trade expanded the daily trading limit for corn from 10
cents a bushel following limit declines on Monday.
   Analysts said the rumors surfaced just as the corn and soybean
markets appeared to be recovering from Monday's collapse, which was
linked to an Agriculture Department crop report released Friday that
indicated that supplies of U.S. corn and soybeans were larger than
most market experts had expected.
   ``When people started talking about net cancellations of U.S.
sales by the Russians, that brought in a pretty bearish attitude
right up until the close,'' said Steven Freed, a grain market
analyst with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   Additional selling of soybean futures was prompted by reports of
improved growing conditions in Brazil and Argentina, where a spate
of hot, dry weather got the South American soybean crop off to a bad
start, analysts said.
   A late rally brought corn and soybean futures off their lows of
the day. But corn for near-month delivery still closed at its lowest
point since Dec. 20 and January soybeans finished at $7.61}, the
lowest soybean futures price since Dec. 5.
   ``The market is searching for support now following the
liquidation as a result of the crop report,'' said Ted Mao, a
grain-market analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   Freed predicted corn prices would stabilize after Tuesday's
sell-off.
   ``The market will go to wherever the demand price is,'' he said.
``My feeling is that don't have to go down too much farther in
corn'' to attract buyers.
   Contracts for deferred deliveries of unleaded gasoline soared the
2-cents-a-gallon daily limit on the New York Mercantile Exchange on
speculation that new pollution-control standards taking effect this
year in several Northeastern states will raise the price of gasoline
production, analysts said.
   The new regulations in states including Massachusetts and New
York create a more stringent standard for a characteristic of
gasoline that is related to automobile exhaust emissions, said
Andrew Lebow, an analyst with E.D.&amp;F. Man International Futures Inc.
in New York.
   Crude oil for near-month delivery finished the day at a new
14-month high of $18.95 a barrel after trading as high as $19.21.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 7 cents to 30 cents
higher with February at $18.95; heating oil was .11 cent lower to
.13 cent higher with February at 53.05 cents a gallon; ands unleaded
gasoline was .19 cent to 2 cents higher with February at 51.10 cents
a gallon.
   Gold and silver futures advanced on New York's Commodity
Exchange, reflecting the U.S. dollar's weakness against major
foreign currencies.
   Gold settled 70 cents to 80 cents higher with February at $404 a
troy ounce; silver was 5.3 cents to 5.4 cents higher with March at
$6.01 a troy ounce.
   On the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, live cattle settled unchanged
to .30 cent higher with February at 74.35 cents a pound; feeder
cattle were .10 cent to .40 cent higher with January at 85 cents a
pound; live hogs were .15 cent lower to .22 cent higher with
February at 44.92 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies were .25
cent lower to .23 cent higher with February at 42.25 cents a pound.
   Stock-index futures retreated slightly on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for March delivery of stocks
represented by the Standard &amp; Poor's 500 index settled .60 point
lower at 286.10. The contract is worth $500 a point.
</TEXT>
