<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 2130EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-SoftwareMergers     01-17 0188</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Software Mergers,0195</SECOND>
<HEAD>Merger Business In Software, Services, Rose 70 Percent In 1988</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar value of acquisitions in the computer
software and services industry shot up 70 percent in 1988, according
to a survey released Tuesday.
   Among the 434 deals done last year were a record 14 valued at
more than $100 million, according to Broadview Associates, an
investment banker that does a quarterly survey for Adapso, the
computer software and services industry association.
   Overall, the transactions were valued at a record $8.4 billion,
up from $4.9 billion in 1987, Broadview said. The number of deals
rose 21 percent from 358 in 1987.
   The biggest deal was the $1.6 billion purchase of IMS
International Inc. by Dun &amp; Bradstreet Corp, Broadview said.
   Many of the buyers were big companies that preferred to buy
established companies rather than try to build software and services
businesses from scratch.
   For private companies, being acquired can enrich the original
owners while giving their company the resources to continue its
growth. The alternative of making a public stock offering is
unattractive in the current market, Broadview said.
</TEXT>
