<FIRST>u f AM-FirstCommodityIndictments 1stLd-Writethru   01-17 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-First Commodity Indictments, 1st Ld-Writethru,0609</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eighteen Former Employees Charged with Defrauding 2,600 Investors</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 5th graf to CORRECT to two branch managers sted three;
picks up 6th graf pvs bg'ng, The defendants ...; ADDS new 8th graf with
three unavailable for comment; picks up 8th graf pvs bg'ng, If convicted
...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal charges were announced Tuesday against 18
former employees of First Commodity Corp. of Boston, alleging they
defrauded more than 2,600 investors of some $40 million.
   The charges stem from an ongoing investigation in Chicago,
Boston, New York, Miami and San Francisco _ the largest single
investigation of its kind ever undertaken by federal officials, U.S.
Attorney Anton Valukas said at a news conference.
   The former employees, named in a federal grand jury indictment
and criminal information, are accused of using high-pressure sales
tactics to persuade customers from around the country to invest in
high-stakes commodity ventures misrepresented as being low-risk.
   More than $22 million of the investments was lost, Valukas said.
   Those named Tuesday include the failed company's former national
vice president for sales, two branch managers, and 15 former
salesmen and managers from its former offices in Chicago and
suburban Oak Brook, Ill., Valukas said. The criminal information
includes charges by his office while the indictment includes charges
by the grand jury.
   The defendants are charged with a total of 187 counts of wire
fraud and mail fraud, racketeering and racketeering conspiracy.
   They include David C. Connolly, 48, of Teaneck, N.J., the former
national sales vice president for the company; Ross A. Barnard, 37,
of suburban Hinsdale, Ill., former branch manager of the Oak Brook
office; and Stephen L. Barnard, 38, of suburban Flossmoor, Ill.,
former house broker of the Chicago office.
   Neither Connolly nor the Barnards could be reached for comment.
The Barnards have unpublished telephone numbers and Connolly was not
listed in the Teaneck telephone listings.
   If convicted, those charged could face lengthy prison terms and
thousands of dollars in fines.
   In the alleged scheme, customers were solicited by telephone by
First Commodity sales representatives posing as phony commodities
experts. Those representatives often made repeated phone calls using
``scripts'' handed out by managers, Valukas said.
   Investors were falsely told that ``commodity trading was not
risky ... and would lead to high profits,'' he said.
   ``In fact ... the defendants knew almost all of (First
Commodity's) customers lost money,'' Valukas said.
   During the alleged scheme, from 1980 to February 1987, $100
million in sales was brought in to the company's Chicago and Oak
Brook offices, and $63 million of that was lost, Valukas said.
   More than $40.6 million of those sales and more than $22.7
million of the losses were attributable to the former employees
named in the complaints, Valukas said. He declined to say whether
more charges were forthcoming, but noted that the investigation is
continuing nationwide.
   Three other former First Commodity employees pleaded guilty to
similar charges in December and have been cooperating in the probe,
Valukas said.
   ``It is a sad reality that sophisticated and deceptive sales
techniques can yield great profits to those willing to use them,''
he said. ``These cases should serve as a clear warning that fraud
and deception in the offer and sale of commodity contracts _ in
whatever form it takes _ will be thoroughly investigated and
vigorously prosecuted.''
   Founded in the late 1970s, First Commodity rapidly grew into one
of the nation's leading futures trading companies. But it collapsed
in 1987 beneath a mountain of investor lawsuits and federal
investigations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890117-0272 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 2049EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-FannieMae     01-17 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Fannie Mae,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fannie Mae's Net Off in Fourth Quarter But Record High in Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal National Mortgage Association Tuesday
reported a 22 percent drop in fourth-quarter income from the year
before, but for all of 1988 profit rose to a record level.
   Fannie Mae, as the federally-chartered private corporation is
commonly known, said after-tax income totaled $152.7 million, or
$1.91 a share, in the final three months of 1988, down from $195
million, or $2.42 a share, in the corresponding 1987 quarter.
   Results for the entire year were better. In 1988, Fannie Mae had
after-tax income of $506.7 million, up 34.8 percent from $376
million the prior year and a record annual amount. That translated
to per-share earnings of $6.43 and $4.66 in the two respective
periods.
   ``Fannie Mae's record 1988 income successfully caps a year in
which the company celebrated the 50th anniversary of its creation
and its 20th year as a private company,'' said David O. Maxwell,
chairman and chief executive officer.
   Fannie Mae is the nation's largest investor in home mortgages.
   Maxwell attributed last year's earnings growth to an increase in
the spread between the yield on the corporation's investment
portfolio and the cost of its debt outstanding, an increase in the
company's average investment portfolio, continued expansion in fee
income from mortgage-backed securities and a decline in the tax rate.
   Also beneficial was a decline in properties having to be taken
over due to foreclosures. Such acquisitions have fallen in each of
the past five quarters.
   The provision for losses on mortgage loans was reduced in the
fourth quarter to $85 million from $120 million in 1987's final
quarter.
   Part of the reason for the drop in the latest quarterly earnings
was that the 1987 results included adjustments associated with
changes undertaken following implementation of a new accounting
standard.
   Without the changes, earnings in the fourth 1987 quarter would
have been $60 million, or 75 cents a share and earnings for all of
that year would have been $242 million, or $2.98 a share.
   As of Dec. 31, Fannie Mae's assets totaled $112.1 billion, up 8.5
percent from $103.5 billion at the end of 1987.
</TEXT>
