<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 1924EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-InsuranceOrder     01-17 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Insurance Order,0594</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Orders Insurance Companies Into Receivership</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Mutual Liability Insurance Co. and
American Mutual Insurance Co. were ordered by the state Supreme
Court into receivership Tuesday at the request of state Insurance
Commissioner Roger Singer.
   The action was prompted by concerns over the Wakefield companies'
reserve capacity to cover primarily high-risk policies written in
the 1960s and 1970s involving asbestos, medical malpractice and
toxic waste claims, Singer said.
   Under the order, which was supported by the companies, Singer was
named receiver and the companies were enjoined from issuing new
policies or proceeding with their business except as permitted by
Singer.
   The companies were authorized to continue paying automobile,
worker's compensation and certain disability and accident and health
claims, but will not renew or write new policies.
   The companies, formed 101 years ago, are licensed in all 50
states but primarily operate in the Northeast. They have 20,000
commercial policies nationwide and nearly 75,000 personal policies.
   Singer said the order was intended to protect policyholders while
the Insurance Division works with management ``in an effort to
improve the companies' financial condition.''
   The Insurance Division will report back to the high court within
30 days on ``whether to rehabilitate them in some ways or declare
them insolvent,'' Singer said. ``We will either have a plan to
somehow get them back on their feet or we'll have the court declare
them insolvent.''
   Singer and company spokesman Tom Synder said there is a
possibility that a portion of the companies may be sold.
   National Grange Mutual Insurance Co. of New Hampshire has signed
a letter of intent to buy a small, stock-controlled subsidiary of
the companies, American Policyholders Insurance Co., which is
unaffected by the order although it too will stop writing new
policies.
   Singer said National Grange has expressed interest in buying
American Policyholders, bringing 500 to 600 of American Mutual's
nearly 800 Wakefield headquarters employees on board and paying off
American Mutual's long-term claims.
   ``One of the big assets of this company (American Mutual) is a
well-trained, experienced work force,'' Singer said.
   Synder said National Grange will be reviewing the potential
acquisition over the next 30 days.
   In the meantime, American Mutual will be looking at cutting its
total 1,400-employee work force to handle only claims, Synder said.
No decision on layoffs has been made yet.
   Singer said the companies' reserve capacity has been under review
by the Insurance Division since 1985. Since then, American Mutual
has brought in new management, sold off assets and upgraded its
business.
   ``During the past several years, the company has made great
strides in strengthening its reserves to pay losses,'' American
Mutual President J. John Wortman said. ``The reserve accounts have
been strengthened by over $250 million since 1986.
   ``However, some very recent changes in payment patterns on old
losses indicate that even more reserves may be necessary,'' he said.
   Singer said the discovery a few weeks ago of $500 million to $700
million in potential long-term claim exposure prompted one investor
interested in buying all three companies to back out and the
Insurance Division's decision to seek the receivership order.
   Synder said it was unclear what direction American Mutual will
take in 30 days. But he said, ``We, obviously, are not going to be
the size or shape of company that we were in the past. It all
depends on what we can bring out of this.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890117-0275 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 1931EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Earns-Computer 1stLd-Writethru   01-17 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Computer, 1st Ld-Writethru,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Apple Plans to Cut Some Prices; Earnings Up 16 Percent</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to CORRECT Loren's title, division president
sted president, and ADD quote; picks up 7th graf, ``Unit sales ....</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CUPERTINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Apple Computer Inc. announced plans to
cut prices on some of its Macintosh line on Tuesday and then saw its
stock drop sharply in heavy trading.
   The announcement coincided with the company releasing figures for
its first fiscal quarter that showed it had a 16 percent increase in
earnings compared to a year earlier.
   The stock fell $3.37{ a share, or 8 percent, to $40.62{ in the
over-the-counter market.
   Some analysts said the stock's sudden spill was unjustified.
   ``It's a highly nervous market and Apple is a highly visible
stock,'' said analyst Bruce Lupatkin of Hambrecht &amp; Quist.
   ``There's nothing wrong and Apple is stronger than ever,'' said
Tim Bajarin, an analyst with Creative Strategies, Inc., of Santa
Clara.
   Apple said it will decrease prices in its USA division on some
Macintosh personal computers, memory expansion kits and hard disk
drives.
   Allan Loren, the division president, said the company hoped the
price cuts on its more advanced models of Macintosh would bring more
customers to them.
   ``Unit sales increased over 30 percent in the United States and
at an even greater rate internationally,'' he said. ``But we also
experienced a shift in the unit mix toward less-costly,
less-configured Macintosh systems.''
   He said the company ``decided to selectively drop prices in the
U.S. to more fully expand momentum for the full range of our
Macintosh product line.''
   The company said net income for the quarter was $140.5 million,
16 percent above the $121.4 million earned in the same period a year
ago. Earnings per share for the quarter that ended Dec. 30 were
$1.10, up from the 92 cents per share.
   Net sales were $1.4 billion, a 35 percent increase over the
year-ago figure.
   International sales accounted for 32 percent of total revenues
during the quarter, compared to 28 percent in the first quarter of
fiscal 1988, according to a company statement.
   The company's profits rose 84 percent in the last fiscal year,
exceeding analysts' expectations.
   ``The numbers were essentially in line with expectations,''
Lupatkin said of Tuesday's report.
   Regarding the announcement of the price cut, Lupatkin said the
company could be ``repositioning existing products in anticipation
of a new product introduction.''
   ``I also think the price decline reflects the general slowing of
overall industry growth,'' the analyst added.
   The company pointed to its commitment to new products in
Tuesday's announcement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890117-0276 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-17-89 2115EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-IBMSued     01-17 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-IBM Sued,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-Employee Claims IBM Fired Him for Balking at South African Transfer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former International Business Machines Corp.
employee, who claims he was fired for refusing a transfer to South
Africa, has filed a $25 million lawsuit against the computer giant.
   Victor S. Khabo, a black naturalized U.S. citizen born in
Pretoria, South Africa, claimed he balked at the transfer to South
Africa because he still faces charges for his anti-apartheid
activities there.
   A former IBM marketing representative, Khabo sued the Armonk,
N.Y.-based company earlier this week at federal court in Manhattan,
accusing IBM of alleged unlawful employment practices.
   On Tuesday, however, an IBM spokeswoman disputed Khabo's claim.
   ``The termination was not related to South Africa. South Africa
was not an issue,'' said Theo Chisholm in a telephone interview.
   IBM announced plans to sell its South African holdings to
employees there in October 1986. Ms. Chisholm said that as of March
1987, IBM had no assets or employees in South Africa.
   She declined to say more, adding: ``We don't comment on cases
that are in litigation.''
   According to Khabo's lawsuit, he was hired by IBM in June 1984
and a year later, was asked to join South African students being
trained to work at IBM's division in South Africa.
   But Khabo, a New Brunswick, N.J., resident with masters degrees
in economics and business administration, claimed he told company
officials that he couldn't go back to his homeland unless the
political system there changed.
   In 1963, when he was 16, according to the lawsuit, Khabo was
twice arrested as a leader in the African Student Association. He
was released the first time but sentenced to 21 months hard labor
the second time.
   In 1975, according to court papers, Khabo _ who already was
living in the United States _ was named a co-conspirator in an
alleged 1963 plot to overthrow the South African government.
   Khabo claimed that after he refused the transfer to South Africa,
he was passed over for assignment to a sales territory and was
denied funds for courses to complete his doctorate, despite previous
company promises to do so.
   In addition to IBM, the lawsuit named four of Khabo's former
managers and IBM Chairman John F. Akers as co-defendants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
